meo-guide/ |archive-date=December 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He does not reveal why he wants the Child, but says he \"means more to me than you will ever know\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Dumaraog |first=Ana |title=The Mandalorian Theory: Moff Gideon Wants To Become The New Darth Vader |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=January 4, 2020 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-moff-gideon-new-darth-vader-darksaber-force-theory/ |accessdate=January 25, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124234658/https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-moff-gideon-new-darth-vader-darksaber-force-theory/ |archive-date=January 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter surviving an attack by Gideon's stormtroopers, during which the Child uses the Force to deflect the fire of an attacking stormtrooper's [[flamethrower]] back against him, the group escapes with the Child through a sewer grate. They seek help from the hidden Mandalorian tribe, but it is revealed the Imperials wiped out the tribe after they revealed themselves in \"Chapter 3: The Sin\".<ref name=\"Snowden1227\">{{cite news |last=Snowden |first=Scott |title='The Mandalorian' Finale is an Electrifying End to Season 1 |work=[[Space.com]] |date=December 27, 2019 |url=https://www.space.com/star-wars-the-mandalorian-episode-8-review.html |accessdate=January 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112033204/https://www.space.com/star-wars-the-mandalorian-episode-8-review.html |archive-date=January 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The tribe's leader, \"[[The Armorer (Star Wars)|The Armorer]]\" ([[Emily Swallow]]), instructs the Mandalorian to watch over and protect the Child,<ref name=\"Hough1230\">{{cite news |last=Hough |first=Q.V. |title=The Mandalorian: Who Plays The Armorer |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 30, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-armorer-actor-voice-emily-swallow/ |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191231185519/https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-armorer-actor-voice-emily-swallow/ |archive-date=December 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Kain1227\">{{cite news |last=Kain |first=Erik |title=Star Wars 'The Mandalorian' Episode 8 Recap And Review: A Terrific Season Finale |work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |date=December 27, 2019 |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/12/27/star-wars-the-mandalorian-episode-8-recap-and-review-a-terrific-season-finale/#3dd4bc9946b5 |accessdate=January 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229033605/https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/12/27/star-wars-the-mandalorian-episode-8-recap-and-review-a-terrific-season-finale/#3dd4bc9946b5 |archive-date=December 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Whalen1231\">{{cite news |last=Whalen |first=Andrew |title='The Mandalorian' Season 2: Release Date, Gamorreans and Everything Else We Know |work=[[Newsweek]] |date=December 31, 2019 |url=https://www.newsweek.com/mandalorian-season-2-release-date-plot-gamorreans-cast-director-episodes-1479892 |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115080619/https://www.newsweek.com/mandalorian-season-2-release-date-plot-gamorreans-cast-director-episodes-1479892 |archive-date=January 15, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> who she formally adopts into the Mandalorian culture as a \"foundling\", like the Mandalorian once was himself.<ref name=\"Kain1227\" /><ref name=\"Joest0108\">{{cite news |last=Joest |first=Mick |title=The Mandalorian Season 1: Episode 8 Ending Explained |work=CinemaBlend |date=January 8, 2020 |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2487822/the-mandalorian-season-1-episode-8-ending-explained |accessdate=February 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108211320/https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2487822/the-mandalorian-season-1-episode-8-ending-explained |archive-date=January 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> She instructs the Mandalorian to seek out and deliver the Child to the others of his kind, and that until this occurs, the Mandalorian and the Child are a \"clan of two\", and that the Mandalorian will be like a father to him.<ref name=\"Joest0108\" /><ref name=\"Ciacoya1229\">{{cite news |last=Ciacoya |first=Bea |title=The Mandalorian Changes Everything We Know About ... Mandalorians |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=December 29, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/mandalorian-tv-series-changes-mandalorians/ |accessdate=February 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230134650/https://www.cbr.com/mandalorian-tv-series-changes-mandalorians/ |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> She declares their \"signet\" to be a likeness of a Mudhorn, the creature the Mandalorian and the Child worked together to kill in \"Chapter 2: The Child\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Marshall |first=Rick |title=The Mandalorian: Easter eggs and episode 8's secrets explained |work=[[Digital Trends]] |date=December 27, 2019 |url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/movies/mandalorian-episode-8-recap-easter-eggs-secrets-explained/ |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101232302/https://www.digitaltrends.com/movies/mandalorian-episode-8-recap-easter-eggs-secrets-explained/ |archive-date=January 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The group departs, and IG-11 sacrifices himself to destroy an entire squad of stormtroopers to protect the Child.<ref name=\"Dumaraog1227\" /> After fending off a final attack from Moff Gideon, the Mandalorian once again departs from Nevarro with the Child.<ref name=\"Snowden1227\" />\n\n==Characterization==\nPhysically, the Child closely resembles Yoda, sharing his signature green skin and long, pointed ears.<ref>{{cite news |last=Crouse |first=Megan |title=Star Wars: The Mandalorian \u2013 Baby Yoda Explained |work=[[Den of Geek]] |date=December 27, 2019 |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-explained/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304033151/https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-explained/ |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Child is small in size, with wide eyes, [[Vellus hair|short hairs]], and wrinkled skin.<ref name=\"Kircher1205\" /><ref name=\"Bahr1231\" /> The Child is capable of sitting up, crawling, walking and eating. He appears capable of understanding some language spoken around him, but cannot speak except in baby-like babble noises.<ref name=\"Spitnagel\">{{Cite news |last=Spitnagel |first=Eric |title=An Alarmingly Deep Dive Into the Science of Baby Yoda |work=[[Popular Mechanics]] |date=December 2, 2019 |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/culture/tv/a30079354/baby-yoda/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304033202/https://www.popularmechanics.com/culture/tv/a30079354/baby-yoda/ |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Gina Carano feels the Child brings a warmth to a series that acts as a counterbalance to the Mandalorian himself, who otherwise acts aloof and unemotional. Carano believes in this way, the Child \"raises the emotional level and the stakes\" of the series.<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /> [[Anthony Breznican]] of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' echoed this sentiment: \"There is an emotional transference happening here. The audience cares more about the unnamed, faceless Mandalorian because he cares so much about Baby Yoda.\"<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /> Rebecca Keegan of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' believes the Child displays a form of wisdom despite his young age, describing him as \"a [[Dalai Lama]] in toddler form\".<ref name=\"Keegan1219\" /> [[Jeanne Cavelos]], former [[NASA]] [[Astrophysics|astrophysicist]] and author of ''[[The Science of Star Wars (book)|The Science of Star Wars]]'', also believes the Child demonstrates intelligence beyond his years, noting his awareness and empathy toward beings even when their faces or bodies are covered completely, as well as his ability to recognize injury in others and attempt to repair it.<ref name=\"Spitnagel\" />\n\nDespite his youth, the Child demonstrates a considerable ability to use and manipulate the Force, such as when he lifts the large Mudhorn creature into the air in \"Chapter 2: The Child\",<ref name=\"Keane1115\" /><ref name=\"Melrose1115\">{{cite news |last=Melrose |first=Kevin |title=The Mandalorian Confirms What We Suspected About 'the Asset' |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=November 15, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/star-wars-mandalorian-baby-yoda-force-powers/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222043716/https://www.cbr.com/star-wars-mandalorian-baby-yoda-force-powers/ |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and when he deflected the fire of an attacking stormtrooper's [[flamethrower]] back against him in \"Chapter 8: Redemption\".<ref name=\"Snowden1227\" /> Kevin Melrose of ''[[Comic Book Resources]]'' noted that in the [[Star Wars trilogy|original ''Star Wars'' trilogy]] film ''[[The Empire Strikes Back]]'' (1980), [[Luke Skywalker]] struggled to lift an [[X-wing fighter]] due to its large size, so the fact that the Child can lift heavy objects despite his diminutive size and young age demonstrates the vastness of his Force powers.<ref name=\"Melrose1115\" /> The Child also repeatedly shows a desire to use the Force to help those around him, such as when he attempts to heal the Mandalorian's wounds in \"Chapter 2: The Child\",<ref name=\"Keane1115\" /> and when he heals Greef Karga's near-fatal wounds in \"Chapter 7: The Reckoning\".<ref name=\"Hall1218\" /><ref name=\"Keane1219\" /> However, after using the Force in this manner, the Child is often exhausted and slips into unconsciousness,<ref name=\"Gallagher1213\">{{cite news |last=Gallagher |first=Caitlin |title=Baby Yoda's Force Power On 'The Mandalorian' Is Still Growing |work=[[Bustle (website)|Bustle]] |date=December 13, 2019 |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/baby-yodas-force-power-on-the-mandalorian-is-still-growing-19414772 |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217033917/https://www.bustle.com/p/baby-yodas-force-power-on-the-mandalorian-is-still-growing-19414772 |archive-date=February 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gallagher |first=Caitlin |title=Every Baby Yoda Moment From 'The Mandalorian' So You Know Where To Fast Forward To |work=[[Bustle (website)|Bustle]] |date=December 5, 2019 |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/every-baby-yoda-moment-from-the-mandalorian-so-you-know-where-to-fast-forward-to-19426794 |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304035923/https://www.bustle.com/p/every-baby-yoda-moment-from-the-mandalorian-so-you-know-where-to-fast-forward-to-19426794 |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Keane |first=Sean |title=The Mandalorian season finale recap: Baby Yoda gets into wild action in episode 8 |work=[[CNET]] |date=December 27, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-mandalorian-episode-8-season-finale-recap-redemption-baby-yoda-wild-action-moff-gideon-darksaber/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126202544/https://www.cnet.com/news/the-mandalorian-episode-8-season-finale-recap-redemption-baby-yoda-wild-action-moff-gideon-darksaber/ |archive-date=January 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> indicating that the Child is still developing his power and does not yet have the skills to fully control it. Despite his raw natural ability with the Force, the Child is untrained and still depends heavily on the assistance of the Mandalorian and other allies for protection.<ref name=\"Gallagher1213\" /> The Child has a sweet temperament,<ref name=\"Keegan1219\" /> and comes across as innocent and kindhearted to most of the people he encounters,<ref name=\"Gallagher1213\" />  but is also occasionally capable of violence, such as during a scene in \"Chapter 7: The Reckoning\" when he uses the Force to choke Cara Dune while she is engaging the Mandalorian in a friendly [[arm wrestling]] match.<ref name=\"Foy1221\" /><ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" /><ref name=\"Hibberd1218\" />\n\n==Concept and creation==\n===Conception===\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 320\n | image1 = Jon Favreau 2016.jpeg\n | image2 = DaveFiloni2016.jpg\n | footer = The Child was created by ''The Mandalorian'' creator and showrunner Jon Favreau (left), and the character was developed in early conversations between Favreau and executive producer Dave Filoni (right).\n}}\nThe Child was conceived by [[Jon Favreau]], the creator and [[showrunner]] of ''The Mandalorian''.<ref name=\"Giardina1205\"/> Upon learning that [[Lucasfilm]] had been sold to [[the Walt Disney Company]] in 2012, Favreau began imagining working on a ''Star Wars'' project, and was particularly interested in exploring the events after the original ''Star Wars'' trilogy.<ref name=\"Keegan1219\">{{cite news |last=Keegan |first=Rebecca |title=In Baby Yoda, Hollywood Sees Its Past, Present and Meme-able Future |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 19, 2019 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/baby-yoda-represents-past-present-future-hollywood-1263588 |accessdate=December 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230193122/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/baby-yoda-represents-past-present-future-hollywood-1263588 |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He conceived the Child based upon a desire to explore the mystery around Yoda and his species,<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" /> and an interest in presenting a character from Yoda's species at the beginning of his journey, in contrast to Yoda ending his own journey in ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'' (1983).<ref name=\"Keegan1219\" /> Favreau believed part of the appeal of Yoda was that George Lucas deliberately kept his origins and details about the species mysterious, and Favreau believed that sense of mystery would extend to the Child: \"I think that's why people are so curious about this little one of the same species.\"<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" /><ref name=\"Britt1205\">{{cite news |last=Britt |first=Ryan |title=''Mandalorian'' Showrunner Confirms Baby Yoda is Not Actually Yoda |work=[[Fatherly]] |date=December 5, 2019 |url=https://www.fatherly.com/news/mandalorian-showrunner-confirms-baby-yoda-is-not-actually-yoda/ |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191207062704/https://www.fatherly.com/news/mandalorian-showrunner-confirms-baby-yoda-is-not-actually-yoda/ |archive-date=December 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2017, shortly after Favreau pitched ''The Mandalorian'' to Lucasfilm President [[Kathleen Kennedy (producer)|Kathleen Kennedy]], she suggested he meet with [[Dave Filoni]], who had co-created several ''Star Wars'' animated series. The character of the Child was further developed in early conversations between Favreau and Filoni, the latter of whom drew a rough sketch of the character on cocktail napkins during the talks.<ref name=\"Keegan1219\" /> Multiple artists worked to refine the image of the Child created by Filoni, but the definitive imagery came from a concept drawing by artist Christian Alzmann, which depicted the character's makeshift garment.<ref name=\"Keegan1219\" /> Favreau said of this rendering: \"It looked cute, but it also looked a little weird. That's part of Yoda. It can't just be cute. It can't just be a straight-up Disney baby, it has to be a little bit tweaked.\"<ref name=\"Keegan1219\" /> The team sought to establish mannerisms and expressions for the Child that would remind viewers of a pet with whom they might share a connection. These characteristics include the Child's ears, posture, and the way he cocks his head.<ref name=\"Keegan1219\" />\n\nDisney [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] [[Bob Iger]] said of the Child: \"The moment I laid eyes on the character, I had a strong feeling that it was going to connect with audiences. So cute, so interesting, so compelling. So familiar and yet so new.\"<ref name=\"Keegan1219\" /> Favreau has clarified that the Child is not a younger version of Yoda himself,<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" /><ref name=\"Alexander0105\" /><ref name=\"Britt1205\" /> but has declined to comment upon whether he is related to Yoda or otherwise connected to him.<ref name=\"Alexander0105\" /> Both Iger and [[Carl Weathers]], the actor who portrays Greef Karga, have said the Child has a proper name that has not yet been revealed, and they have not disclosed it.<ref name=\"Cooper1223\" /><ref name=\"Gael1223\">{{cite news |last=Cooper |first=Gael Fashingbauer |title=Baby Yoda in The Mandalorian has a real name, Disney CEO says |work=[[CNET]] |date=December 23, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/baby-yoda-in-the-mandalorian-has-a-real-name-disney-ceo-says/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224164308/https://www.cnet.com/news/baby-yoda-in-the-mandalorian-has-a-real-name-disney-ceo-says/ |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Agar1118\">{{cite news |last=Agar |first=Chris |title=Star Wars: The Mandalorian's Baby Yoda Has A Proper Name (But It's A Secret) |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=November 18, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-real-name-secret/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128185636/https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-real-name-secret/ |archive-date=January 28, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Development===\nThe Child is mostly a work of [[animatronics]] and [[puppetry]], although accentuated with [[computer-generated imagery]] (CGI).<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" /> [[Legacy Effects]], the [[special effect]]s studio started by prot\u00e9g\u00e9s of [[Prosthetic makeup|special make-up effects]] creator [[Stan Winston]], designed the Child puppet and supplied the puppeteers to animate it during filming.<ref name=\"Miller1203\">{{cite news |last=Miller |first=Liz Shannon |title=Bryce Dallas Howard Screamed When She First Saw ''The Mandalorian''{{'}}s Baby Yoda |work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] |date=December 3, 2019 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-bryce-dallas-howard-sanctuary-baby-yoda.html |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117100201/https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-bryce-dallas-howard-sanctuary-baby-yoda.html |archive-date=January 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Miller1209\">{{cite news |last=Miller |first=Liz Shannon |title=Meet the Man Beneath the Mandalorian's Armor |work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] |date=December 9, 2019 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-double-brendan-wayne-interview.html |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113162948/https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-double-brendan-wayne-interview.html |archive-date=January 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The puppet cost about $5 million to make,<ref>{{cite news |last=Snierson |first=Dan |title=Adam Pally on his punchy ''Mandalorian'' scene: 'Baby Yoda is a bit of a diva' |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=January 11, 2020 |url=https://ew.com/tv/2020/01/11/adam-pally-on-punching-baby-yoda-mandalorian/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112125752/https://ew.com/tv/2020/01/11/adam-pally-on-punching-baby-yoda-mandalorian/ |archive-date=January 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and is relatively heavy due to the amount of wires and animatronic technology inside it.<ref name=\"Rosas5440\">{{harvnb|Rosas|Ballance|2020|loc=54:40\u201355:01 Ballance: \"So, the Baby Yoda, you've held him. He's heavy?\" Rosas: \"Yes and no. I mean, he's heavy when I'm in my costume and holding him too, so it's more weight and lots of wires everywhere between the two of us. Yeah, he's got weight to him. He just melts my heart, he's so cute.\"}}</ref> It is controlled by two technicians, one who operates the eyes and mouth and another who controls other facial expressions.<ref name=\"Spencer1202\">{{cite news |last=Spencer |first=Samuel |title=''The Mandalorian'' crew on how they made 'Baby Yoda' |work=[[Newsweek]] |date=December 2, 2019 |url=https://www.newsweek.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-child-puppet-cgi-disney-plus-werner-herzog-1474991 |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208002313/https://www.newsweek.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-child-puppet-cgi-disney-plus-werner-herzog-1474991 |archive-date=December 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Paiella1118\">{{cite news |last=Paiella |first=Gabriella |title=Werner Herzog Was Brought to Tears by Baby Yoda |work=[[GQ]] |date=November 18, 2019 |url=https://www.gq.com/story/werner-herzog-baby-yoda |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127044727/https://www.gq.com/story/werner-herzog-baby-yoda |archive-date=January 27, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> There are several stand-in versions for the Child used in filming in addition to the primary puppet.<ref name=\"Bonomolo0221\">{{cite news |last=Bonomolo |first=Cameron |title=Star Wars: The Mandalorian's Giancarlo Esposito Teases Scenes With Baby Yoda in Season 2 |work=Comicbook.com |date=February 21, 2020 |url=https://comicbook.com/starwars/2020/02/22/star-wars-the-mandalorian-season-2-baby-yoda-moff-gideon-giancarlo-esposito/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222172758/https://comicbook.com/starwars/2020/02/22/star-wars-the-mandalorian-season-2-baby-yoda-moff-gideon-giancarlo-esposito/ |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The crew of ''The Mandalorian'' wanted to use animatronics for the Child as often as possible.<ref name=\"Couch1115\">{{cite news |last=Couch |first=Aaron |title=The 'Mandalorian' Moment That Caused Werner Herzog to Call His Bosses \"Cowards\" |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=November 15, 2019 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mandalorian-why-werner-herzog-called-jon-favreau-a-coward-1254941 |accessdate=January 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123003024/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mandalorian-why-werner-herzog-called-jon-favreau-a-coward-1254941 |archive-date=November 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, they also shot versions of the character's scenes both with and without the puppet, so they had the option of replacing it with a CGI effect in post-production if the puppet did not look satisfactory.<ref name=\"Couch1115\" /><ref name=\"Husband1126\">{{cite news |last=Husband |first=Andrew |title=When 'The Mandalorian' Considered Replacing Baby Yoda's Puppet With CGI, Werner Herzog Rebuked Them |work=[[Uproxx]] |date=November 26, 2019 |url=https://uproxx.com/tv/werner-herzog-baby-yoda-cowards/ |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127044708/https://uproxx.com/tv/werner-herzog-baby-yoda-cowards/ |archive-date=January 27, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> When CGI is used, Favreau said they try to make the character obey the same physical laws that he would if he were a puppet, adding: \"I think a lot of times CG makes itself too obvious where you don't create parameters creatively that allow the character to keep the same identity and charm.\"<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" />\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 320\n | image1 = Matthew Wood.JPG\n | image2 = David Acord Animate Florida 2016.jpg\n | footer = The voice and sounds of the Child were created by sound editors Matthew Wood (left) and David Acord (right).\n}}\nThe voice and sounds of the Child were created by [[David Acord]] and [[Matthew Wood (sound editor)|Matthew Wood]], sound editors with [[Skywalker Sound]], who had previously worked on various ''Star Wars'' projects. Acord recorded animals' noises at a wildlife rescue near [[San Diego]],<ref name=\"Giardina0129\">{{cite news |last=Giardina |first=Carolyn |title='Star Wars' Sound Editors on Using Elephant Screams for Battles and Creating Baby Yoda's Voice |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 29, 2020 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/behind-screen/star-wars-sound-editors-using-elephant-screams-battles-creating-baby-yodas-voice-1273986 |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221221123/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/behind-screen/star-wars-sound-editors-using-elephant-screams-battles-creating-baby-yodas-voice-1273986 |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and used recordings of a [[bat-eared fox]] and [[kinkajou]] to make the initial version of the Child's voice.<ref name=\"Cooper1223\" /><ref name=\"Giardina0129\" /><ref name=\"Burton1209\">{{cite news |last=Burton |first=Bonnie |title=Baby Yoda's cute voice created by kinkajous and big-eared foxes |work=[[CNET]] |date=December 9, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-cute-voice-created-by-foxes-kinkajous/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224173322/https://www.cnet.com/news/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-cute-voice-created-by-foxes-kinkajous/ |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, Favreau suggested the voice needed to sound more human-like and relatable to audiences, so instead the animal sounds were scaled back and used only for small grunts and cooing noises. Actual infant vocals were used to create the new version of the Child's voice, and Acord used a highly-[[Pitch (music)|pitched]] version of his own voice for some of the more articulated vocalizations.<ref name=\"Giardina0129\" /> Acord also previously voiced [[List of Star Wars characters#Rotta the Hutt|Rotta the Hutt]], the young [[Hutt (Star Wars)|Huttlet]] son of [[Jabba the Hutt]], in the animated film ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' (2008).<ref name=\"Burton1209\" />\n\n===Filming===\nThe character was referred to as \"The Child\" in screenplays for ''The Mandalorian'', though [[Bryce Dallas Howard]], who directed \"[[Chapter 4: Sanctuary]]\", said she always referred to him on set simply as \"Baby\",<ref name=\"Miller1203\" /> and other cast members called it \"The Being\".<ref name=\"Breznican1112\" /> During filming, the director of each episode would communicate with the Child's puppeteers to discuss what was happening in the scene, what emotions the Child should express, and what actions the character should take.<ref name=\"Spencer1202\" /><ref name=\"Breznican1126\">{{cite news |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |title=Baby Yoda Has Conquered the World |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=November 26, 2019 |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/the-mandalorian-star-wars-baby-yoda |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127163301/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/the-mandalorian-star-wars-baby-yoda |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Director [[Deborah Chow]] said in this way, it was similar to providing direction to a living actor.<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /><ref name=\"Breznican1122\">{{cite news |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |author-link=Anthony Breznican |title=''The Mandalorian'': Deborah Chow Reveals the Inspiration For the Baby Yoda Rescue |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=November 22, 2019 |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/deborah-chow-director-episode-three-the-mandalorian |access-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref> Favreau encouraged the editors to test and push the boundaries of the Child puppet during filming, urging them to experiment and attempt to get the most realistic movements and mannerisms possible from the character.<ref name=\"Miller1203\" /> Brendan Wayne, a body double for the Mandalorian character, said the puppet looked so realistic that performing against it felt like working with an actual [[child actor]].<ref name=\"Miller1209\" /> [[Rick Famuyiwa]], the director of \"Chapter 2: The Child\", said he was shocked when he learned that the premiere episode of ''The Mandalorian'' ended with the introduction of the Child, because it meant he would be directing the next episode that further expanded upon the character.<ref name=\"Couch1115\" />\n\nThe Child puppet was extremely popular among the cast and crew on the set of ''The Mandalorian''.<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /><ref name=\"Itzkoff1122\">{{cite news |last=Itzkoff |first=Dave |author-link=Dave Itzkoff |title='The Mandalorian' Director: Baby Yoda 'Steals the Show' |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 22, 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/22/arts/television/the-mandalorian-star-wars-baby-yoda.html |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127044719/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/22/arts/television/the-mandalorian-star-wars-baby-yoda.html |archive-date=January 27, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Chow said: \"With the baby, every time it came on set, the whole crew would respond to it. Even the grip department, every production assistant is coming to the monitors, trying to see it.\"<ref name=\"Itzkoff1122\" /> Howard screamed in excitement when she first saw it,<ref name=\"Miller1203\" /> and Gina Carano said of the Child: \"That was our precious. Our precious is this being that we all end up taking care of in some way.\"<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /> Emily Swallow said she \"fell in love with it like everybody else\",<ref>{{cite news |last=Silliman |first=Brian |title=The Mandalorian's Emily Swallow on the Armorer's secrets and the Baby Yoda puppet |work=[[Syfy|Syfy Wire]] |date=November 27, 2019 |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/the-mandalorians-emily-swallow-on-the-armorers-secrets-and-the-baby-yoda-puppet |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224092134/https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/the-mandalorians-emily-swallow-on-the-armorers-secrets-and-the-baby-yoda-puppet |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Swallow|Silliman|Busch|2019|loc=21:01\u201321:12 Busch: \"Did you ever get to see or meet the Yoda baby puppet, even just behind the scenes?\" Sparrow: \"Oh I did, yeah, and I fell in love with it like everybody else. And it does look so real. It's so deceptive.\"}}</ref> adding: \"I was thrilled when they brought him in that little bag for the scene that I got to have with it. I just wanted to snuggle it.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Cavanaugh |first=Patrick |title=Star Wars: The Mandalorian's Emily Swallow Wanted to Snuggle Baby Yoda |work=Comicbook.com |date=January 14, 2020 |url=https://comicbook.com/starwars/2020/01/14/star-wars-the-mandalorian-emily-swallow-baby-yoda-reaction/ |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115171534/https://comicbook.com/starwars/2020/01/14/star-wars-the-mandalorian-emily-swallow-baby-yoda-reaction/ |archive-date=January 15, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Swallow|2020|loc=8:25\u20138:33 Swallow: \"I was thrilled when they brought him in that little bag for the scene that I got to have with it. I just wanted to snuggle it.\"}}</ref> Amy Sedaris said the animatronic Child puppet made everyone on the set happy: \"The minute you looked into Baby Yoda's eyes you just got lost.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Gaindo |first=Brian |title=We Asked Amy Sedaris About Baby Yoda Because How Could We Not |work=[[Buzzfeed]] |date=December 13, 2019 |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/briangalindo/we-talked-to-amy-sedaris-about-baby-yoda-and-the-holidays |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219035547/https://www.buzzfeed.com/briangalindo/we-talked-to-amy-sedaris-about-baby-yoda-and-the-holidays |archive-date=February 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Likewise, Giancarlo Esposito said he enjoyed interacting with the Child puppet during filming: \"It melts my heart, because the reality is, this little baby does things that you could never imagine and when you look at those eyes and that little body, how can you not help but fall in love?\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Lash |first=Jolie |title=The Mandalorian Season 2: Giancarlo Esposito Offers Clue on Why Moff Gideon Wants Baby Yoda |work=[[IGN]] |date=January 17, 2020 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/the-mandalorian-season-2-moff-gideon-baby-yoda-darksaber |accessdate=January 24, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200121054150/https://www.ign.com/articles/the-mandalorian-season-2-moff-gideon-baby-yoda-darksaber |archive-date=January 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Carl Weathers has said of him: \"He is very interesting and very knowledgeable and very cute. I never use that word, but he is a cute little guy.\"<ref name=\"Agar1118\" /><ref>{{cite news |title='Mandalorian' creator Favreau teases more 'Star Wars' surprises |work=[[Reuters]] |date=November 14, 2019 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-television-starwars-mandalorian-idUSKBN1XO184 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209213006/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-television-starwars-mandalorian-idUSKBN1XO184 |archive-date=February 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Werner Herzog Berlin 2015.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=A man with thinning great hair wearing a green shirt looks off-camera.|Werner Herzog, who portrays The Client in ''The Mandalorian'', strongly urged the show's producers to remain committed to the animatronics and puppetry for the Child, calling them \"cowards\" for considering using computer-generated imagery.]]\nWerner Herzog particularly enjoyed filming scenes with the animatronic Child puppet, which he called \"heartbreakingly beautiful\".<ref name=\"Paiella1118\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Kiefer |first=Halle |title=Werner Herzog Says He Cried When He Saw Baby Yoda on the ''Mandalorian'' Set |work=Vulture |date=November 17, 2019 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/11/werner-herzog-on-baby-yoda-in-star-wars-the-mandalorian.html |accessdate=January 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217155624/https://www.vulture.com/2019/11/werner-herzog-on-baby-yoda-in-star-wars-the-mandalorian.html |archive-date=December 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lavin |first=Will |title=Werner Herzog called out 'Mandalorian' crew for almost replacing Baby Yoda puppet with CGI: \"You are cowards\" |work=[[NME]] |date=November 27, 2019 |url=https://www.nme.com/news/tv/werner-herzog-mandalorian-baby-yoda-puppet-cgi-you-are-cowards-2579577 |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129021143/https://www.nme.com/news/tv/werner-herzog-mandalorian-baby-yoda-puppet-cgi-you-are-cowards-2579577 |archive-date=November 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Chow said directing the scene between Herzog and the Child in \"Chapter 3: The Sin\" was \"one of the weirdest\" moments of her career,<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /><ref name=\"Itzkoff1122\" /><ref name=\"Lawler1125\">{{cite news |last=Lawler |first=Kelly |title='The Mandalorian': Star Werner Herzog is more obsessed with Baby Yoda than you are |work=[[USA Today]] |date=November 25, 2019 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2019/11/25/the-mandalorian-star-werner-herzog-obsessed-baby-yoda/4296133002/ |accessdate=January 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191216210215/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2019/11/25/the-mandalorian-star-werner-herzog-obsessed-baby-yoda/4296133002/ |archive-date=December 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> because he had so much affection for the puppet and was interacting with it like it was a living being.<ref name=\"Itzkoff1122\" /><ref name=\"Lawler1125\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Oller |first=Jacob |title=The Mandalorian's Werner Herzog fell 'in love' with Baby Yoda, forgot it wasn't real during shoot |work=[[Syfy]] |date=November 25, 2019 |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/baby-yoda-werner-herzog-the-mandalorian |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128073441/https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/baby-yoda-werner-herzog-the-mandalorian |archive-date=November 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> She said: \"I literally think that he had forgotten that it's not a real-live creature and he had fallen in love with it.\"<ref name=\"Lawler1125\" /> Herzog strongly urged the ''Mandalorian'' filmmakers to use the puppet for the character and not CGI. While filming one scene, Dave Filoni began to remove the puppet to shoot an alternate take, in case they decided to use a CGI version of the Child in its place. Herzog passionately urged him not to do so and to remain committed to the animatronics and puppetry, saying: \"You are cowards. Leave it. Leave it.\"<ref name=\"Couch1115\" /><ref name=\"Husband1126\" /> Esposito has also said having an actual Child puppet to perform against has been beneficial for the cast, because \"that space allows all of us to be so wowed by its presence\".<ref name=\"Bonomolo0221\" />\n\nMisty Rosas, who delivered the motion capture performance for Kuiil, often held the Child puppet during her scenes in \"Chapter 7: The Reckoning\". This occasionally proved challenging for Rosas, who also had to manage the weight of the animatronics in her own costume and face mask, as well as the weight of the Child prop.<ref name=\"Rosas5440\" /> One full day of filming the episode focused upon Kuiil riding the [[blurrg]] creature, a process Rosas described as \"intense\" due to the amount of time she spent on the fake creature and the speeds at which it was made to run. The process was made further challenging because she was carrying the heavy animatronic Child puppet throughout the scenes, and she occasionally needed breaks between takes. Rosas said: \"My legs are not exactly long, so I was squeezing for dear life and holding the baby.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Rosas|Ballance|2020|loc=53:41\u201354:29 Rosas: \"It was Deb's episode, which was very intense. So there was a day and it was just me, on this set with this unit on the blurrg all day long, and it was a lot of running hard like that. And, I mean, my legs are not exactly long, so I was squeezing for dear life and holding the baby. And the animatronic baby is heavy, so this arm, and then holding the reins, I was like, 'Oh my god,' like at the end of every scene I would hold on to it and lean back and say, 'Give me a second, I need to catch my breath.'\"}}</ref> Nevertheless, Rosas said she enjoyed working with the Child character, saying: \"He just melts my heart, he's so cute.\"<ref name=\"Rosas5440\" />\n\nDuring the opening scene of \"Chapter 8: Redemption\", an Imperial Scout Trooper portrayed by comedian [[Adam Pally]] punched the Child. During the first take of filming the scene, Pally punched the animatronic Child puppet hard, prompting Favreau to inform the actor that the puppet costs about $5 million to make. This made Pally so nervous that he missed the Child altogether when he tried to punch him in the three subsequent takes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Corrigan |first=Hope |title=The Mandalorian's Baby Yoda Puppet Cost $5 Million |work=[[IGN]] |date=January 15, 2020 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/the-mandalorians-baby-yoda-puppet-cost-5-million |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114231448/https://www.ign.com/articles/the-mandalorians-baby-yoda-puppet-cost-5-million |archive-date=January 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hart |first=Matthew |title=Baby Yoda Puppet from The Mandalorian Cost $5 Million |work=[[Nerdist Industries|Nerdist]] |date=January 13, 2020 |url=https://nerdist.com/article/mandalorian-baby-yoda-puppet-cost/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114175342/https://nerdist.com/article/mandalorian-baby-yoda-puppet-cost/ |archive-date=January 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pearce |first=Tilly |title=Baby Yoda cost The Mandalorian a staggering $5million (but it was totally worth it) |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=January 12, 2020 |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/01/12/baby-yoda-cost-mandalorian-staggering-5million-totally-worth-12044065/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116090534/https://metro.co.uk/2020/01/12/baby-yoda-cost-mandalorian-staggering-5million-totally-worth-12044065/ |archive-date=January 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Pally joked about working with the Child: \"I gotta tell you, the truth is that Baby Yoda is a bit of a diva. He's constantly [[Electronic cigarette|vaping]].\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Keane |first=Sean |title=Baby Yoda puppet apparently cost around $5 million |work=[[CNET]] |date=January 14, 2020 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/baby-yoda-puppet-apparently-cost-around-5-million/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115172955/https://www.cnet.com/news/baby-yoda-puppet-apparently-cost-around-5-million/ |archive-date=January 15, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Muncy |first=Julie |title=Adam Pally Tells All About the Day He Punched Baby Yoda |work=[[Gizmodo]] |date=January 12, 2020 |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/adam-pally-tells-all-about-the-day-he-punched-baby-yoda-1840958370 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113232853/https://io9.gizmodo.com/adam-pally-tells-all-about-the-day-he-punched-baby-yoda-1840958370 |archive-date=January 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fuster |first=Jeremy |title='The Mandalorian': Meet the Actor Who Punched the $5 Million Baby Yoda |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=January 12, 2020 |url=https://www.thewrap.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-punch-adam-pally/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113130023/https://www.thewrap.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-punch-adam-pally/ |archive-date=January 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> At some point during filming of ''The Mandalorian'', George Lucas visited the set and held the Child puppet. Favreau posted a picture of Lucas holding the Child on [[Instagram]] on January 16, 2020, which drew considerable [[Internet]] attention.<ref name=\"Carras0117\">{{cite news |last=Carras |first=Christi |title=Jon Favreau shares photo of George Lucas cradling Baby Yoda. No caption needed |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=January 17, 2020 |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/tv/story/2020-01-17/george-lucas-baby-yoda-photo-jon-favreau |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224041822/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/tv/story/2020-01-17/george-lucas-baby-yoda-photo-jon-favreau |archive-date=February 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ankers |first=Adele |title=George Lucas Meets Baby Yoda in Adorable Mandalorian Set Photo |work=[[IGN]] |date=January 17, 2020 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/george-lucas-meets-baby-yoda-in-adorable-mandalorian-set-photo |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215070248/https://www.ign.com/articles/george-lucas-meets-baby-yoda-in-adorable-mandalorian-set-photo |archive-date=February 15, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Langmann |first=Brady |title=George Lucas Cradling Baby Yoda is This Year's Greatest Parenting Moment |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=January 17, 2020 |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/a30563402/best-baby-yoda-george-lucas-social-media-reactions/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213001408/https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/a30563402/best-baby-yoda-george-lucas-social-media-reactions/ |archive-date=February 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Prerelease===\n[[Image:Donald Glover TIFF 2015.jpg|thumb|upright|Jon Favreau has credited actor Donald Glover (pictured) with inspiring the decision to keep the Child's revelation a secret.]]\nThe Child was kept secret and was deliberately withheld from ''The Mandalorian''{{'s}} prerelease marketing and merchandise plans due to the risk that details about the character could leak before the show aired.<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" /><ref name=\"Keegan1219\" /><ref name=\"DelBarco1205\">{{cite news |last=del Barco |first=Mandalit |author-link=Mandalit del Barco |title=You'll Have to Wait for Official Baby Yoda Toys |work=[[NPR]] |date=December 5, 2019 |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/05/784994963/youll-have-to-wait-for-official-baby-yoda-toys |accessdate=December 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191212111404/https://www.npr.org/2019/12/05/784994963/youll-have-to-wait-for-official-baby-yoda-toys |archive-date=December 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Agar |first=Chris |title=The Mandalorian Hiding Baby Yoda For So Long Was A Marketing Mistake |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=November 20, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-star-wars-baby-yoda-marketing-mistake-bad/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110195312/https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-star-wars-baby-yoda-marketing-mistake-bad/ |archive-date=January 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Favreau said of this plan: \"I think that part of what people really value is to be surprised and delighted, and I think that's becoming all too rare.\"<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" /> Favreau has credited [[Donald Glover]] as the source of that strategy. While developing ''The Mandalorian'', Favreau was simultaneously directing Glover in the photorealistic remake of ''[[The Lion King (2019 film)|The Lion King]]'' (2019). While discussing music and pop culture, Glover told Favreau that people enjoy being surprised, because true surprises had become much less common in the Internet era. As an example, Glover cited the excitement generated by the sudden releases of surprise albums by singer and songwriter [[Beyonc\u00e9]].<ref name=\"Keegan1219\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Bonomolo |first=Cameron |title=Star Wars: The Mandalorian Fans Can Blame Donald Glover for Lack of Baby Yoda Merch |work=Comicbook.com |date=December 21, 2019 |url=https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/12/22/star-wars-baby-yoda-merchandise-the-mandalorian-jon-favreau-donald-glover-idea/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204193756/https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/12/22/star-wars-baby-yoda-merchandise-the-mandalorian-jon-favreau-donald-glover-idea/ |archive-date=February 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Favreau felt keeping the Child a secret until he was revealed would allow fans to connect with the character and \"discover the story as it was unfolding\".<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" /> The leadership and marketing team at the Walt Disney Company was supportive of this strategy.<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" /> Screeners of the pilot episode were not distributed to reviewers to avoid leaks about the Child,<ref name=\"Tassi1119\">{{cite news |last=Tassi |first=Paul |title=Even Disney Is Talking About That Secret 'Mandalorian' Character Now So I Give Up |work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |date=November 19, 2019 |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paultassi/2019/11/19/even-disney-is-talking-about-that-secret-mandalorian-character-now-so-i-give-up/#52cff86c2818 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121123314/https://www.forbes.com/sites/paultassi/2019/11/19/even-disney-is-talking-about-that-secret-mandalorian-character-now-so-i-give-up/#52cff86c2818 |archive-date=November 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the official Lucasfilm and ''Star Wars'' social media accounts did not start posting messages about the Child until about a week after the series debuted, to avoid spoiling the character's debut as much as possible.<ref name=\"Tassi1119\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Schaefer |first=Sandy |title=Star Wars Officially Spoils The Mandalorian's Baby Yoda Twist |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=November 18, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-baby-yoda-spoiler/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222171029/https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-baby-yoda-spoiler/ |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Kuchera1118\">{{cite news |last=Kuchera |first=Ben |title=Disney made it official: We can talk about that Mandalorian character now |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=November 18, 2019 |url=https://www.polygon.com/star-wars/2019/11/18/20970783/star-wars-mandalorian-spoilers-baby-yoda-disney-plus-spoiler-culture |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222035443/https://www.polygon.com/star-wars/2019/11/18/20970783/star-wars-mandalorian-spoilers-baby-yoda-disney-plus-spoiler-culture |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\n===Parenting and fatherhood===\nOne of the primary themes of ''The Mandalorian'' is [[parenting]] and [[Father|fatherhood]], particularly through the father-son relationship dynamic between the Mandalorian and the Child.<ref name=\"Britt1129\">{{cite news |last=Britt |first=Ryan |title=Baby Yoda, Daddy Mando, and How Star Wars Gave Parents a New Fantasy |work=[[Fatherly]] |date=November 29, 2019 |url=https://www.fatherly.com/play/baby-yoda-star-wars-the-mandalorian-adults/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218213005/https://www.fatherly.com/play/baby-yoda-star-wars-the-mandalorian-adults/ |archive-date=December 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Singer1213\">{{cite news |last=Singer |first=Matt |title='The Mandalorian' Is A Good Show About How Hard It Is to Be a Single Parent |work=[[ScreenCrush]] |date=December 13, 2019 |url=https://screencrush.com/the-mandalorian-episode-6-recap-single-dad/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229155055/https://screencrush.com/the-mandalorian-episode-6-recap-single-dad/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Chase1216\">{{cite news |last=Chase |first=Eileen |title=Why The Mandalorian is, in fact, a show about a single dad |work=[[Today (American TV program)|Today]] |date=December 16, 2019 |url=https://community.today.com/parentingteam/post/why-the-mandalorian-is-in-fact-a-show-about-a-single-dad |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229160800/https://community.today.com/parentingteam/post/why-the-mandalorian-is-in-fact-a-show-about-a-single-dad |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Ryan Britt of ''[[Fatherly]]'' wrote: \"For years the ''Star Wars'' franchise avoided depicting a parent-child dynamic. With Mando and Baby Yoda, that\u2019s finally changing.\"<ref name=\"Britt1129\"/> ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]'' writer Kathryn VanArendonk argued that parenting has been the subject of past ''Star Wars'' stories, but almost always during later stages of parenthood, rather than an infant in early developmental stages such as the Child. As examples, she cited [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]] serving as a mentor to the adolescent Anakin Skywalker, [[Princess Leia]] lamenting over her grown son [[Kylo Ren]], or the absence of [[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]]'s parents.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\">{{cite news |last=VanArendonk |first=Kathryn |title=''The Mandalorian'' Doesn't Care About Diapers |work=[[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] |date=January 3, 2020 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/the-mandalorian-parenting-fatherhood-archetype.html |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107030832/https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/the-mandalorian-parenting-fatherhood-archetype.html |archive-date=January 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Several reviewers have compared the dynamic between the Child and the Mandalorian to ''[[Lone Wolf and Cub]]'', a [[manga]] about a [[samurai]] warrior and his young son.<ref>{{cite news |last=Collins |first=Hannah |title=Somali and the Forest Spirit Will Fill The Mandalorian Hole in Your Life |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=January 4, 2020 |url=https://www.cbr.com/somali-and-the-forest-spirit-the-mandalorian-comparison/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227221535/https://www.cbr.com/somali-and-the-forest-spirit-the-mandalorian-comparison/ |archive-date=February 27, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pierce-Bohen |title=5 Westerns & 5 Samurai Movies To Watch If You Love The Mandalorian |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 23, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-westerns-samurai-movies-similar/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216014331/https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-westerns-samurai-movies-similar/ |archive-date=February 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Schedeen |first=Jesse |title=How The Mandalorian's Plot Twist Evokes a Classic Manga Series |work=[[IGN]] |date=November 12, 2019 |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/11/12/the-mandalorian-plot-twist-lone-wolf-and-cub |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191124001555/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/11/12/the-mandalorian-plot-twist-lone-wolf-and-cub |archive-date=November 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Housman |first=Andrew |title=The Mandalorian: How the Series Takes Star Wars Back to Its Samurai Roots |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=November 20, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-lone-wolf-and-cub-influence/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204173214/https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-lone-wolf-and-cub-influence/ |archive-date=December 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Child makes the Mandalorian a softer and more relatable character;<ref name=\"Frank1203\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Lawler |first=Kelly |title=Baby Yoda is the adorable, big-eared savior of Disney+'s 'The Mandalorian' |work=[[USA Today]] |date=November 22, 2019 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2019/11/22/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-ode-disney-plus-star-wars/4240481002/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223122908/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2019/11/22/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-ode-disney-plus-star-wars/4240481002/ |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> he changes in a positive way because of raising the Child, becoming less selfish and self-absorbed.<ref name=\"Pereira1129\" /> Several examples of the Mandalorian parenting the Child appear throughout the series, such as when he stops the Child from pressing random buttons in the cockput of the Mandalorian's spaceship, ultimately by holding him in his lap.<ref name=\"Britt1129\" /> In another example, the Mandalorian sets up a [[car seat]] for the Child in the cockpit of his ship, so he can be seated safely and comfortably during their travels.<ref name=\"Atkin1230\">{{cite news |last=Atkin |first=Jessie |title=5 Reasons The Witcher Geralt Will Be a Better Dad Than the Mandalorian (& 5 Reasons He Won't) |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 30, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/5-reasons-the-witcher-geralt-will-be-a-better-dad-than-the-mandalorian-5-reasons-he-wont/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220043947/https://screenrant.com/5-reasons-the-witcher-geralt-will-be-a-better-dad-than-the-mandalorian-5-reasons-he-wont/ |archive-date=February 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe relationship between the Mandalorian and the Child is an example of unexpected fatherhood.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /><ref name=\"Pereira1129\">{{cite news |last=Pereira |first=Sergio |title=The Mandalorian Is Basically Big Daddy in Space |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=November 29, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-big-daddy-in-space/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229214420/https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-big-daddy-in-space/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mandalorian feels a connection and parental bond with the Child because of his own childhood, when he was orphaned upon the death of his parents and was adopted by the Mandalorian culture as a \"foundling\".<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> Nevertheless, fatherhood was not a role the Mandalorian was initially seeking, and he makes repeated initial attempts to avoid this responsibility.<ref name=\"Pereira1129\" /> He first does so in \"Chapter 3: The Sin\", when he leaves the Child with the Client,<ref name=\"Pereira1129\" /> and then again in \"Chapter 4\" Sanctuary\", when he plans to leave the Child with Omera, a protective mother on the planet Sorgan who is willing to take the Child into her own family.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> The Mandalorian does not fully commit to the role of fatherhood until the first season finale, \"Chapter 8: Redemption\", when the Child himself is also adopted into the Mandalorian culture as a \"foundling\" and the Mandalorian is formally declared to be his father figure.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" />\n\nAnthony Breznican of ''Vanity Fair'' has noted that none of the day-to-day difficulties of parenthood are portrayed in the series: \"There is no shrill squawking from Baby Yoda, no tantrum, no spit-up, no uncontrollable shrieking that burrows into a parent\u2019s psyche like a dentist\u2019s drill shredding a soft, pink nerve.\"<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /> Likewise, ''Vulture'' writer Kathryn VanArendonk said the show ignores or does not address many parenting details that make fatherhood difficult, such as what the Child eats, when he goes him to sleep, and whether he wears diapers. She wrote: \"''The Mandalorian'' is uninterested in diapers, and so Mando gets to be a very particular image of fatherhood: the guy who doesn't have to sweat the small stuff.\"<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> VanAnderonk described this as a [[wish fulfillment]] fantasy for parents or prospective parents: \"a vision of parenting stripped so thoroughly of all detail and specificity that all that\u2019s left are archetypes: the parent, the child\".<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" />\n\nThe Child encounters a handful of other protector figures throughout the first season, including Omera, IG-11, and Peli Motto.<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> Some observers have criticized the series for the fact that the Mandalorian repeatedly leaves the Child alone or in the hands of relative strangers,<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /> as well as for making decisions that place the Child in danger. One example is in \"Chapter 6: The Prisoner\", when he allows a team of dangerous mercenaries to use his ship while the Child is on board, nearly resulting in the Child's death.<ref name=\"Singer1213\" /><ref name=\"White1218\">{{cite news |last=White |first=Brett |title=Is Baby Yoda Bad to the Bone? This Week's 'The Mandalorian' Has Us Wondering |work=[[New York Post|Decider]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://decider.com/2019/12/18/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-evil/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108031652/https://decider.com/2019/12/18/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-evil/ |archive-date=January 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> An interaction the Mandalorian has with Peli Motto in \"Chapter 5: The Gunslinger\" is one of the most overt discussions about the challenges of caring for the Child. When the Mandalorian accidentally wakes the child, who had been sleeping in Peli's arms, she chides him: \"Do you have any idea how long it took me to get it to sleep?\"<ref name=\"VanArendonk0103\" /> She also condemns the Mandalorian for leaving the child alone on the ship, saying: \"you have an awful lot to learn about raising a young one\".<ref name=\"Keane1207\" /> ''[[ScreenCrush]]'' writer Matt Singer argued the Mandalorian's parenting errors makes the show that much more appealing and relatable because making mistakes is a large part of being a parent.<ref name=\"Singer1213\" />\n\n===Good and evil; nature versus nurture===\nOne scene in \"Chapter 7: The Reckoning\" led many fans to reevaluate the Child and question whether he may demonstrate evil tendencies. During a scene on the Mandalorian's spaceship, the Child observes as the Mandalorian and Cara Dune engage in a friendly [[arm wrestling]] match. During the contest, the Child uses the Force to choke Cara, nearly strangling her before the Mandalorian intervenes.<ref name=\"Foy1221\">{{cite news |last=Foy |first=Peter |title=The Mandalorian: Could Baby Yoda Actually Be... [Spoiler]? |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=December 21, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-actually-evil/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114120025/https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-actually-evil/ |archive-date=January 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Gallagher1226\">{{cite news |last=Gallagher |first=Caitlin |title=Is Baby Yoda Evil On 'The Mandalorian'? The Force Choke Means He Could Join The Dark Side |work=[[Bustle (website)|Bustle]] |date=December 26, 2019 |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/is-baby-yoda-evil-on-the-mandalorian-the-force-choke-means-he-could-join-the-dark-side-19629941 |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301160308/https://www.bustle.com/p/is-baby-yoda-evil-on-the-mandalorian-the-force-choke-means-he-could-join-the-dark-side-19629941 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Hibberd1218\" /> Throughout the ''Star Wars'' franchise, that ability has been most commonly associated with the [[dark side of the Force]], and particularly with the antagonist character [[Darth Vader]].<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /><ref name=\"Burwick1219\">{{cite news |last=Burwick |first=Kevin |title=Baby Yoda Might Be Evil in The Mandalorian, Is He Wielding the Dark Side of the Force? |work=TVweb |date=December 19, 2019 |url=https://tvweb.com/baby-yoda-evil-the-mandalorian-dark-side-force/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126110433/https://tvweb.com/baby-yoda-evil-the-mandalorian-dark-side-force/ |archive-date=January 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Miller1218\">{{cite news |last=Miller |first=Matt |title=We Regret to Inform You Baby Yoda Might Be Evil |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a30272695/evil-baby-yoda-force-choke-the-mandalorian-episode-7/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101112915/https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a30272695/evil-baby-yoda-force-choke-the-mandalorian-episode-7/ |archive-date=January 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sarah Bea Milner of ''[[Screen Rant]]'' wrote: \"The moment is genuinely shocking \u2014 and more than a little disturbing.\"<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /> Some reviewers noted, however, that the Child likely mistakenly believed the Mandalorian was in danger and intervened to help.<ref name=\"Miller1218\" /><ref name=\"Hedash1219\">{{cite news |last=Hedash |first=Kara |title=Wait... Is Baby Yoda Tempted By The Dark Side? |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 19, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-force-choke-dark-side/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103183558/https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-force-choke-dark-side/ |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Additionally, in the same episode, the Child uses the Force to heal and save Greef Karga, a power typically associated with the Light Side.<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /><ref name=\"Foy1221\" /><ref name=\"Hedash1219\" /> Peter Foy of ''Comic Book Resources'' wrote: \"It doesn't exactly seem realistic that Disney would blow its merchandising potential with the little cutie by going all [[Damien Thorn|Damien]] (''[[The Omen]]'') in his storyline.\"<ref name=\"Foy1221\" />\n\nNevertheless, some writers have suggested viewers had been underestimating the Child's capacity for evil because he is cute.<ref name=\"Hibberd1218\">{{cite news |last=Hibberd |first=James |title=What if Baby Yoda is secretly evil? |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=December 18, 2019 |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/12/18/evil-baby-yoda/ |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221090227/https://ew.com/tv/2019/12/18/evil-baby-yoda/ |archive-date=December 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Miller1218\" /><ref name=\"Abdulbaki0106\">{{cite news |last=Abdulbaki |first=Mae |title='Mandalorian' Season 2 theory links Baby Yoda to a Dark side icon |work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |date=January 6, 2020 |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/62121-mandalorian-season-2-theory-baby-yoda-prophecy-anakin-skywalker |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301162110/https://www.inverse.com/article/62121-mandalorian-season-2-theory-baby-yoda-prophecy-anakin-skywalker |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Fans speculated the Child could be presenting a false personality or using the Force to manipulate people into caring about him to help ensure his survival.<ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" /> ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' writer Matt Miller noted that Yoda lied about his identity during his initial appearance in ''The Empire Strikes Back'', posing as a simple-minded observer to Luke Skywalker before revealing himself to be a Jedi Master. Miller suggested the Child could be putting on a similar performance.<ref name=\"Miller1218\" /> One fan theory suggests the Child could be related to a prophecy in a past ''Star Wars'' work that predicted an evil that could consume the galaxy. The prophecy, described in the novel ''[[Star Wars: Master and Apprentice]]'' (2019), says: \"The danger of the past is not past, but sleeps in an egg. When the egg cracks, it will threaten the galaxy entire.\" Fans theorized this could refer to the Child, who sleeps in an egg-like bassinet in ''The Mandalorian''.<ref name=\"Abdulbaki0106\" /> Others have theorized the reason the Imperial remnant wants the Child is to turn him over to the dark side of the Force,<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /> or for use as a weapon.<ref name=\"Foy1221\" /> Moff Gideon in the season finale says: \"You may think you have some idea what you\u2019re in possession of, but you do not.\" Peter Foy of ''Comic Book Resources'' suggested this could allude to the Child's potential to cause mass destruction.<ref name=\"Foy1221\" />\n\nCaitlin Gallagher of ''[[Bustle (website)|Bustle]]'' suggested rather than building toward the Child becoming evil, the show could be suggesting the Mandalorian needs to find a way to raise the Child in a less violent environment.<ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" /> All season long, the Child has witnessed those around him committing violent acts.<ref name=\"Milner1222\">{{cite news |last=Milner |first=Sarah Bea |title=The Mandalorian: Baby Yoda Learns About Good & Bad In A Powerful Way |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 22, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-makes-statement-nature-versus-nurture/ |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223125659/https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-makes-statement-nature-versus-nurture/ |archive-date=December 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" /> For example, ''Vulture'' writer Keith Phipps noticed that when IG-11 kills multiple stormtroopers in front of him, the Child has a \"look of wonder\" in his eyes, which Phipps said \"is hilarious, but also a little chilling\".<ref name=\"Phipps1227\" /> Some writers applied a [[nature versus nurture]] argument to this, contending the Child is becoming violent because of what he is learning based on the actions around him.<ref name=\"Gallagher1226\" /> This suggests the Child is not inherently good or evil,<ref name=\"Milner1222\" /><ref name=\"Foy1221\" /> but that instead, like all children, he is impressionable and does not fully understand the events occurring around him. He is learning about life and needs guidance as he develops his abilities.<ref name=\"White1218\" /><ref name=\"Milner1222\" /><ref name=\"Burwick1219\" /> This is why he uses Force powers generally associated with both the light and dark sides of the Force.<ref name=\"Foy1221\" /> It will largely fall to the Mandalorian to provide this guidance,<ref name=\"White1218\" /> as when the Mandalorian stops him from strangling Cara.<ref name=\"Milner1222\" />\n\n==Cultural impact==\n===Critical reception===\nThe Child has received a positive reception from fans and reviewers,<ref name=\"Vasquez1203\" /><ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /> and is widely considered the show's [[List of breakout characters|breakout character]].<ref name=\"Cooper1223\" /><ref name=\"Ellis1122\">{{cite news |last=Ellis |first=Emma Grey |title=Love Baby Yoda, You Must |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=November 22, 2019 |url=https://www.wired.com/story/baby-yoda-internet/ |accessdate=December 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127225959/https://www.wired.com/story/baby-yoda-internet/ |archive-date=November 27, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Alexander0221\">{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Julia |title=Hasbro's first look at animatronic Baby Yoda will steal your heart |work=[[The Verge]] |date=February 21, 2020 |url=https://www.theverge.com/tldr/2020/2/21/21146913/baby-yoda-animatronic-toy-hasbro-release-date-price-mandalorian-star-wars-disney |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223050010/https://www.theverge.com/tldr/2020/2/21/21146913/baby-yoda-animatronic-toy-hasbro-release-date-price-mandalorian-star-wars-disney |archive-date=February 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Fans immediately adopted the nickname \"Baby Yoda\" to describe the character,<ref name=\"Alexander0105\" /><ref name=\"Feldman1204\">{{cite news |last=Feldman |first=Brian |title='Am I Allowed to Say Baby Yoda?': Rules for the Yoda Discourse |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=December 4, 2019 |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/12/what-is-baby-yodas-name.html |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205112823/http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/12/what-is-baby-yodas-name.html |archive-date=December 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McCarter |first=Reid |title=Stop fighting it, pedants: ''The Mandalorian''{{'}}s baby Yoda is, and must forever be, \"Baby Yoda\" |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=November 18, 2019 |url=https://news.avclub.com/stop-fighting-it-pedants-the-mandalorians-baby-yoda-i-1839921482 |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218072653/https://news.avclub.com/stop-fighting-it-pedants-the-mandalorians-baby-yoda-i-1839921482 |archive-date=December 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> a moniker Favreau has embraced as \"the easiest, shortest, most hashtagable way to identify that character\".<ref name=\"Alexander0105\" /> However, the nickname is not used internally by the crew of ''The Mandalorian'', and Disney CEO Bob Iger said he \"got my wrist slapped\" by Favreau for calling the character Baby Yoda in e-mail messages.<ref name=\"Gael1223\" /><ref name=\"Hussain1227\">{{cite news |last=Hussain |first=Humza |title=Disney CEO Was Told Off By Mandalorian Creator For Calling Child \"Baby Yoda\" |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 27, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-name-child-jon-favreau-disney/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201200846/https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-name-child-jon-favreau-disney/ |archive-date=February 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' called Baby Yoda \"2019's biggest new character\",<ref name=\"Vasquez1203\" /> and many writers have described him as a key part in the success of Disney+.<ref name=\"Vasquez1203\" /><ref name=\"Alexander1206\">{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Julia |title=Baby Yoda is key to the Disney+ takeover |work=[[The Verge]] |date=December 6, 2019 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/12/6/20997564/baby-yoda-disney-plus-star-wars-mandalorian-merchandise-stranger-things-game-of-thrones-streaming |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208220254/https://www.theverge.com/2019/12/6/20997564/baby-yoda-disney-plus-star-wars-mandalorian-merchandise-stranger-things-game-of-thrones-streaming |archive-date=December 8, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Winck |first=Ben |title=The massive popularity of Baby Yoda memes highlights just how successful Disney Plus has been, one analyst says |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=January 2, 2020|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/baby-yoda-mandalorian-helping-disney-plus-succeed-stock-rosenblatt-says-2020-1-1028792134 |accessdate=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102235627/https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/baby-yoda-mandalorian-helping-disney-plus-succeed-stock-rosenblatt-says-2020-1-1028792134 |archive-date=January 2, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Julia Alexander of ''[[The Verge]]'' wrote: \"There\u2019s no question that Baby Yoda is driving interest in Disney+\".<ref name=\"Alexander1206\" /> Carolyn Giardina of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' said ''The Mandalorian'' \"accomplished the feat of impacting the zeitgeist, in no small part because of the introduction of Baby Yoda\".<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" /> Bryan Alexander of ''[[USA Today]]'' wrote: \"There's nothing hotter in the universe than Baby Yoda.\"<ref name=\"Alexander0105\" />\n\n''Vulture'' writer Madison Malone Kircher described the Child as \"the latest in a series of cute and viral characters whose fame nearly eclipses that of their franchises\", comparing him to the [[Porgs]] from ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]'' (2017), and [[Groot|Baby Groot]] from the ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' films.<ref name=\"Kircher1205\">{{cite news |last=Kircher |first=Madison Malone |title=How Baby Yoda Took Over the Internet |work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] |date=December 5, 2019 |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/how-baby-yoda-took-over-the-internet.html |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224121701/https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/how-baby-yoda-took-over-the-internet.html |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Samuel Spencer of ''[[Newsweek]]'' wrote that \"The entire Internet has fallen in love with the character\".<ref name=\"Spencer1202\" /> Anthony Breznican of ''Vanity Fair'' wrote that the Child \"has become an instant and indelible pop-culture phenomenon. Its fandom is obsessive, transcending age and experience. In an era of bitter division on nearly all matters, there is seemingly unanimous adoration for this tiny alien creature.\"<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /> [[NPR]] reporter [[Mandalit del Barco]] said the Child \"steals the show every time it appears\".<ref name=\"DelBarco1205\" /> ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' writer Emma Grey Ellis wrote that the character is so lovable that its lovability is evidence of storytellers and character designers at the peak of their powers\".<ref name=\"Ellis1122\" /> Julia Alexander wrote: \"There is no one I love more, real or fictional, than Baby Yoda.\"<ref name=\"Alexander0221\" /> Ryan Britt of ''[[Fatherly]]'' that the Child has made ''Star Wars'' relevant to an even wider range of audiences.<ref name=\"Britt1205\" /> Likewise, ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' writer Allegra Frank said the Child made ''The Mandalorian'' \"instantly more memorable and evocative\", and alleviated the solitude and tension that might otherwise have surrounded the show's protagonist.<ref name=\"Frank1203\">{{cite news |last=Frank |first=Allegra |title=Baby Yoda: the Mandalorian's adorable alien co-star, explained |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=December 3, 2019 |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/11/23/20972511/baby-yoda-meme-the-mandalorian-gif-star-wars |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228015643/https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/11/23/20972511/baby-yoda-meme-the-mandalorian-gif-star-wars |archive-date=December 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''The Guardian'' writer Zach Vasquez wrote: \"The mysterious green tyke has been dominating pop culture and social media ever since episode one.\" He noted past ''Star Wars'' works had featured young characters that have not resonated as strongly as the Child, so he credited his success with the character's designers and special effects.<ref name=\"Vasquez1203\" /> Leah Asmelash of ''[[CNN]]'' called the Child a \"perfect creature\" and \"the cutest character to probably ever grace our collective TV screens\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Asmelash |first=Leah |title=People can't stop sharing Baby Yoda memes (and we don't want them to) |work=[[CNN]] |date=November 23, 2019 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/23/us/baby-yoda-memes-trnd/index.html |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221183109/https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/23/us/baby-yoda-memes-trnd/index.html |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Mashable]]'' writer Kellen Beck called the Child \"one of the greatest things to come out of the ''Star Wars'' universe\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Beck |first=Kellen |title=The Baby Yoda puppet cost $5 million to make, but its true value is priceless |work=[[Mashable]] |date=January 14, 2020 |url=https://mashable.com/article/baby-yoda-cost-5-million/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116015957/https://mashable.com/article/baby-yoda-cost-5-million/ |archive-date=January 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Mike Jones of ''Screen Rant'' said the character experienced a \"whirlwind of fame\" since his release, and that there had not been this much \"genuine excitement\" about the unveiling of a new ''Star Wars'' character in decades.<ref name=\"Jones1220\" /> Ben Kuchera called the Child \"the best character the ''Star Wars'' franchise has ever included in anything\".<ref name=\"Kuchera1118\" /> ''[[Insider (website)|Insider]]'' writer Jim Renfro wrote: \"Very rarely do new TV characters come along that seemingly unite entire fandoms in glowing adoration. But the tiny Baby Yoda on ''The Mandalorian'' has done just that in less than one week.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Renfro |first=Kim |title=15 tweets and memes about 'Baby Yoda' on 'The Mandalorian' that prove the character is the best thing in 'Star Wars' |work=[[Insider (website)|Insider]] |date=November 18, 2019 |url=https://www.insider.com/best-baby-yoda-tweets-memes-the-mandalorian-2019-11 |accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' writer Caroline Framke said she fell in love with the character even despite acknowledging that he is an \"inherently manipulative product of the most powerful media conglomerate\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Framke |first=Caroline |title=Why Baby Yoda Unequivocally, Unfortunately Rules (Column) |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=December 4, 2019 |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/columns/why-baby-yoda-rules-mandalorian-star-wars-column-1203424388/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109144557/https://variety.com/2019/tv/columns/why-baby-yoda-rules-mandalorian-star-wars-column-1203424388/ |archive-date=January 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Child was featured on the cover of the December 2019 issue of ''The Hollywood Reporter'', along with the headline: \"Baby Yoda represents the future of Hollywood\".<ref name=\"Keegan1219\" /> In an article in the magazine, writer Rebecca Keegan argued the Child is the culmination of several shifts and trends in the entertainment industry over the decade prior to the release of ''The Mandalorian''. These include the decline of the traditional movie star, the growth of [[Streaming services|streaming media services]], the rise of [[Internet culture]], and technological advances in CGI.<ref name=\"Keegan1219\" /> An online report conducted an analysis of which U.S. states responded most positively to the Child, finding that interest in him was highest in [[Utah]], and lowest in [[Mississippi]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Burton |first=Bonnie |title=Baby Yoda love: See which states are most smitten by the Disney Plus star |work=[[CNET]] |date=December 12, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/baby-yoda-love-see-which-states-are-most-smitten-by-the-disney-plus-star/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226205533/https://www.cnet.com/news/baby-yoda-love-see-which-states-are-most-smitten-by-the-disney-plus-star/ |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Robyn Bahr of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' said the response to the Child, along with that of the show ''[[The Dark Crystal: Age of Resistance]]'', demonstrate that audiences still desire puppetry, animatronics, and practical effects rather than only CGI. Bahr wrote: \"If Baby Yoda were entirely 3D animation, he wouldn't have become an icon the minute we laid our eyes on him.\"<ref name=\"Bahr1231\">{{cite news |last=Bahr |first=Robyn |title=Critic's Notebook: Baby Yoda, 'The Dark Crystal' and the Need for Puppetry in the Age of CGI |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 31, 2019 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/baby-yoda-dark-crystal-prove-we-still-need-puppetry-age-cgi-1265008 |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207090527/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/baby-yoda-dark-crystal-prove-we-still-need-puppetry-age-cgi-1265008 |archive-date=February 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Actress [[Elisabeth Moss]] said of the Child: \"I feel like Baby Yoda has united the country in a way that is very necessary.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Gillibrand |first=Abigail |title=The Handmaid's Tale star Elisabeth Moss praises Baby Yoda for 'uniting the country' |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=December 3, 2019 |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/12/03/handmaids-tale-star-elisabeth-moss-praises-baby-yoda-uniting-country-11263587/ |accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref> Later commenting on the critical response to the Child, Bob Iger said the scale of the reaction was \"beyond my expectations by a wide margin\".<ref name=\"Jones1220\">{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Mike |title=Baby Yoda's Popularity Widely Exceeded Disney's Expectations |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 20, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-popularity-disney-expectations-iger/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221151146/https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-baby-yoda-popularity-disney-expectations-iger/ |archive-date=December 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Couch1216\">{{cite news |last1=Couch |first1=Aaron |last2=Parker |first2=Ryan |title=Bob Iger, J.J. Abrams Reflect on \"Bittersweet\" Close to Skywalker Saga at 'Star Wars' Premiere |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 16, 2019 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/star-wars-rise-skywalker-premiere-stars-reflect-bittersweet-ending-1262952 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206100348/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/star-wars-rise-skywalker-premiere-stars-reflect-bittersweet-ending-1262952 |archive-date=February 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNot all reviews of the Child were positive. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' writer [[Alan Sepinwall]] said the reveal of the Child was a rehash of the appearance of Rotta the Hutt in ''Star Wars: The Clone Wars''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |title='The Mandalorian' (and Mistakes) Kick Off Disney+ Entry to Streaming |work=[[Roling Stone]] |date=November 12, 2019 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-features/mandalorian-episode-1-disneyplus-streaming-launch-review-910060/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229160748/https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-features/mandalorian-episode-1-disneyplus-streaming-launch-review-910060/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Emily Todd VanDerWerff of ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' described the character as \"yet another merchandising opportunity\" and did not feel the character was worth Disney attempting to keep secret before his reveal.<ref>{{cite news |last=VanDerWerff |first=Emily Todd |title=Disney+'s Star Wars series, The Mandalorian, is a triumph of atmosphere \u2014 and little else |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=November 12, 2019 |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/11/12/20961484/mandalorian-star-wars-disney-plus-review-pedro-pascal |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191216231149/https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/11/12/20961484/mandalorian-star-wars-disney-plus-review-pedro-pascal |archive-date=December 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[BBC]]'' writer Caryn James said he did not believe anyone without an emotional attachment to ''Star Wars'' would care about the Child.<ref>{{cite news |last=James |first=Caryn |title=Star Wars show The Mandalorian is difficult to care about |work=[[BBC]] |date=November 13, 2019 |url=https://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20191112-star-wars-show-the-mandalorian-is-difficult-to-care-about |accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> Jeremy Gordon of ''[[The Outline (website)|The Outline]]'' called the Child the \"product of a merciless capitalist machine\" intended primarily to generate merchandising revenue for Disney. Gordon wrote: \"It's not really Baby Yoda I hate, of course. He's really cute. It's the feeling that I'm being pandered to, that all of this is a foregone conclusion.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Gordon |first=Jeremy |title=Love Baby Yoda, I cannot |work=[[The Outline (website)|The Outline]] |date=November 19, 2019 |url=https://theoutline.com/post/8276/baby-yoda-sucks?zd=1&zi=esogsr53 |accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> Emma Gray Ellis wrote that there was some backlash to the Child on social media in response to the character's massive Internet popularity. She wrote: \"There's something grindingly, performatively grouchy in leaping forward to damn something that 'everyone' likes, in no small part because everyone likes it.\"<ref name=\"Ellis1122\" /> The Child ranked first on several ''Screen Rant'' lists about the series, including the most interesting characters from the first season of ''The Mandalorian'',<ref name=\"Pham1231\" /> the best characters from the show,<ref name=\"Pantoja0102\">{{cite news |last=Pantoja |first=Kevin |title=The Mandalorian: 10 Best New Star Wars Characters Introduced In The Show, Ranked |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=January 2, 2020 |url=https://screenrant.com/the-mandalorian-new-star-wars-characters-disney-plus/ |accessdate=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103135900/https://screenrant.com/the-mandalorian-new-star-wars-characters-disney-plus/ |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the best costumes from the first season.<ref name=\"Atkin0108\">{{cite news |last=Atkin |first=Jessie |title=The Mandalorian: 10 of the Best Outfits From Season 1 |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=January 8, 2020 |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-best-fashion-disney-plus/ |accessdate=February 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109140807/https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-best-fashion-disney-plus/ |archive-date=January 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Internet memes===\nThe Child quickly became a popular [[Internet meme]].<ref name=\"Feldman1204\" /><ref name=\"Barron1209\">{{cite news |last=Barron |first=Tory |title=Athletes join in on the 'Baby Yoda' meme frenzy |work=[[ESPN]] |date=December 5, 2019 |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28233739/athletes-join-baby-yoda-meme-frenzy |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206153317/https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28233739/athletes-join-baby-yoda-meme-frenzy |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.esquiresg.com/baby-yoda-memes-of-star-wars-the-mandalorian-on-disney-plus-breaks-the-internet/|title=Baby Yoda Memes of ''Star Wars''{{'}} ''The Mandalorian'' on Disney Plus breaks the Internet|date=December 6, 2019|first=Joy|last=Ling|magazine=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|accessdate=December 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208002313/https://www.esquiresg.com/baby-yoda-memes-of-star-wars-the-mandalorian-on-disney-plus-breaks-the-internet/|archive-date=December 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In the week following the debut of ''The Mandalorian'', the Child was driving almost twice as many social media interactions on news stories about it as any of the 2020 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] presidential [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|candidates]].<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Savitsky |first=Shane |title=Why Baby Yoda should scare Michael Bloomberg and Deval Patrick |work=[[Axios]] |date=February 26, 2020 |url=https://www.axios.com/baby-yoda-2020-democrats-michael-bloomberg-deval-patrick-b3bf5f78-436a-42a5-8904-7c33ac15b85c.html |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103131607/https://www.axios.com/baby-yoda-2020-democrats-michael-bloomberg-deval-patrick-b3bf5f78-436a-42a5-8904-7c33ac15b85c.html |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Cooper1129\">{{cite news |last=Cooper |first=Gael Fashingbauer |title=Baby Yoda trending higher on social media than Democratic candidates |work=[[CNET]] |date=November 29, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/baby-yoda-the-mandalorian-trending-higher-on-social-media-than-democratic-candidates/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224173328/https://www.cnet.com/news/baby-yoda-the-mandalorian-trending-higher-on-social-media-than-democratic-candidates/ |archive-date=December 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Baby Yoda search term saw continuous growth on [[Google Trends]] in the weeks following the release of ''The Mandalorian''.<ref name=\"Kircher1205\" /> There were 2.28 million social media interactions about the characters on news stories in the first two weeks after the release of ''The Mandalorian'',<ref name=\"Cooper1129\" /> and 2 million tweets featuring the words \"Baby Yoda\" were sent on [[Twitter]] between November 12 and December 5, 2019.<ref name=\"Kircher1205\" /> When Favreau tweeted a concept art image of the character by artist Christian Alzmann on November 19, it received more than 34,000 retweets and 217,000 likes within one week.<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /> Various celebrities have tweeted about the character, including [[Ariana Grande]],<ref name=\"Kircher1205\" /> [[Elon Musk]],<ref name=\"Dzurilla1219\">{{cite news |last=D'Zurilla |first=Christie |title=From Baby Yoda to OK, boomer: A look back at 2019's internet obsessions |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=December 19, 2019 |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2019-12-19/2019-internet-obsessions-memes |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116064137/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2019-12-19/2019-internet-obsessions-memes |archive-date=January 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Dwayne Johnson]], [[Russell Wilson]], [[Alex Rodriguez]],<ref name=\"Barron1209\" /> and [[Donald Trump Jr.]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Miller |first=Matt |title=The MAGA Idiots Are Trying to Take Baby Yoda. Sure, Go For It. |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=January 16, 2020 |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/a30546250/maga-baby-yoda-trump-shirts-far-right-symbol/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122134833/https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/a30546250/maga-baby-yoda-trump-shirts-far-right-symbol/ |archive-date=January 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Zach Vasquez of ''The Guardian'' wrote: \"It's now practically impossible to scroll through any social media platform without being inundated with pics, videos, memes and gifs of the bug-eyed, big-eared tot.\"<ref name=\"Vasquez1203\" /> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' included the Child in its list of \"2019's Internet Obsessions\", with writer Christie D'Zurilla writing: \"Baby Yoda won the Internet in 2019.\"<ref name=\"Dzurilla1219\" />\n\nOne of the more popular memes involved a screenshot from \"Chapter 4: Sanctuary\" in which the Child casually sips from a mug of soup,<ref name=\"Kircher1205\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Bell |first=Amanda |title=The Best Baby Yoda Cup Memes on the Internet |work=[[TV Guide]] |date=December 1, 2019 |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/the-best-baby-yoda-cup-memes-on-the-internet/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191202221626/https://www.tvguide.com/news/the-best-baby-yoda-cup-memes-on-the-internet/ |archive-date=December 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Rennex1202\">{{cite news |last=Rennex |first=Michelle |title=This Photo Of Baby Yoda Drinking A Cup Of Soup Has Become A Huge Meme |work=[[Junkee]] |date=December 2, 2019 |url=https://junkee.com/baby-yoda-soup-meme/232760 |accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref> which has been compared to a similar meme of [[Kermit the Frog]] passive-aggressively sipping a glass of tea.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cooper |first=Gael Fashingbauer |title=Baby Yoda sipping-soup meme threatens to replace Kermit sipping tea |work=[[CNET]] |date=November 30, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-new-baby-yoda-sipping-soup-meme-has-so-many-uses/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114052419/https://www.cnet.com/news/the-new-baby-yoda-sipping-soup-meme-has-so-many-uses/ |archive-date=January 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Daley |first=Katerina |title=Star Wars: The 10 Best Baby Yoda Sipping 'Tea' Memes |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 6, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-yoda-sipping-tea-memes/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191207141054/https://screenrant.com/star-wars-yoda-sipping-tea-memes/ |archive-date=December 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leishman |first=Rachel |title=Baby Yoda With His Little Cup Is All of Us |work=[[The Mary Sue]] |date=December 2, 2019 |url=https://www.themarysue.com/baby-yoda-tea/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223075043/https://www.themarysue.com/baby-yoda-tea/ |archive-date=December 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another popular meme utilized a scene from that episode in which the Child randomly presses buttons in the cockpit of the Mandalorian's spaceship,<ref name=\"Kircher1205\" /><ref name=\"Boing1216\">{{cite news |title=Baby Yoda's just fiddling with the radio (meme alert) |work=[[Boing Boing]] |date=December 16, 2019 |url=https://boingboing.net/2019/12/16/baby-yodas-just-fiddling-wit.html |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217200233/https://boingboing.net/2019/12/16/baby-yodas-just-fiddling-wit.html |archive-date=December 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Rennex1206\">{{cite news |last=Rennex |first=Michelle |title=The 'Baby Yoda Playing With The Radio' Meme Is Peak Internet Culture |work=[[Junkee]] |date=December 6, 2019 |url=https://junkee.com/baby-yoda-radio-meme/233711 |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206134909/https://junkee.com/baby-yoda-radio-meme/233711 |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> with most of the memes changing the audio so that it appeared the Child was trying to put various songs on the radio.<ref name=\"Boing1216\" /><ref name=\"Rennex1206\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Yeo |first=Amanda |title=Baby Yoda just wants to listen to his tunes in the latest 'Mandalorian' meme |work=[[Mashable]] |date=December 1, 2019 |url=https://mashable.com/article/baby-yoda-music-edit-the-mandalorian-star-wars/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114053921/https://mashable.com/article/baby-yoda-music-edit-the-mandalorian-star-wars/ |archive-date=January 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In late November 2019, the online [[GIF]] database [[Giphy]] temporarily removed its GIFs of the Child due to \"confusion\" over the legal status of the images, sparking outrage among fans. However, they were quickly restored,<ref name=\"Novak1125\">{{cite news |last=Novak |first=Matt |title=Baby Yoda GIFs Are Back Online and Giphy Has Apologized to Disney For Some Reason |work=[[Gizmodo]] |date=November 25, 2019 |url=https://gizmodo.com/baby-yoda-gifs-are-back-online-and-giphy-has-apologized-1840028385 |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128065918/https://gizmodo.com/baby-yoda-gifs-are-back-online-and-giphy-has-apologized-1840028385 |archive-date=November 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC1125\">{{cite news |title=Baby Yoda Gifs reinstated after Star Wars takedown confusion |work=[[BBC]] |date=November 25, 2019 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-50545583 |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127160713/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-50545583 |archive-date=January 27, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cooper |first=Gael Fashingbauer |title=The Baby Yoda GIF war is over, and fans won |work=[[CNET]] |date=November 25, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-baby-yoda-gif-war-is-over-and-fans-won/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128072814/https://www.cnet.com/news/the-baby-yoda-gif-war-is-over-and-fans-won/ |archive-date=November 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and Giphy issued an apology to Disney for having removed them.<ref name=\"Novak1125\" /><ref name=\"BBC1125\" /> Various sports teams have created their own memes with the Child, including [[Los Angeles Clippers]], [[New York Islanders]], [[Phoenix Suns]], [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], [[San Francisco Giants]], [[Sacramento Kings]], [[Seattle Mariners]], and [[Tennessee Volunteers football]].<ref name=\"Barron1209\" />\n\n===Cultural references===\nIn December 2019, artwork of Disney CEO Bob Iger with the Child appeared in the ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine article naming Iger their Businessperson of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/businessperson-of-the-year-2019-bob-iger/|title=Bob Iger Is ''Time''{{'s}} 2019 Businessperson of the Year|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|first=Belinda|last=Buscombe|date=December 11, 2019|accessdate=December 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211152846/https://time.com/businessperson-of-the-year-2019-bob-iger/|archive-date=December 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' published a cartoon of a woman pushing a [[Baby transport|baby stroller]] and saying to the baby inside it: \"No offense, but Baby Yoda, like, blows you out of the water.\"<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /> Ice2Ice, a musician associated with the website ''[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]'', released \"Dear Baby Yoda: A Love Song\" on December 3, 2019, with the music based upon the song \"[[Dear Theodosia]]\" from the [[Musical theatre|musical]] ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=\"Dear Baby Yoda\": A Love Song |work=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] |date=December 3, 2019 |url=https://www.theringer.com/video/2019/12/3/20994270/dear-baby-yoda-a-love-song |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225034556/https://www.theringer.com/video/2019/12/3/20994270/dear-baby-yoda-a-love-song |archive-date=December 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Diaz |first=Eric |title=\"Dear Baby Yoda\" Mashes Up Mandalorian and Hamilton |work=[[Nerdist Industries|Nerdist]] |date=December 3, 2019 |url=https://nerdist.com/article/dear-baby-yoda-hamilton-theodosia-mandalorian/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221084846/https://nerdist.com/article/dear-baby-yoda-hamilton-theodosia-mandalorian/ |archive-date=December 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Dear Baby Yoda' Is the Star Wars/Hamilton Mashup You've Been Waiting For |work=[[Relevant (magazine)|Relevant]] |date=December 5, 2019 |url=https://relevantmagazine.com/culture/dear-baby-yoda-is-the-star-wars-hamilton-mashup-youve-been-waiting-for/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206083845/https://relevantmagazine.com/culture/dear-baby-yoda-is-the-star-wars-hamilton-mashup-youve-been-waiting-for/ |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The character was also parodied in the December 2019 ''[[South Park]]'' episode \"[[Basic Cable (South Park)|Basic Cable]]\". In the episode, a character named [[Scott Malkinson]] attempts to secure a streaming television show because the woman he is interested in loves the Child, so he believes she will love him too if he gets his own series.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shepherd |first=Jack |title=''South Park'' mocks both Baby Yoda and Disney Plus in latest episode |work=[[GamesRadar+]] |date=December 5, 2019 |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/south-park-baby-yoda-disney-plus-season-23/ |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206210641/https://www.gamesradar.com/south-park-baby-yoda-disney-plus-season-23/ |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The Child was also parodied in the December 14, 2019 episode of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''. He was portrayed by comedian [[Kyle Mooney]] in a ''[[Weekend Update]]'' segment, in which he gossiped about the ''Mandalorian'' cast, talked about his future business ventures, and threatened Baby Groot.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bonnie |first=Burton |title=Baby Yoda threatens Baby Groot on ''SNL'' |work=[[CNET]] |date=December 15, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/star-wars-the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-threatens-baby-groot-on-snl/ |accessdate=January 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229201503/https://www.cnet.com/news/star-wars-the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-threatens-baby-groot-on-snl/ |archive-date=December 29, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Perez |first=Lexy |title='SNL': Kyle Mooney's Baby Yoda Calls Baby Groot His Enemy, Shares Friendship With Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 15, 2019 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/snl-kyle-mooney-portrays-baby-yoda-says-baby-groot-is-his-enemy-1262820 |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211115841/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/snl-kyle-mooney-portrays-baby-yoda-says-baby-groot-is-his-enemy-1262820 |archive-date=February 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the [[77th Golden Globe Awards]], host [[Ricky Gervais]] jokingly mistook [[Joe Pesci]] for \"Baby Yoda\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Amatulli |first=Jenna |title=Ricky Gervais Says Epstein Didn't Kill Himself, Drags Felicity Huffman at Golden Globes |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/ricky-gervais-opening-monologue-golden-globes-2020_n_5e0fa2d3c5b6b5a713ba297d?zwi |access-date=January 5, 2020 |work=[[Huffington Post]] |date=January 5, 2020 |language=en-AU |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106210349/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/ricky-gervais-opening-monologue-golden-globes-2020_n_5e0fa2d3c5b6b5a713ba297d?zwi |archive-date=January 6, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On February 20, the [[United States Army]] revealed that a [[M1 Abrams]] [[tank]] belonging to the 3rd Infantry Division of [[Fort Stewart]] in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] had been named after the Child, with the words \"BABY YODA\" printed on the barrel of its gun.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mizokami |first=Kyle |title=The U.S. Army Has a Tank Named 'Baby Yoda' |work=[[Popular Mechanics]] |date=February 21, 2020 |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/technology/a31045566/baby-yoda-army-tank/ |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Vermane |first=Olivia |title=Baby Yoda tank is the weapon we never knew we needed |work=[[Army Times]] |date=February 24, 2020 |url=https://www.armytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/02/24/baby-yoda-tank-is-the-weapon-we-never-knew-we-needed/ |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Merchandise===\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#ffeeaa |salign=right |width=250px |align=right |quote=I think that part of what people really value is to be surprised and delighted, and I think that's becoming all too rare. It's very difficult to keep secrets about projects you're working on. By holding back on that one product, we knew that we may have had the disadvantage of not having toys available day and date, but what we got in exchange was an excitement surrounding the character, because everybody felt like they discovered him together. |source='''Jon Favreau'''<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" />}}\nDue to the secrecy surrounding the Child, designs of the character were withheld from product manufacturers in the months prior to the release of ''The Mandalorian''. As a result, toys and merchandise of the character were not available in time for the 2019 [[Christmas and holiday season|Christmas season]], despite a high demand for them.<ref name=\"Alexander0105\" /><ref name=\"Bonomolo1230\">{{cite news |last=Bonomolo |first=Cameron |title=''Star Wars'': Disney CEO Explains Lack of Baby Yoda Merchandise for Holiday Season |work=ComicBook.com |date=December 30, 2019 |url=https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/12/28/star-wars-why-cant-buy-baby-yoda-merchandise-holiday-season-2019-disney-ceo-bob-iger-explains/ |accessdate=January 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112060845/https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/12/28/star-wars-why-cant-buy-baby-yoda-merchandise-holiday-season-2019-disney-ceo-bob-iger-explains/ |archive-date=January 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Walt Disney Company accepted this plan despite knowing it would cost the company merchandising revenue in the short term; Favreau said \"they understood the value of it\".<ref name=\"Giardina1205\" /> Iger said if the Child's design had been distributed for toys before the show's release, \"it would have gone out to hundreds and hundreds of people, probably all over the world, and we didn't want to do that\".<ref name=\"Bonomolo1230\" /> Iger reiterated that Disney is a story-first company which has \"never set out to tell a story simply because it can become a toy or a game or a consumer product of some sort\",<ref name=\"Bonomolo1230\"/> and he described the wait to unveil the Child as \"worth it\".<ref name=\"Jones1220\" /><ref name=\"Couch1216\" /> The [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] product research tool Jungle Scout projected that Disney may have lost $2.7 million in revenue because of the delay in release merchandise of the Child;<ref>{{cite news |last=Bonomolo |first=Cameron |title=Star Wars: Delayed Baby Yoda Merchandise Cost Disney Millions |work=Comicbook.com |date=December 6, 2019 |url=https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/12/05/star-wars-baby-yoda-merchandise-delay-cost-disney-millions-the-mandalorian/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112060850/https://comicbook.com/starwars/2019/12/05/star-wars-baby-yoda-merchandise-delay-cost-disney-millions-the-mandalorian/ |archive-date=January 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> demand for toys of the Child were so high that Amazon customers searched for Baby Yoda products more than 90,000 times in one month.<ref name=\"Burch1205\">{{cite news |last=Burch |first=Sean |title=Sorry They Are! Lack of Baby Yoda Merchandise Has Cost Disney Millions This Year |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=December 5, 2019 |url=https://www.thewrap.com/baby-yoda-merchandise-lack-disney-cost-millions/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229004754/https://www.thewrap.com/baby-yoda-merchandise-lack-disney-cost-millions/ |archive-date=December 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> David Lazarus, consumer columnist for the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', said he understood Disney's strategy, but felt the company missed out on significant commercial opportunity: \"The fact that they didn't anticipate that this was going to be a commercial goldmine is insane, and that they let this opportunity slip away strikes me as sheer madness.\"<ref name=\"DelBarco1205\" />\n\nDue to the scarcity of licensed merchandise of the Child, many unlicensed products featuring the character were created and sold through the Internet, including via websites like [[Etsy]].<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /><ref name=\"DelBarco1205\" /><ref name=\"Chaney1121\">{{cite news |last=Chaney |first=Jen |title=A Black Market Baby Yoda Gift Guide |work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] |date=November 21, 2019 |url=https://www.vulture.com/article/baby-yoda-gift-guide.html |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122040344/https://www.vulture.com/article/baby-yoda-gift-guide.html |archive-date=November 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> These included [[felt]] and [[crochet]]ed dolls, shirts, [[jewellery]], [[Christmas ornament]]s, art prints, [[bumper sticker]]s, [[Mug|coffee mugs]], and more.<ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /><ref name=\"Chaney1121\" /> [[Do it yourself]] videos were also produced showing how fans could make their own toys based upon the Child.<ref name=\"DelBarco1205\" /> The top 47 unofficial Child products by Amazon merchants sold an average of 1,842 pieces of merchandise in the month following the show's release, at an average of $23 per product.<ref name=\"Burch1205\" /> In mid-January 2020, Disney issued takedown notices against several Etsy sellers using the words \"Star Wars\", \"Mandalorian\", and \"Yoda\", citing copyright violations.<ref name=\"Carras0117\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Priestman |first=Chris |title=Disney Is Removing Baby Yoda Toys Due to Copyright Violations |work=[[IGN]] |date=January 17, 2020 |url=https://nordic.ign.com/the-mandalorian-season-1/32971/news/disney-is-removing-baby-yoda-toys-due-to-copyright-violations |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124235728/https://nordic.ign.com/the-mandalorian-season-1/32971/news/disney-is-removing-baby-yoda-toys-due-to-copyright-violations |archive-date=January 24, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gartenberg |first=Chaim |title=Disney is hunting down the most popular Baby Yoda toys on Etsy |work=[[The Verge]] |date=January 17, 2020 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/17/21069124/baby-yoda-dolls-etsy-disney-mandalorian-copyright-takedown-enforcement |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215052835/https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/17/21069124/baby-yoda-dolls-etsy-disney-mandalorian-copyright-takedown-enforcement |archive-date=February 15, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Official [[Consumables|soft goods]] such as T-shirts were the first to be made available because they were the easiest to produce.<ref name=\"Alexander0105\" /><ref name=\"Breznican1126\" /> The first two official dolls of the Child released were a 10-inch [[Funko]] figurine and an 11-inch plush toy from [[Mattel]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hibberd |first=James |title=Baby Yoda dolls from ''The Mandalorian'' have arrived |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=December 3, 2019 |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/12/03/baby-yoda-mandalorian-doll/|accessdate=December 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211031133/https://ew.com/tv/2019/12/03/baby-yoda-mandalorian-doll/ |archive-date=December 11, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> which began shipping in February.<ref name=\"DelBarco1205\" /> Pre-orders for the Funko doll made it the top toy on Amazon upon its release.<ref name=\"Hussain1227\" /> More official merchandise is expected to be released in early 2020.<ref name=\"Kircher1205\" /><ref name=\"Burch1205\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Hersko |first=Tyler |title=Why There Won't be Any Baby Yoda Toys Until Spring 2020 |work=[[IndieWire]] |date=December 7, 2019 |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-merchandise-questions-1202195206/ |accessdate=December 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191207155208/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/the-mandalorian-merchandise-questions-1202195206/ |archive-date=December 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2019, the [[Electronic Arts]] video game ''[[The Sims 4]]'' added \"The Child Statue\" as a purchasable decoration.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tenbarge |first=Kat |title=You can buy a Baby Yoda statue in ''The Sims 4'' now, and fans are posting memes of their hilarious in-game creations |work=[[Insider (website)|Insider]] |date=December 15, 2019 |url=https://www.insider.com/baby-yoda-statue-decoration-item-the-sims-4-memes-2019-12 |access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSeveral toys of the Child were announced [[American International Toy Fair]] in [[New York City]] in February 2020,<ref name=\"Song0220\">{{cite news |last=Song |first=Victoria |title=Hasbro's Baby Yoda Animatronic Is Too Cute and Somehow Only $60 |work=[[Gizmodo]] |date=February 20, 2020 |url=https://gizmodo.com/hasbros-baby-yoda-animatronic-is-too-cute-and-somehow-o-1841809285 |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221131633/https://gizmodo.com/hasbros-baby-yoda-animatronic-is-too-cute-and-somehow-o-1841809285 |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Whitbrook0220\">{{cite news |last=Whitbrook |first=James |title=Exclusive: Baby Yoda Steals the Show in Hasbro's Adorable New Star Wars Vehicle Line |work=[[Gizmodo]] |date=February 20, 2020 |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/exclusive-baby-yoda-steals-the-show-in-hasbros-adorabl-1841646670 |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221132344/https://io9.gizmodo.com/exclusive-baby-yoda-steals-the-show-in-hasbros-adorabl-1841646670 |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> most notably a nearly life-sized animatronic Child toy by [[Hasbro]], which moves, blinks, and makes sounds like the actual character.<ref name=\"Alexander0221\" /><ref name=\"Song0220\" /> The toy sold out within days of its announcement, with new deliveries not expected until December 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fickenscher |first=Lisa |title= New 'animatronic' Baby Yoda already sold out until December |work=[[New York Post]] |date=February 25, 2020 |url=https://nypost.com/2020/02/25/new-animatronic-baby-yoda-already-sold-out-until-next-december/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref> Other toys announced at the Fair include a Child [[waffle iron]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Petite |first=Steven |title=Eat Baby Yoda For Breakfast With This Adorable Waffle Maker |work=[[GameSpot]] |date=March 3, 2020 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/eat-baby-yoda-for-breakfast-with-this-adorable-waf/1100-6474358/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304022023/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/eat-baby-yoda-for-breakfast-with-this-adorable-waf/1100-6474358/ |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Chia Pet]]s of the Child,<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Neill |first=Mae Harrington |title=Baby Yoda Chia Pets Are Coming Soon |work=[[Mental Floss]] |date=March 2, 2020 |url=https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/619196/baby-yoda-chia-pets |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304022022/https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/619196/baby-yoda-chia-pets |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a vehicle set as part of Hasbro's ''Mission Fleet'' toyline, which include the Mandalorian on a [[speeder bike]] and the Child in his floating bassinet.<ref name=\"Whitbrook0220\" /> [[Build-A-Bear Workshop]] has also announced it will release a version of a Child doll in early 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Huhn |first=Mary |title=Animatronic Baby Yoda toy now available, with Build-A-Bear version soon to follow |work=[[New York Post]] |date=February 20, 2020 |url=https://nypost.com/2020/02/20/animatronic-baby-yoda-toy-now-available-with-build-a-bear-version-soon-to-follow/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221131759/https://nypost.com/2020/02/20/animatronic-baby-yoda-toy-now-available-with-build-a-bear-version-soon-to-follow/ |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Lego]] has announced plans for an August 2020 release of BrickHeadz figures of both the Child and the Mandalorian, as well as a September 2020 release of a Lego set for the Mandalorian's ''Razor Crest'' spaceship, which will include a small figurine of Child.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lego Baby Yoda (and The Mandalorian's Razor Crest) is now a thing, because of course it is |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=February 20, 2020 |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/02/20/lego-baby-yoda-mandalorians-razor-crest-now-thing-course-12275368/ |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221131637/https://metro.co.uk/2020/02/20/lego-baby-yoda-mandalorians-razor-crest-now-thing-course-12275368/ |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2020, an unofficial user-created mod for the video game ''[[Star Wars Battlefront II (2017 video game)|Star Wars Battlefront II]]'' allowed the character [[BB-8]] to be replaced with a playable version of the Child.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hall |first=Charlie |title=Watch Baby Yoda slaughter a town of stormtroopers in this Battlefront 2 mod |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=March 3, 2020 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/3/3/21162868/star-wars-baby-yoda-battlefront-2-mod-video |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304022022/https://www.polygon.com/2020/3/3/21162868/star-wars-baby-yoda-battlefront-2-mod-video |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McCarter |first=Reid |title=Baby Yoda's a stone-cold killer now |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=March 3, 2020 |url=https://news.avclub.com/baby-yodas-a-stone-cold-killer-now-1842059528 |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304022021/https://news.avclub.com/baby-yodas-a-stone-cold-killer-now-1842059528 |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Knox |first=Kelly |title=Unofficial Star Wars Battlefront II Mod Adds Baby Yoda to the Fray |work=[[Nerdist Industries|Nerdist]] |date=March 3, 2020 |url=https://nerdist.com/article/star-wars-battlefront-ii-mods-baby-yoda/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304023525/https://nerdist.com/article/star-wars-battlefront-ii-mods-baby-yoda/ |archive-date=March 4, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Works cited===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite podcast |last1=Rosas |first1=Misty |last2=Ballance |first2=Brian |url=https://soundcloud.com/theinterestingpodcast/ep-108-misty-rosas |publisher=The Interesting Podcast |