{"title_page": "National Statistical Commission", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| agency_name = '''National Statistical Commission''' '''\u0930\u093e\u0937\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930\u0940\u092f \u0938\u093e\u0902\u0916\u094d\u092f\u093f\u0915\u0940 \u0906\u092f\u094b\u0917'''\n| type = Autonomous Body\n| seal = \n| nativename_a = \n| nativename_r = \n| logo = Emblem_of_India.svg\n| logo_width = 150\n| formed = July 12 2006\n| jurisdiction = \n| headquarters = [[New Delhi]]\n| employees = \n| budget = \n| chief1_name = \n| chief1_position = \n| chief2_name = \n| chief2_position = \n| chief3_name = \n| chief3_position = \n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = \n| website = {{URL|www.mospi.nic.in}}\n}}\n\nThe '''National Statistical Commission''' (NSC) of [[India]] is an autonomous body which formed in June 2005 under the recommendation of Rangarajan commission. The NSC is currently headed by Prof. [[Bimal K. Roy]]<ref>http://mospi.gov.in/present-composition-nsc</ref><ref>https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/bimal-kumar-roy-to-be-new-chairman-of-national-statistical-commission-2065033</ref> who was appointed as Chairperson of the Commission on 15th July 2019 for a period of three years. Dr. Kiran Pandya, Shri Pulak Ghosh and Dr. Gurucharan Manna are other members of the Commission. Shri [[Amitabh Kant]], current CEO of [[NITI Aayog]] is the ex-officio Member and Shri Pravin Srivastava, Chief Statistician of India and Secretary, [[Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation]] is Secretary to the Commission.<ref>http://mospi.gov.in/present-composition-nsc</ref> The Chairperson of the Commission enjoys the status of a Minister of State and the Members of the Commission have the status equivalent to the Secretary to the Government of India. The Chairperson and the Members also enjoy a relative security of tenure as once they assume office, they can be removed only by the President after the Supreme Court of India has on inquiry held in accordance with the procedure Article 145 of the [[Constitution of India]] reported that they ought to be removed.\n\nThe objective of its constitution is to reduce the problems faced by statistical agencies in the country in relation to collection of data.\n\nStatistical agencies like the [[Central Statistical Office (India)|Central Statistics Office]] (CSO) and the [[National Sample Survey Organisation]] (NSSO) face numerous problems in collecting data from State and Central government departments, but an autonomous body like the NSC is thought to be more able to coordinate things as a statutory status would lend it teeth.\n\nIt would lay special emphasis on ensuring collection of unbiased data so as to restore public trust in the figures released by the Government.\n\n==Present Composition==\n1 Chairperson + 4 Members\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ National Statistical Commission\n! Position !! Name of the Member\n|-\n| Chairman || Prof. [[Bimal Kumar Roy]]\n|-\n| Member || Dr. Kiran Pandya\n|-\n| Member || Shri Pulak Ghosh\n|-\n| Member || Dr. Gurucharan Manna\n|-\n| Member || Vacant\n|-\n| Ex-Officio Member<ref>http://www.mospi.gov.in/present-composition-nsc</ref> || Shri Amitabh Kant, CEO NITI Aayog\n|-\n| Secretary to the NSC || Sh.Pravin Srivastava, Chief Statistician of India & Secretary MOSPI\n|}\n<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/two-remaining-nsc-members-resign/article26124850.ece</ref>\n\n==Present Composition - Members of Working Group==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ National Statistical Commission\n! Name of the Member !! Position\n|-\n| Prof. R. Radhakrishna || Member (Non-Official)\n|-\n| Prof. Jandhyala B. G. Tilak, || Member (Non-Official)\n|-\n| Prof. Sridhar Srivastava || Member (Non-Official)\n|-\n| Dr. (Mrs) Usha Ram || Member (Non-Official)\n|-\n| Dr. C. Ravi || Member (Non-Official)\n|-\n| Mr. Probir Chaudhury || Member (Non-Official)\n|-\n| Dr. Rattan Chand || Member (Non-Official)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Indian commissions}}\n\n[[Category:Indian commissions and inquiries]]\n[[Category:Statistical organisations in India]]\n[[Category:Government of India]]\n\n\n{{India-gov-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n| agency_name = '''National Statistical Commission''' '''\u0930\u093e\u0937\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930\u0940\u092f \u0938\u093e\u0902\u0916\u094d\u092f\u093f\u0915\u0940 \u0906\u092f\u094b\u0917'''\n| type = Autonomous Body\n| seal = \n| nativename_a = \n| nativename_r = \n| logo = Emblem_of_India.svg\n| logo_width = 150\n| formed = July 12 2006\n| jurisdiction = \n| headquarters = [[New Delhi]]\n| employees = \n| budget = \n| chief1_name = \n| chief1_position = \n| chief2_name = \n| chief2_position = \n| chief3_name = \n| chief3_position = \n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = \n| website = {{URL|www.mospi.nic.in}}\n}}\n\nThe '''National Statistical Commission''' (NSC) of [[India]] is an autonomous body which formed in June 2005 under the recommendation of Rangarajan commission. The NSC is currently headed by Prof. [[Bimal K. Roy]]<ref>http://mospi.gov.in/present-composition-nsc</ref><ref>https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/bimal-kumar-roy-to-be-new-chairman-of-national-statistical-commission-2065033</ref> who was appointed as Chairperson of the Commission on 15th July 2019 for a period of three years. Dr. Kiran Pandya, Shri Pulak Ghosh and Dr. Gurucharan Manna are other members of the Commission. Shri [[Amitabh Kant]], current CEO of [[NITI Aayog]] is the ex-officio Member and Shri Pravin Srivastava, Chief Statistician of India and Secretary, [[Ministry of Statistics and Programme Implementation]] is Secretary to the Commission.<ref>http://mospi.gov.in/present-composition-nsc</ref> The Chairperson of the Commission enjoys the status of a Minister of State and the Members of the Commission have the status equivalent to the Secretary to the Government of India. The Chairperson and the Members also enjoy a relative security of tenure as once they assume office, they can be removed only by the President after the Supreme Court of India has on inquiry held in accordance with the procedure Article 145 of the [[Constitution of India]] reported that they ought to be removed.\n\nThe objective of its constitution is to reduce the problems faced by statistical agencies in the country in relation to collection of data.\n\nStatistical agencies like the [[Central Statistical Office (India)|Central Statistics Office]] (CSO) and the [[National Sample Survey Organisation]] (NSSO) face numerous problems in collecting data from State and Central government departments, but an autonomous body like the NSC is thought to be more able to coordinate things as a statutory status would lend it teeth.\n\nIt would lay special emphasis on ensuring collection of unbiased data so as to restore public trust in the figures released by the Government.\n\n==Present Composition==\n1 Chairperson + 4 Members\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ National Statistical Commission\n! Position !! Name of the Member\n|-\n| Chairman ||[[Vacant]]\n|-\n| Member || Dr. Kiran Pandya\n|-\n| Member || Shri Pulak Ghosh\n|-\n| Member || Dr. Gurucharan Manna\n|-\n| Member || Vacant\n|-\n| Ex-Officio Member<ref>http://www.mospi.gov.in/present-composition-nsc</ref> || Shri Amitabh Kant, CEO NITI Aayog\n|-\n| Secretary to the NSC || Sh.Pravin Srivastava, Chief Statistician of India & Secretary MOSPI\n|}\n<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/two-remaining-nsc-members-resign/article26124850.ece</ref>\n\n==Present Composition - Members of Working Group==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ National Statistical Commission\n! Name of the Member !! Position\n|-\n| Prof. R. Radhakrishna || Member (Non-Official)\n|-\n| Prof. Jandhyala B. G. Tilak, || Member (Non-Official)\n|-\n| Prof. Sridhar Srivastava || Member (Non-Official)\n|-\n| Dr. (Mrs) Usha Ram || Member (Non-Official)\n|-\n| Dr. C. Ravi || Member (Non-Official)\n|-\n| Mr. Probir Chaudhury || Member (Non-Official)\n|-\n| Dr. Rattan Chand || Member (Non-Official)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Indian commissions}}\n\n[[Category:Indian commissions and inquiries]]\n[[Category:Statistical organisations in India]]\n[[Category:Government of India]]\n\n\n{{India-gov-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ashwinjha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePresent Composition:Add current chairperson", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Statistical_Commission"}
{"title_page": "Pilotbird", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Pilotbird\n| image = Pilotbird - Blue Mountains.jpg\n| image_caption = Pilotbird, Blue Mountains\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704513/0 |title=''Pycnoptilus floccosus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International|year=2016|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n| genus = Pycnoptilus\n| parent_authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1851\n| species = floccosus\n| authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1851\n}}\n\nThe '''pilotbird''' (''Pycnoptilus floccosus'') is a species of passerine [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]]. It is [[monotypic]] within the genus '''''Pycnoptilus'''''.  The species is [[Endemism|endemic]] to south-eastern [[Australia]]. \n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe species was first described by English ornithologist, [[John Gould]], in 1851. The generic name ''Pycnoptilus'' derives from the Ancient Greek ''pyknos'' 'thick' and ''ptilon'' 'feather'.<ref name=Helm>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-20}}</ref> Its specific epithet ''floccosus'' is Late Latin for 'flocked with wool'.<ref name=Helm></ref> There are two subspecies: the nominate subspecies ''Pycnoptilus floccosus floccosus'' lives in alpine areas; and ''P. f. sandfordi'' lives in lowland forest.<ref name=Gregory>Gregory, P. (2020). \"Pilotbird (Pycnoptilus floccosus), version 1.0.\" In ''Birds of the World'' (J. del Hoyo, A. Elliott, J. Sargatal, D. A. Christie, and E. de Juana, Editors). Cornell Lab of Ornithology, Ithaca, NY, USA. https://doi.org/10.2173/bow.pilotb1.01</ref><ref name=Slater></ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe pilotbird is a large, plump species of acanthizid, measuring around {{convert|18|cm|in}} in length and weighing {{convert|27|g|oz}}.<ref name=Gregory></ref> The [[plumage]] of the underparts is reddish-brown with scalloping on the chest and the centre of the belly speckled dull white. The upperparts are chocolate-brown.<ref name=Slater>Slater, Peter (1974) ''A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Passerines.'' Adelaide: Rigby. ISBN 085179813-6</ref><ref name=Simpson>Simpson, Ken, Day, N. and Trusler, P. (6th edn., 1999). ''Field Guide to the Birds of Australia''. Ringwood, Victoria: Penguin Books Australia ISBN 067087918-5.</ref> \nThe bill is short and finely pointed.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> Its tail is broad and semi-erect, and flicked up and down when feeding.<ref name=Slater></ref><ref name=Pizzey></ref>\n\n==Distribution and Habitat==\nThe pilotbird is found from the [[Wollemi National Park]] and [[Blue Mountains National Park]] in New South Wales through to the [[Dandenong Ranges]], near Melbourne in Victoria.<ref name=eBird>{{cite web|url=https://ebird.org/map/pilotb1|title=eBird map: Pilotbird|accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> Its natural [[habitat]] is temperate [[wet sclerophyll]] forests and occasionally temperate [[rainforest]], where there is dense undergrowth with abundant debris.<ref name=IUCN></ref><ref name=Morcombe></ref> It is sedentary and common.<ref name=Morcombe></ref>\n\n==Behaviour==\nIts name comes from its supposed habit of following [[lyrebird]]s, taking prey that they flush, and also from its call guiding bushmen seeking for lyrebirds.<ref name=Morcombe>Morcombe, Michael (2012) ''Field Guide to Australian Birds''. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref> This habit is well known but seldom observed. The pilotbird is highly terrestrial, feeding on or near the ground and when disturbed it runs swiftly on strong legs.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> Its call has been described as \"piercing and sweet\".<ref name=Pizzey>Pizzey, Graham; Doyle, Roy (1980) ''A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia''. Collins Publishers, Sydney. ISBN 073222436-5</ref> The male makes a far-carrying call of ''wit-wit-weet-WHEER'' to which the female may respond with a softer ''wit-a-wit-ee''.<ref name=Morcombe></ref><ref name=Pizzey></ref><ref name=Gregory></ref> \n\n===Breeding===\nThe breeding season for the pilotbird is from August to December.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> The globular nest is built with a side-entrance and hidden amongst the accumulated debris on the forest floor.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> It is an untidy construction of bark, ferns, dead leaves and rootlets.<ref name=Pizzey></ref> A clutch of usually two eggs, each measuring {{convert|27|by|20|mm|in|2}} and varying in colour from grey-green to purple-brown, is incubated by the female for 20-22 days.<ref name=Morcombe></ref><ref name=Pizzey></ref> During the nestling period, which lasts 14-17 days, the male will often feed the female or help with the care of the nestlings, if the female has a subsequent brood.<ref name=Gregory></ref> The nests are sometimes [[brood parasites|parasitised]] by the [[fan-tailed cuckoo]] (''Cacomantis flabelliformis'').<ref name=Gregory/>\n\n==Conservation==\nThe pilotbird is fairly common within its small range, which has reduced as a result of forest clearance and urban development, but much of its habitat is within national parks or reserves.<ref name=Gregory></ref> Its habitat is also threatened by climate change, severe weather and bushfires;<ref name=IUCN></ref> nevertheless, the most recent assessment in October 2016 classified the pilotbird as [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1585682}}\n\n[[Category:Acanthizidae]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1851]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Pilotbird\n| image = Pilotbird - Blue Mountains.jpg\n| image_caption = Pilotbird, Blue Mountains\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704513/0 |title=''Pycnoptilus floccosus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n| genus = Pycnoptilus\n| parent_authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1851\n| species = floccosus\n| authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1851\n}}\n\nThe '''pilotbird''' (''Pycnoptilus floccosus'') is a species of passerine [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]]. It is [[monotypic]] within the genus '''''Pycnoptilus'''''.  The species is [[Endemism|endemic]] to south-eastern [[Australia]]. \n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe species was first described by English ornithologist, [[John Gould]], in 1851. The generic name ''Pycnoptilus'' derives from the Ancient Greek ''pyknos'' 'thick' and ''ptilon'' 'feather'.<ref name=Helm>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-20}}</ref> Its specific epithet ''floccosus'' is Late Latin for 'flocked with wool'.<ref name=Helm></ref> There are two subspecies: the nominate subspecies ''Pycnoptilus floccosus floccosus'' lives in alpine areas; and ''P. f. sandfordi'' lives in lowland forest.<ref name=Gregory>Gregory, P. (2020). \"Pilotbird (Pycnoptilus floccosus), version 1.0.\" In ''Birds of the World'' (J. del Hoyo, A. Elliott, J. Sargatal, D. A. Christie, and E. de Juana, Editors). Cornell Lab of Ornithology, Ithaca, NY, USA. https://doi.org/10.2173/bow.pilotb1.01</ref><ref name=Slater></ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe pilotbird is a large, plump species of acanthizid, measuring around {{convert|18|cm|in}} in length and weighing {{convert|27|g|oz}}.<ref name=Gregory></ref> The [[plumage]] of the underparts is reddish-brown with scalloping on the chest and the centre of the belly speckled dull white. The upperparts are chocolate-brown.<ref name=Slater>Slater, Peter (1974) ''A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Passerines.'' Adelaide: Rigby. ISBN 085179813-6</ref><ref name=Simpson>Simpson, Ken, Day, N. and Trusler, P. (6th edn., 1999). ''Field Guide to the Birds of Australia''. Ringwood, Victoria: Penguin Books Australia ISBN 067087918-5.</ref> \nThe bill is short and finely pointed.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> Its tail is broad and semi-erect, and flicked up and down when feeding.<ref name=Slater></ref><ref name=Pizzey></ref>\n\n==Distribution and Habitat==\nThe pilotbird is found from the [[Wollemi National Park]] and [[Blue Mountains National Park]] in New South Wales through to the [[Dandenong Ranges]], near Melbourne in Victoria.<ref name=eBird>{{cite web|url=https://ebird.org/map/pilotb1|title=eBird map: Pilotbird|accessdate=2020-04-20}}</ref> Its natural [[habitat]] is temperate [[wet sclerophyll]] forests and occasionally temperate [[rainforest]], where there is dense undergrowth with abundant debris.<ref name=IUCN></ref><ref name=Morcombe></ref> It is sedentary and common.<ref name=Morcombe></ref>\n\n==Behaviour==\nIts name comes from its supposed habit of following [[lyrebird]]s, taking prey that they flush, and also from its call guiding bushmen seeking for lyrebirds.<ref name=Morcombe>Morcombe, Michael (2012) ''Field Guide to Australian Birds''. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref> This habit is well known but seldom observed. The pilotbird is highly terrestrial, feeding on or near the ground and when disturbed it runs swiftly on strong legs.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> Its call has been described as \"piercing and sweet\".<ref name=Pizzey>Pizzey, Graham; Doyle, Roy (1980) ''A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia''. Collins Publishers, Sydney. ISBN 073222436-5</ref> The male makes a far-carrying call of ''wit-wit-weet-WHEER'' to which the female may respond with a softer ''wit-a-wit-ee''.<ref name=Morcombe></ref><ref name=Pizzey></ref><ref name=Gregory></ref> \n\n===Breeding===\nThe breeding season for the pilotbird is from August to December.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> The globular nest is built with a side-entrance and hidden amongst the accumulated debris on the forest floor.<ref name=Morcombe></ref> It is an untidy construction of bark, ferns, dead leaves and rootlets.<ref name=Pizzey></ref> A clutch of usually two eggs, each measuring {{convert|27|by|20|mm|in|2}} and varying in colour from grey-green to purple-brown, is incubated by the female for 20-22 days.<ref name=Morcombe></ref><ref name=Pizzey></ref> During the nestling period, which lasts 14-17 days, the male will often feed the female or help with the care of the nestlings, if the female has a subsequent brood.<ref name=Gregory></ref> The nests are sometimes [[brood parasites|parasitised]] by the [[fan-tailed cuckoo]] (''Cacomantis flabelliformis'').<ref name=Gregory/>\n\n==Conservation==\nThe pilotbird is fairly common within its small range, which has reduced as a result of forest clearance and urban development, but much of its habitat is within national parks or reserves.<ref name=Gregory></ref> Its habitat is also threatened by climate change, severe weather and bushfires;<ref name=IUCN></ref> nevertheless, the most recent assessment in October 2016 classified the pilotbird as [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1585682}}\n\n[[Category:Acanthizidae]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1851]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pilotbird"}
{"title_page": "Pantropy", "text_new": "'''Pantropy''' is a hypothetical process of [[space colonization]] in which rather than [[terraforming]] other planets or building [[space habitat]]s suitable for human habitation, humans are modified (for example via [[genetic engineering]]) to be able to thrive in the existing environment. The term was coined by [[science fiction author]] [[James Blish]], who wrote a series of short stories based on the idea (collected in the anthology ''[[James Blish#The Seedling Stars (Pantropy)|The Seedling Stars]]'').\n\n==Fictional depictions==\n\n* 1930\u2014In the science fiction [[novel]] ''[[Last and First Men]]'' by [[Olaf Stapledon]], when humanity migrates from [[Earth]] to [[Venus]] and later from Venus to [[Neptune]], human beings are [[Genetic engineering|genetically engineered]] to fit the new environments in which they will be living.\n* 1944\u2014One of the first science fiction stories about pantropy (the word had not yet been coined) was the [[short story]] \"Desertion,\" by [[Clifford D. Simak]], which appeared in the November 1944 ''[[Astounding Science Fiction]]''. In this story, human colonists living in a [[domed city]] on the planet [[Jupiter]] are put through a biological converter that converts their bodies into the form of the indigenous Jovian lifeform called the \"Lopers.\"  The head director of the domed colony, Kent Fowler, wondering why none of those biologically converted ever come back, goes into the biological converter himself with his [[dog]] and finds that the reason they never come back is that the Lopers have [[brain]]s and [[sense]]s so much in advance of humans that they don't want to come back.  He also finds that he is able to completely accurately [[telepathy|telepathically communicate]] with his dog Towser (whose intelligence has also greatly increased) after going through the converter.  He himself decides not to go back.<ref>Conklin, Groff (editor) ''[[Big Book of Science Fiction]]'' New York:1950 Crown Publishers \"Desertion,\" by [[Clifford D. Simak]] Pages 413-423</ref> The story was incorporated into the novel ''[[City (novel)|City]]'' (1952).\n* 1957\u2014''[[James Blish#The Seedling Stars (Pantropy)|The Seedling Stars]]'', by [[James Blish]], a collection of science fiction stories about pantropy. The best-known of these is \"[[Surface Tension (short story)|Surface Tension]]\", often anthologized in its original 1952 standalone version.\n* 1976\u2014[[Frederik Pohl]]'s novel ''[[Man Plus]]'' is a story about the transformation of a human into a hybrid/[[cyborg]] in order to allow him to live comfortably on [[Mars]].  In the sequel, ''[[Mars Plus]]'', some colonists opt for an intermediate existence, and are known as [[Creole peoples|Creoles]].\n* 1981-1983\u2014[[Jack L. Chalker]]'s ''[[Four Lords of the Diamond]]'' series describes the changes in personality that result from physical changes caused by a symbiotic microorganism that adapts humans into a form that can survive on each of  four different planets.\n* 1989-1997\u2014[[Dan Simmons]]' ''[[Hyperion Cantos]]'' is a series of four books featuring a faction known as the Ousters, which use pantropy as a way of living in harmony with nature and space.\n* 2000\u2014[[Stephen Baxter (author)|Stephen Baxter]]'s novels repeatedly deal with pantropy as an approach to the far future of the human species.\n* 2002\u2014[[Timothy Zahn]]'s novel Manta's Gift features technology capable of transmitting human consciousness to an alien body.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hromic |first1=Alma |title=The SF Site Featured Review: Manta's Gift |url=https://www.sfsite.com/02a/ma145.htm |accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n* 2009\u2014[[James Cameron]]'s film ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'' is a somewhat different take on pantropy.\n* 2011\u2014In the manga ''[[Terra Formars]]'', humans sent to Mars undergo genetic modification to inherit the characteristics of other organisms.\n* 2014\u2014In the video game ''[[Civilization: Beyond Earth]]'', the Harmony affinity represents pantropy.''\n\n==References==\n\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Science fiction themes]]\n[[Category:Space colonization]]\n[[Category:Transhumanism]]\n", "text_old": "'''Pantropy''' is a hypothetical process of [[space colonization]] in which rather than [[terraforming]] other planets or building [[space habitat]]s suitable for human habitation, humans are modified (for example via [[genetic engineering]]) to be able to thrive in the existing environment. The term was coined by [[science fiction author]] [[James Blish]], who wrote a series of short stories based on the idea (collected in the anthology ''[[James Blish#The Seedling Stars (Pantropy)|The Seedling Stars]]'').\n\n==Fictional depictions==\n\n* 1930\u2014In the science fiction [[novel]] ''[[Last and First Men]]'' by [[Olaf Stapledon]], when humanity migrates from [[Earth]] to [[Venus]] and later from Venus to [[Neptune]], human beings are [[Genetic engineering|genetically engineered]] to fit the new environments in which they will be living.\n* 1944\u2014One of the first science fiction stories about pantropy (the word had not yet been coined) was the [[short story]] \"Desertion,\" by [[Clifford D. Simak]], which appeared in the November 1944 ''[[Astounding Science Fiction]]''. In this story, human colonists living in a [[domed city]] on the planet [[Jupiter]] are put through a biological converter that converts their bodies into the form of the indigenous Jovian lifeform called the \"Lopers.\"  The head director of the domed colony, Kent Fowler, wondering why none of those biologically converted ever come back, goes into the biological converter himself with his [[dog]] and finds that the reason they never come back is that the Lopers have [[brain]]s and [[sense]]s so much in advance of humans that they don't want to come back.  He also finds that he is able to completely accurately [[telepathy|telepathically communicate]] with his dog Towser (whose intelligence has also greatly increased) after going through the converter.  He himself decides not to go back.<ref>Conklin, Groff (editor) ''[[Big Book of Science Fiction]]'' New York:1950 Crown Publishers \"Desertion,\" by [[Clifford D. Simak]] Pages 413-423</ref> The story was incorporated into the novel ''[[City (novel)|City]]'' (1952).\n* 1957\u2014''[[James Blish#The Seedling Stars (Pantropy)|The Seedling Stars]]'', by [[James Blish]], a collection of science fiction stories about pantropy. The best-known of these is \"[[Surface Tension (short story)|Surface Tension]]\", often anthologized in its original 1952 standalone version.\n* 1976\u2014[[Frederik Pohl]]'s novel ''[[Man Plus]]'' is a story about the transformation of a human into a hybrid/[[cyborg]] in order to allow him to live comfortably on [[Mars]].  In the sequel, ''[[Mars Plus]]'', some colonists opt for an intermediate existence, and are known as [[Creole peoples|Creoles]].\n* 1981-1983\u2014[[Jack L. Chalker]]'s ''[[Four Lords of the Diamond]]'' series describes the changes in personality that result from physical changes caused by a symbiotic microorganism that adapts humans into a form that can survive on each of  four different planets.\n* 1989-1997\u2014''[[Dan Simmons]]''' ''[[Hyperion Cantos]]'' is a series of four books featuring a faction known as the Ousters, which use pantropy as a way of living in harmony with nature and space.\n* 2000\u2014[[Stephen Baxter (author)|Stephen Baxter]]'s novels repeatedly deal with pantropy as an approach to the far future of the human species.\n* 2002\u2014[[Timothy Zahn]]'s novel Manta's Gift features technology capable of transmitting human consciousness to an alien body.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hromic |first1=Alma |title=The SF Site Featured Review: Manta's Gift |url=https://www.sfsite.com/02a/ma145.htm |accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n* 2009\u2014[[James Cameron]]'s film ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'' is a somewhat different take on pantropy.\n* 2011\u2014In the manga ''[[Terra Formars]]'', humans sent to Mars undergo genetic modification to inherit the characteristics of other organisms.\n* 2014\u2014In the video game ''[[Civilization: Beyond Earth]]'', the Harmony affinity represents pantropy.''\n\n==References==\n\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Science fiction themes]]\n[[Category:Space colonization]]\n[[Category:Transhumanism]]\n", "name_user": "Tamfang", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFictional depictions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pantropy"}
{"title_page": "China-Thailand meme war", "text_new": "The '''China-Thailand meme war''' refers to an online incident between [[netizens]] in [[mainland China]], [[Thailand]] and other regions in [[Southeast Asia]] that occurred in April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-china-internet-idUSKCN21W11P|title=Insta-star wars: China tensions in Southeast Asia flare online|date=April 14, 2020|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref>\n\nThe cause of the incident was that some mainland Chinese netizens thought that Weeraya, the girlfriend of Thai actor [[Vachirawit Chiva-aree]] (aka \"Bright\") (known on Twitter as \"nnevvy\"), made [[Taiwan independence]] remarks online, that Bright and liked online rumors about the origin of [[SARS-CoV-2]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/china-thailand-coronavirus-social-media-war-escalates-200414121313775.html|title=China-Thailand coronavirus social media war escalates|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> that Bright reposted an article about the [[2019-20 Hong Kong protests]]. The two were accused of \"insulting China\" by mainland Chinese netizens, and asked to apologized publicly. \n\nThe behavior of mainland Chinese netizens caused dissatisfaction among Thai netizens, and the two sides immediately engaged in a scolding battle (meme war). In the process, they also attracted netizens from Hong Kong, Taiwan and some Southeast Asian countries such as Vietnam and the Philippines to support the Thai side.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3916050|title=Photo of the Day: Taiwan joins Eight-Nation A...|first=|last=|website=Taiwan News}}</ref> The incident later rose to affect [[foreign relations]] between the two countries, and both Chinese and Thai officials responded to the incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/asia/nnevvy-china-taiwan-twitter-intl-hnk/index.html|title=A Chinese troll campaign is inadvertently showing how censorship limits political thought|first=James |last=Griffiths|website=CNN}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nOn April 11, 2020, some mainland Chinese netizens found online conversations between Thai actor [[Vachirawit Chiva-aree]] (Bright) and online celebrity girlfriend Weeraya (Twitter name \"nnevvy\") from two years ago. In the conversations, when Weeraya was travelling to [[Taiwan]] in 2018, Bright commented on a photo and said \"Looks like a Chinese girl\". Weeraya replied \"What?\" Other netizens left a message and asked, \"What style is this today?\" Weeraya replied, \"Taiwanese girl.\" Some mainland Chinese netizens interpreted this dialogue as Weeraya supporting [[Taiwanese independence]]. Some mainland Chinese netizens also mentioned that Weeraya once tweeted alternative theories around the origin of [[SARS-CoV-2]], and that Bright also praised the tweet. In addition, Bright had also reposted an article about the [[2019 Hong Kong extradition bill]] that sparked the [[2019-20 Hong Kong protests]]. Since the article listed [[Hong Kong]] as a country, Bright publicly apologized to mainland Chinese netizens. Afterwards, mainland Chinese netizens brigaded Weeraya's Twitter and Instagram accounts with messages, accusing them of \"humiliating China\" and demanding an apology. The hashtag #\u6cf0\u570b\u8fb1\u83ef (#ThailandInsultsChina) was promoted onto [[Weibo]]'s top searches list, and the Thai TV series [[2gether: The Series (Thai TV series)]] was brigaded with negative comments on [[Douban]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/04/17/nnevvy-bright-firewall-thailand-china-online-army/|title=Thais Show How to Beat China\u2019s Online Army|first=Lauren|last=Teixeira}}</ref>\n\n==Incident==\nThai netizens felt dissatisfied at the behavior of mainland Chinese netizens, and immediately went to Bright and Weeraya\u2019s social media accounts to support the two.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscats.org/?p=23988|title=PROOF China Covered Up Coronavirus &#124; Thai-China Meme War \u2013 Newscats Hasslefree Allsort}}</ref>\n\nNetizens from both [[China]] and [[Thailand]] immediately launched a scolding battle (meme war). Thai netizens questioned why China did not apologize for the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]], and said \"Taiwan is an independent country\", questioning why [[mainland Chinese]] citizens needed a [[visa]] to visit [[Taiwan]], but [[Thai]] citizens did not need a visa to go to [[Pattaya]]. During the dispute, netizens from the [[Japan]], [[Philippines]], [[Malaysia]], [[South Korea]], [[India]], [[Taiwan]], and [[Hong Kong]] also joined the war in solidarity with the Thai side, and the #nnevvy hashtag was added to [[Twitter]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/netizens-milktea-04152020142015.html|title=Milk Tea Alliance Takes on China's Little Pinks in Meme War|website=Radio Free Asia}}</ref>\n\nThe focus of the scolding war then gradually shifted to topics such as the leaders of [[China]] and [[Thailand]], food culture and historical events in the two places. Mainland Chinese netizens insulted the Thai king [[Rama X]] and asked \"Where are your kings going?\". Thai netizens asked the mainland Chinese netizens to \"speak again\", \"speak louder\" and responded with \"we are also looking for him, thank you for your concern!\". Mainland Chinese netizens also insulted Thai netizens with \"nmsl\" (\"Your mother is dead\" in Chinese [[pinyin]]) and similar phrases. Thai netizens responded, \"we have 20 mothers\" (a reference to [[Rama X]]'s retreat in Paris during the coronavirus pandemic) and ridiculed the many Thai queen palaces. Mainland Chinese netizens called Thailand's prime minister \"stupid\" and government \"very trash\", Thai netizens expressed their agreement and asked the other party to \"speak louder.\" Thai netizens accused Chinese state leader [[Xi Jinping]] for his policies. They also satirized China\u2019s lack of freedom and expressed their support for Taiwan and Hong Kong\u2019s independence. On the topic of food culture, mainland Chinese netizens said that Thai food is not appetizing, but Thai netizens responded \"because you all eat bats\". Since Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Thailand all have unique and famous [[Milk tea]]s, the three countries started calling each other \"milk tea\" in solidarity. In addition, mainland Chinese netizens were noted for being only able to use [[swear words]] such as \"NMSL\" and \"CNMB\" (\"fuck your mother's cunt\"). The Thai netizens counterattacked that the netizens were not \"[[Chinese]]\" but \"Nmslese\" (\"your mother is dead\" people). Thai netizens also used \"June 4th\", \"[[Tiananmen Incident]]\", \"[[1989]]\" and other sensitive keywords in mainland China to attack the other side. Mainland Chinese netizens countered with the [[Thammasat University massacre]] in 1976, but Thai netizens asked the other side to \"speak louder\", and responded that \"unlike some countries, our government will not hide the truth from people\" and \"are you ready to face the incidents of 1989?\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://supchina.com/2020/04/13/chinese-nationalists-and-thai-meme-creators-face-off-on-twitter/|title=Chinese nationalists and Thai meme-creators face off on Twitter|author=Luiz|date=April 13, 2020|website=SupChina}}</ref>\n\n[[Joshua Wong]], a Hong Kong democracy activist, also vocally supported the \"Milk Tea Alliance\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joshuawongcf/status/1249254158538072064|title=1. Hong Kong stand with our freedom-loving friends in Thailand against Chinese bullying! #nnevvypic.twitter.com/Pm4KFhVGXr|first=Joshua |last=Wong|date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> due to the [[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]] was used by democracy activists in [[Hong Kong]], including Joshua Wong, as a platform to [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|protest]], including flags containing protest slogans such as \u201c[[Liberate Hong Kong, revolution of our time]]\u201d and funeral photographs of [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|general secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] as part of the virtual protests. In reaction, the game has been removed and banned from online stores in China such as [[Taobao]] where it had been available on the [[grey market]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nintendo-china-animalcrossing/nintendo-game-pulled-from-chinese-platforms-after-hong-kong-protest-idUSKCN21S11F |title=Nintendo game pulled from Chinese platforms after Hong Kong protest |website=Reuters|date=April 10, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-52269671 | title = Animal Crossing removed from sale in China and banned amid Hong Kong protests | date = April 13, 2020 | accessdate=  April 13, 2020 | work =[[BBC]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hongkongfp.com/2020/04/15/activist-joshua-wong-trolls-chinese-censors-after-gamers-blame-him-for-animal-crossing-ban/ |title=Activist Joshua Wong \u2018trolls\u2019 Chinese censors after gamers blame him for Animal Crossing ban |website=[[Hong Kong Free Press]] |first=Rachel |last=Wong |date=April 15, 2020 |accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Official government responses==\nOn April 14, 2020, the Chinese Embassy in Thailand responded to the meme war, declaring that the one-China principle is a long-standing position of the Thai government and the Thai people. They stated that individual netizens will not succeed in creating hostilities between the two countries, that [[China\u2013Thailand relations]] have a long history, that \"China and Thailand are one country\", and that the two countries' friendship will be stronger as a result of the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/ChineseEmbassyinBangkok/posts/2942654555781330|title=Chinese Embassy Bangkok \u0e2a\u0e16\u0e32\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e2d\u0e31\u0e04\u0e23\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e17\u0e39\u0e15\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e18\u0e32\u0e23\u0e13\u0e23\u0e31\u0e10\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e19\u0e08\u0e35\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e08\u0e33\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e17\u0e28\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:2020 in internet culture]]\n", "text_old": "The '''China-Thailand meme war''' refers to an online incident between [[netizens]] in [[mainland China]], [[Thailand]] and other regions in [[Southeast Asia]] that occurred in April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-china-internet-idUSKCN21W11P|title=Insta-star wars: China tensions in Southeast Asia flare online|date=April 14, 2020|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref>\n\nThe cause of the incident was that some mainland Chinese netizens thought that Weeraya, the girlfriend of Thai actor [[Vachirawit Chiva-aree]] (aka \"Bright\") (known on Twitter as \"nnevvy\"), made [[Taiwan independence]] remarks online, that Bright and liked online rumors about the origin of [[SARS-CoV-2]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/china-thailand-coronavirus-social-media-war-escalates-200414121313775.html|title=China-Thailand coronavirus social media war escalates|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> that Bright reposted an article about the [[2019-20 Hong Kong protests]]. The two were accused of \"insulting China\" by mainland Chinese netizens, and asked to apologized publicly. \n\nThe behavior of mainland Chinese netizens caused dissatisfaction among Thai netizens, and the two sides immediately engaged in a scolding battle (meme war). In the process, they also attracted netizens from Hong Kong, Taiwan and some Southeast Asian countries such as Vietnam and the Philippines to support the Thai side.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3916050|title=Photo of the Day: Taiwan joins Eight-Nation A...|first=Taiwan|last=News|website=Taiwan News}}</ref> The incident later rose to affect [[foreign relations]] between the two countries, and both Chinese and Thai officials responded to the incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/14/asia/nnevvy-china-taiwan-twitter-intl-hnk/index.html|title=A Chinese troll campaign is inadvertently showing how censorship limits political thought|first=Analysis by James Griffiths|last=CNN|website=CNN}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nOn April 11, 2020, some mainland Chinese netizens found online conversations between Thai actor [[Vachirawit Chiva-aree]] (Bright) and online celebrity girlfriend Weeraya (Twitter name \"nnevvy\") from two years ago. In the conversations, when Weeraya was travelling to [[Taiwan]] in 2018, Bright commented on a photo and said \"Looks like a Chinese girl\". Weeraya replied \"What?\" Other netizens left a message and asked, \"What style is this today?\" Weeraya replied, \"Taiwanese girl.\" Some mainland Chinese netizens interpreted this dialogue as Weeraya supporting [[Taiwanese independence]]. Some mainland Chinese netizens also mentioned that Weeraya once tweeted alternative theories around the origin of [[SARS-CoV-2]], and that Bright also praised the tweet. In addition, Bright had also reposted an article about the [[2019 Hong Kong extradition bill]] that sparked the [[2019-20 Hong Kong protests]]. Since the article listed [[Hong Kong]] as a country, Bright publicly apologized to mainland Chinese netizens. Afterwards, mainland Chinese netizens brigaded Weeraya's Twitter and Instagram accounts with messages, accusing them of \"humiliating China\" and demanding an apology. The hashtag #\u6cf0\u570b\u8fb1\u83ef (#ThailandInsultsChina) was promoted onto [[Weibo]]'s top searches list, and the Thai TV series [[2gether: The Series (Thai TV series)]] was brigaded with negative comments on [[Douban]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/04/17/nnevvy-bright-firewall-thailand-china-online-army/|title=Thais Show How to Beat China\u2019s Online Army|first=Lauren|last=Teixeira}}</ref>\n\n==Incident==\nThai netizens felt dissatisfied at the behavior of mainland Chinese netizens, and immediately went to Bright and Weeraya\u2019s social media accounts to support the two.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newscats.org/?p=23988|title=PROOF China Covered Up Coronavirus &#124; Thai-China Meme War \u2013 Newscats Hasslefree Allsort}}</ref>\n\nNetizens from both [[China]] and [[Thailand]] immediately launched a scolding battle (meme war). Thai netizens questioned why China did not apologize for the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]], and said \"Taiwan is an independent country\", questioning why [[mainland Chinese]] citizens needed a [[visa]] to visit [[Taiwan]], but [[Thai]] citizens did not need a visa to go to [[Pattaya]]. During the dispute, netizens from the [[Japan]], [[Philippines]], [[Malaysia]], [[South Korea]], [[India]], [[Taiwan]], and [[Hong Kong]] also joined the war in solidarity with the Thai side, and the #nnevvy hashtag was added to [[Twitter]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rfa.org/english/news/china/netizens-milktea-04152020142015.html|title=Milk Tea Alliance Takes on China's Little Pinks in Meme War|website=Radio Free Asia}}</ref>\n\nThe focus of the scolding war then gradually shifted to topics such as the leaders of [[China]] and [[Thailand]], food culture and historical events in the two places. Mainland Chinese netizens insulted the Thai king [[Rama X]] and asked \"Where are your kings going?\". Thai netizens asked the mainland Chinese netizens to \"speak again\", \"speak louder\" and responded with \"we are also looking for him, thank you for your concern!\". Mainland Chinese netizens also insulted Thai netizens with \"nmsl\" (\"Your mother is dead\" in Chinese [[pinyin]]) and similar phrases. Thai netizens responded, \"we have 20 mothers\" (a reference to [[Rama X]]'s retreat in Paris during the coronavirus pandemic) and ridiculed the many Thai queen palaces. Mainland Chinese netizens called Thailand's prime minister \"stupid\" and government \"very trash\", Thai netizens expressed their agreement and asked the other party to \"speak louder.\" Thai netizens accused Chinese state leader [[Xi Jinping]] for his policies. They also satirized China\u2019s lack of freedom and expressed their support for Taiwan and Hong Kong\u2019s independence. On the topic of food culture, mainland Chinese netizens said that Thai food is not appetizing, but Thai netizens responded \"because you all eat bats\". Since Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Thailand all have unique and famous [[Milk tea]]s, the three countries started calling each other \"milk tea\" in solidarity. In addition, mainland Chinese netizens were noted for being only able to use [[swear words]] such as \"NMSL\" and \"CNMB\" (\"fuck your mother's cunt\"). The Thai netizens counterattacked that the netizens were not \"[[Chinese]]\" but \"Nmslese\" (\"your mother is dead\" people). Thai netizens also used \"June 4th\", \"[[Tiananmen Incident]]\", \"[[1989]]\" and other sensitive keywords in mainland China to attack the other side. Mainland Chinese netizens countered with the [[Thammasat University massacre]] in 1976, but Thai netizens asked the other side to \"speak louder\", and responded that \"unlike some countries, our government will not hide the truth from people\" and \"are you ready to face the incidents of 1989?\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://supchina.com/2020/04/13/chinese-nationalists-and-thai-meme-creators-face-off-on-twitter/|title=Chinese nationalists and Thai meme-creators face off on Twitter|first1=Luiz|last1=April 14|first2=2020 at 2:07 am|last2=Reply|date=April 13, 2020|website=SupChina}}</ref>\n\n[[Joshua Wong]], a Hong Kong democracy activist, also vocally supported the \"Milk Tea Alliance\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joshuawongcf/status/1249254158538072064|title=1. Hong Kong stand with our freedom-loving friends in Thailand against Chinese bullying! #nnevvypic.twitter.com/Pm4KFhVGXr|first=Joshua Wong|last=\u9ec3\u4e4b\u92d2  \ud83d\ude37|date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> due to the [[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]] was used by democracy activists in [[Hong Kong]], including Joshua Wong, as a platform to [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|protest]], including flags containing protest slogans such as \u201c[[Liberate Hong Kong, revolution of our time]]\u201d and funeral photographs of [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|general secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] as part of the virtual protests. In reaction, the game has been removed and banned from online stores in China such as [[Taobao]] where it had been available on the [[grey market]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nintendo-china-animalcrossing/nintendo-game-pulled-from-chinese-platforms-after-hong-kong-protest-idUSKCN21S11F |title=Nintendo game pulled from Chinese platforms after Hong Kong protest |website=Reuters|date=April 10, 2020 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-52269671 | title = Animal Crossing removed from sale in China and banned amid Hong Kong protests | date = April 13, 2020 | accessdate=  April 13, 2020 | work =[[BBC]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hongkongfp.com/2020/04/15/activist-joshua-wong-trolls-chinese-censors-after-gamers-blame-him-for-animal-crossing-ban/ |title=Activist Joshua Wong \u2018trolls\u2019 Chinese censors after gamers blame him for Animal Crossing ban |website=[[Hong Kong Free Press]] |first=Rachel |last=Wong |date=April 15, 2020 |accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Official government responses==\nOn April 14, 2020, the Chinese Embassy in Thailand responded to the meme war, declaring that the one-China principle is a long-standing position of the Thai government and the Thai people. They stated that individual netizens will not succeed in creating hostilities between the two countries, that [[China\u2013Thailand relations]] have a long history, that \"China and Thailand are one country\", and that the two countries' friendship will be stronger as a result of the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/ChineseEmbassyinBangkok/posts/2942654555781330|title=Chinese Embassy Bangkok \u0e2a\u0e16\u0e32\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2d\u0e01\u0e2d\u0e31\u0e04\u0e23\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e17\u0e39\u0e15\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e18\u0e32\u0e23\u0e13\u0e23\u0e31\u0e10\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e19\u0e08\u0e35\u0e19\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e08\u0e33\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e17\u0e28\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:2020 in internet culture]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed cite errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/China-Thailand_meme_war"}
