{"title_page": "LGBT rights in Israel", "text_new": "{{short description|Rights of lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender people in Israel}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox LGBT rights\n| location_header              = [[Israel]]\n| image                        = Israel (orthographic projection) with disputed territories.svg\n| legal_status                 = Legal since 1988 (but no record of enforcement of \"buggery\" law before this, and the Attorney General declared that laws against homosexuality would not be enforced in 1963)\n| gender_identity_expression   = Legal sex change possible\n| recognition_of_relationships = [[Unregistered cohabitation in Israel|Unregistered cohabitation since 1994]];<br />[[Recognition of same-sex unions in Israel|Same-sex marriages performed outside of Israel recognized since 2006]]\n| recognition_of_relationships_restrictions = Only marriages sanctioned by the religious authorities may be performed within Israel (this also applies to opposite-sex couples who are not eligible for religious weddings)\n| adoption                     = Yes, same-sex couples allowed to adopt\n| military                     = [[Sexual orientation and gender identity in the Israeli military|LGBT people allowed to serve openly]]\n| discrimination_protections   = Sexual orientation protection in employment and other services; both sexual orientation and gender identity protections in schools ([[#Discrimination protections|see below]])\n}}\n\n'''Lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) rights in Israel''' are the most developed in the [[Middle East]], and among the most tolerant in [[Asia]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/love-sex/taboo-tolerance/the-five-most-improved-places-for-gay-tolerance-932635.html | location=London | work=The Independent | title=The five most improved places for gay tolerance | date=17 September 2008}}</ref> Although same-sex sexual activity was legalized in 1988, the former law against sodomy had not been enforced since a court decision in 1963. [[Israel]] became the first country in Asia to recognize [[Unregistered cohabitation in Israel|unregistered cohabitation]] between same-sex couples, making it the first country in Asia to recognize same-sex unions in any capacity. Although [[Same-sex marriage in Israel|same-sex marriages]] are not performed in the country, Israel recognizes same-sex marriages performed elsewhere. Discrimination on the grounds of sexual orientation was prohibited in 1992. Same-sex couples are allowed to jointly adopt, following a landmark court decision in 2008. Previously, stepchild adoption as well limited co-guardianship rights for non-biological parents was permitted. [[LGBT]] people are also allowed to serve [[Coming out|openly]] in the military.\n\n[[Tel Aviv]] has frequently been referred to by publishers as one of the most gay-friendly cities in the world,<ref>\"The world's most gay-friendly places\". Calgary Herald. 29 June 2011.</ref> famous for its annual [[Tel Aviv Pride|Pride Parade]] and gay beach,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/07/02/dispatch-gay-tel-aviv/?_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Anthony | last=Grant | title=Dispatch | date=2 July 2010}}</ref> earning it the nickname \"the gay capital of the Middle East\" by ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'' magazine.<ref>James Kirchick. Out. [http://www.out.com/entertainment/2007/07/29/was-arafat-gay Was Arafat Gay?]</ref> According to LGBT travelers, it was ranked as the best gay city in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/LifeStyle/Tel-Aviv-named-worlds-best-gay-city-for-2011|title=Tel Aviv named 'world's best gay city' for 2011|work=The Jerusalem Post - JPost.com}}</ref> despite reports of some LGBT violence during the 2000s,<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/two-killed-in-shooting-at-tel-aviv-gay-center-1.281193|title=Two killed in shooting at Tel Aviv gay center|author=Haaretz Service and News Agencies|date=1 August 2009|work=Haaretz.com}}</ref> which were criticized by Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] and President [[Shimon Peres]]. A monument dedicated to the [[Persecution of homosexuals in Nazi Germany and the Holocaust|gay victims of the Holocaust]] was erected in Tel Aviv in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |date=10 January 2014 |title=Tel Aviv unveils first memorial to gay Holocaust victims |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-25687190 |newspaper=BBC News |accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref> [[Opinion poll]]s have found that a majority of Israelis support the legalization of same-sex marriage,<ref>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/most-israelis-favor-same-sex-marriage-but-half-of-mks-mum-on-issue/ Most Israelis favor same-sex marriage, but half of MKs mum on issue]</ref> as well as adoption and surrogacy rights for same-sex couples.<ref name=\"ynetnews\"/>\n\n==Law==\n\n===Same-sex sexual activity===\nThe State of Israel inherited the ''[[Buggery Act]] of 1533'' as part of the British Mandate's legal code. There is no known record that it was ever enforced against homosexual acts that took place between consenting adults in private. In certain cases, defendants were found guilty of \"sodomy\" (which according to Israeli law included [[oral sex]] as well), apparently by way of plea bargains: Those defendants had been indicted for more serious sexual offences. It was also used as \"[[Aggravation (law)|aggravating circumstances]]\" for other sexual offences. There were also several cases of soldiers tried for homosexual acts in military courts. [[Attorney General of Israel|The Attorney General]] decided in the early 1960s, and the [[Supreme Court of Israel|Israeli Supreme Court]] ruled in 1963, that the law should not be applied to acts between consenting adults in private. The ban on consensual same-sex sexual acts was formally repealed by the National Legislative Assembly ([[Knesset]]) in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tau.ac.il/law/aeyalgross/Danilowitz.htm |title=Supreme Court of Israel |publisher=Tau.ac.il |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> The [[age of consent]] for both homosexual and heterosexual acts is 16 years of age.\n\n===Recognition of same-sex relationships===\n{{Main|Unregistered cohabitation in Israel|Recognition of same-sex unions in Israel}}\n[[File:Hayovel gay 3.JPG|thumb|Signs supporting same-sex marriage in [[Herzliya]], 2012]]\nBetween 1994 and 2007, numerous rights were granted to Israeli same-sex couples.<ref>[http://www.acri.org.il/en/2009/02/15/protecting-and-promoting-lgbt-rights-in-israel/ Protecting and Promoting LGBT Rights in Israel]</ref>\n\nSame-sex marriage cannot legally be performed in Israel. Israeli law allows same-sex marriages performed elsewhere to be registered, but not recognized based upon a 2006 Israeli Supreme Court decision which stated \"Before we conclude, let us reemphasize what it is that we are deciding today, and what it is that we are not deciding today. We are deciding that within the context of the status of the population registry as a recorder of statistics, the registration official should register in the population register what is implied by the public certificate that is presented to him by the petitioners, according to which the petitioners are married and in view of the role of the registration official as a collector of statistical material for the purpose of managing the registry...We are not deciding that marriage between persons of the same sex is recognized in Israel; we are not recognizing a new status of such marriages; we are not adopting any position with regard to recognition in Israel of marriages between persons of the same sex that take place outside Israel (whether between Israeli residents or between persons who are not Israeli residents)\"<ref name=\"elyon1.court.gov.il\">{{cite web |url=http://elyon1.court.gov.il/files_eng/05/450/030/a09/05030450.a09.htm |title=Judgement of the Supreme Court sitting as the High Court of Justice }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Civil marriage]] doesn't exist in Israel for heterosexual couples either (except where both heterosexual spouses do not belong to any of the recognized religious communities in the country),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/136544|title=Civil Marriage for Non-Jews|work=Arutz Sheva}}</ref> and therefore only a marriage sanctioned by the small number of officially recognized religious authorities can take place within Israel. (This restriction forces not only same-sex couples, but also all mixed-religion heterosexual couples and any person who wishes a non-religious marriage, to marry outside the country.)\n\nThe State of Israel allows foreign partners of its homosexual [[citizenry]] to receive residency permits. The Civil Service Commission extends spousal benefits and pensions to the partners of homosexual employees. The Israeli State Attorney's Office has extended the spousal exemption from property-transfer taxes to same-sex couples. Israel's Attorney General has granted legal recognition to same-sex couples in financial and other business matters. [[Attorney General]] [[Meni Mazuz]] said the couples will be treated the same as common-law spouses, recognizing them as legal units for tax, real estate, and financial purposes. Mazuz made his decision by refusing to appeal a district court ruling in an inheritance case that recognized the legality of a same-sex union, his office said in a statement. Mazuz did differentiate, however, between recognizing same-sex unions for financial and practical purposes, as he did, and changing the law to officially sanction the unions, which would be a matter for Parliament, according to the statement.\n\nThe city of [[Tel Aviv]] recognizes unmarried couples, including gays and lesbians, as family units and grants them discounts for [[municipal services]]. Under the bylaw, unmarried couples qualify for the same discounts on daycare and the use of swimming pools, sports facilities, and other city-sponsored activities that married couples enjoy. On 29 January 2007, following a Supreme Court ruling ordering them to do so, Jerusalem registered its first same-sex couple, Avi and Binyamin Rose.<ref>{{cite web |last=Eglash |first=Ruth |url=http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1167467842994&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull |title=Jerusalem registers its first gay couple &#124; Israel &#124; Jerusalem Post |publisher=Fr.jpost.com |date=30 January 2007 |accessdate=2011-06-14 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Israel's marriage law was amended with the passage of the ''Civil Union Law for Citizens with no Religious Affiliation, 2010'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Julie|first1=Dayer|title=\u05d2\u05df \u05d4\u05e8\u05de\u05d5\u05d6\u05d5 \u05d0\u05d5\u05dc\u05dd (\u05d0\u05d5\u05dc\u05de\u05d5\u05ea) \u05d0\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9\u05e2\u05d9\u05df, \u05d9\u05d5\u05e7\u05e8\u05ea\u05d9 (\u05d9\u05d5\u05e7\u05e8\u05ea\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd) \u05d1\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05e9\u05dc\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05de\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9\u05e2\u05d9\u05df \u05d1\u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6 \u05d4\u05d0\u05e8\u05e5, \u05d2\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d0\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6|url=http://www.hermozo.co.il|website=\u05d4\u05e8\u05de\u05d5\u05d6\u05d5|publisher=\u05d0\u05d5\u05dc\u05dd \u05d0\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6|accessdate=21 September 2016|language=he-IL|date=4 March 2013}}</ref> allowing an opposite-sex couple to form a [[civil union]] in Israel if they are both registered as officially not belonging to any religion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myjewishlearning.com/israel/Contemporary_Life/Society_and_Religious_Issues/Freedom_of_Religion/civil_marriage_in_israel.shtml|title=Civil Marriage in Israel|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/review/data/eng/law/kns18_CivilUnion_eng.pdf Civil Union Law for Citizens with no Religious Affiliation, 2010]</ref>\n\nThere have been 5 failed legislative attempts in the [[Knesset]] to recognise same-sex unions. The first attempt was a civil marriage bill, which included provisions for same-sex marriages, introduced by [[Meretz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontopmag.com/article/3320/Israeli_Knesset_To_Consider_Gay_Marriage|title=Israeli Knesset To Consider Gay Marriage|website=On Top Magazine}}</ref> The bill was rejected in May 2012 in a 39 to 11 vote, with 70 not attending.<ref name=\"bill\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/05/16/israeli-parliament-rejects-gay-and-inter-faith-civil-marriage-bill/|title=Israeli parliament rejects gay and inter-faith civil marriage bill|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jpost.com/DiplomacyAndPolitics/Article.aspx?id=270221 |author=Harkov, Lahav |title=Knesset rejects marriage equality bill |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post |date=16 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522013505/http://www.jpost.com/DiplomacyAndPolitics/Article.aspx?id=270221 |archivedate=22 May 2012 }}</ref> The second and third attempts were two similar bills that would have provided for [[civil union]]s in Israel for both opposite-sex and same-sex couples; one introduced by [[Hatnuah]],<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/livni-to-sponsor-groundbreaking-knesset-bill-allowing-same-sex-civil-partnership.premium-1.529818|title=Israeli Ministers Set to Vote on Bill Allowing Same-sex Civil Unions|journal=Haaretz|first=Jonathan|last=Lis|date=16 June 2013|via=Haaretz}}</ref> and the other by [[Yesh Atid]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/30/world/middleeast/centrist-party-in-israel-introduces-civil-union-bill.html |author=Rudoren, Jodi |title=Centrist Party in Israel Introduces Civil Union Measure |journal=The New York Times |date=29 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper|author1=JODI RUDOREN|title=Centrist Party in Israel Introduces Civil Union Measure|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/30/world/middleeast/centrist-party-in-israel-introduces-civil-union-bill.html|journal=The New York Times|accessdate=20 January 2015|date=29 October 2013}}</ref> At the same time, [[Meretz]] proposed a civil marriage bill, which included provisions for same-sex marriages. On 8 July 2015, the Knesset rejected the [[Meretz]] and [[Yesh Atid]] bills, in a 39-50 vote,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Politics-And-Diplomacy/Knesset-shoots-down-civil-union-bills-408373 |title=Knesset shoots down civil union bills |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post |date=8 July 2015}}</ref> while Hatnuah's bill was rejected on 22 February 2016 in a 40-47 vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/day-after-marking-lgbt-rights-knesset-nixes-5-gender-equality-bills/ |author=Newman, Marissa |title=Day after marking LGBT rights, Knesset nixes 5 gender equality bills |publisher=The News of Israel |date=24 February 2016}}</ref> In June 2018, the Knesset rejected a same-sex marriage bill introduced by [[The Zionist Union]]. The bill failed by just three votes, 39-42.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishpress.com/news/breaking-news/gay-marriage-law-fails-on-3-votes-says-shaffir/2018/06/08/|title=Gay Marriage Law Fails on 3 Votes, Says Shaffir|publisher=Jewish Press|date=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5284391,00.html|title=PM brags about gay community, but Knesset rejects same-sex civil union bill|work=Ynetnews|first1=Shahar|last1=Hay|first2=Alexandra|last2=Lukash|first3=Nir|last3=Cohen|date=11 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/247165|title=Arab MKs skip vote on recognizing gay marriage|work=Israel National News|last=Baruch|first=Hezki|date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Adoption and parenting===\n[[LGBT adoption|Adoption by LGBT parents]] had only been permitted in certain restricted situations, notably when a previous connection exists between the adopting parent and the child, such as being a family member or a foster child. On 10 January 2005, the [[Supreme Court of Israel|Supreme Court]] ruled that a lesbian couple is able to legally [[Adoption|adopt]] each other's children. During the past 15 years that Tal and Avital Jarus-Hakak had lived together, they had a total of three children. The couple petitioned the Tel Aviv Family Court for the right to formally adopt each other's children in 1997, but the request was rejected because Israel's adoption law had no provisions for same-sex couples. The couple appealed. While they failed to get a favorable ruling in the Tel Aviv District Court, the Supreme Court accepted the case. Citing Article 25 of the ''Adoption of Children Law of 1981'' ({{lang-he|\u05d7\u05d5\u05e7 \u05d0\u05d9\u05de\u05d5\u05e5 \u05d9\u05dc\u05d3\u05d9\u05dd, \u05ea\u05e9\u05de\"\u05d0-1981}}; [[Arabic]]: {{lang|ar|\u0642\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u062a\u0628\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0637\u0641\u0627\u0644 1981}}), the Jarus-Hakaks argued that the law allows for \"special circumstances\" for adoption when it is for the good of the child, even if the child's parents are still alive. The only condition is that the person seeking to adopt be single. The couple argued that since the state does not recognize same-sex marriage, they are single by law. They added that adoption was in the best interest of the children if one of their natural mothers should die. The Supreme Court of Israel agreed, ruling 7\u20132 in favor of the couple. Following the Supreme Court ruling, the couple was allowed to adopt each other's biological children on 12 February 2006. Before that, the gay partner of the parent was granted guardianship over their partner's children. Lesbian couples can also legally gain access to IVF and assisted insemination.\n\nIn February 2008, a court in [[Israel]] ruled that same-sex couples are now permitted to adopt a child even if that child is not biologically related to either parent.<ref name=\"Haaretz\">[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/953097.html AG okays wider adoption rights for same-sex couples], By Yuval Yoaz, 12 February 2008.</ref> This marked a watershed in granting [[Egalitarianism|equal rights]] to all [[gay]] people in Israel.<ref name=\"Haaretz\" /> [[isRealli]], the official blog of the State of Israel, frequently publishes updates on gay adoption news in Israel. The site also has a complete timeline of [[LGBT Rights|gay rights]] milestones in Israel. On 10 March 2009, the Tel Aviv Family Court ruled that former Knesset member [[Uzi Even]] and his partner, Amit Kama, could legally adopt their 30-year-old foster son, Yossi, making them the first same-sex male couple in Israel whose right of adoption was legally acknowledged.<ref name=edelman>{{Cite news | last = Edelman | first = Ofra | title = Gay couple wins right to adopt foster son | work = Haaretz | accessdate = 2009-03-11 | date = 11 March 2009 | url = http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1070060.html}}</ref> However, same-sex couples could only adopt children heterosexual couples did not want.\n\nOn 28 January 2014, the Israel High Court of Justice ruled in favor of a May 2013 modification by Israel Attorney General Yehuda Weinstein and stated that same-sex couples in Israel could easily adopt through [[surrogacy]] so long as the biological parent in the same-sex relationship was willing to take a paternity test or present highly convincing alternative medical and legal evidence of paternity.<ref name=surrogateisrael>[http://www.jpost.com/National-News/High-Court-orders-Israel-to-recognize-gay-adoption-of-child-born-through-surrogacy-339655 HIGH COURT ORDERS ISRAEL TO RECOGNIZE GAY ADOPTION OF CHILD BORN THROUGH SURROGACY]</ref> Prior to the 2013 modification, both a paternity test by the biological parent and a lengthy legal process by the non-biological parent were required in order for a joint adoption to take place for same-sex couples participating in surrogacy.<ref name=surrogateisrael /> This ruling was further enhanced in August 2016 when the Tel Aviv Family Court ruled that Israeli same-sex couples could adopt through surrogacy from individuals residing in either Israel or from other countries.<ref name=surroisrael>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Court-Gay-adoption-of-child-born-through-surrogacy-possible-without-paternity-test-463681 COURT: GAY ADOPTION OF CHILD BORN THROUGH SURROGACY POSSIBLE WITHOUT PATERNITY TEST]</ref>\n\nIn late August 2017, the Israeli Government announced that it no longer opposes same-sex adoption and that new criteria for adoption would be enacted. Under the new criteria, the potential parents can legally adopt a child, regardless of their sexual orientation; opposite-sex and same-sex couples being given equal treatment.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/1.809647 In Complete Reversal, Israel Says It No Longer Opposes Same-sex Adoption]</ref> Previously, same-sex couples could only adopt children opposite-sex couples did not want to adopt. From 2008 to 2017, only 3 same-sex couples (out of 550 applicants) were able to adopt, compared to 1,000 opposite-sex adoptions.<ref>[https://www.thejc.com/news/israel/reversal-over-israel-s-same-sex-adoption-policy-1.443803 Reversal over Israel\u2019s same-sex adoption policy]</ref> According to a poll conducted earlier in August 2017, 60% of Israelis supported adoption rights for same-sex couples, while 33% were against.<ref name=\"ynetnews\">[https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5001831,00.html Poll finds 60% of Israelis support same-sex adoptions]</ref> As of 2019, however, the Justice Minister has blocked the criteria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-despite-promise-to-top-court-israel-still-discriminates-on-gay-adoption-1.7339552|title=Despite Promise to Top Court, Israel Still Discriminates Against Gay Couples Wanting to Adopt|work=Haaretz|date=6 June 2019|last=Yaron|first=Lee}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli surrogacy law allows opposite-sex couples to sign a surrogacy agreement with a surrogate mother. In July 2018, the Knesset passed a bill expending surrogacy rights to single women, but rejected an amendment that would have included same-sex couples. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu supported the amendment, but later voted against it due to objections from Orthodox groups. Subsequently, an estimated 100,000 people marched in Tel Aviv in protest.<ref>[https://www.i24news.tv/en/news/israel/179963-180722-thousands-to-protest-strike-over-surrogacy-law-excluding-gay-men 100,000 in Israel protest, strike over surrogacy law excluding gay men]</ref> The protests also received support from multiple companies, including [[Apple Inc.]], [[Microsoft]], [[Israir Airlines]] and many more, and an opinion poll conducted in July 2018 found that 57% of Israelis were in favour of surrogacy for same-sex couples. Despite the passage of the law, several court rulings have protected surrogacy rights for same-sex couples.<ref name=\"surroisrael\"/> In February 2020, the Israeli Supreme Court unanimously ruled that same-sex couples should be given access to surrogacy, holding that the current law harms the \"right to equality\" and gave the state one year to amend the existing legislation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/article/rkVSudHEI|title=Supreme Court rules same-sex couples be given access to surrogacy|date=2020-02-27|website=ynetnews|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, the Israeli High Court proposed to make it easier for children raised by same-sex couples to be registered on official documents with the names of both their parents. Under the proposal, the non-biological parent would have to send a notice to the Interior Ministry. However, the Israeli Government rejected this measure, and insisted that same-sex couples should receive a court order if they wish to register their child(ren) with both their names.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/amp/israel-news/.premium-israel-rejects-compromise-on-legal-requirements-for-lesbian-parents-1.6450803|title=Israel Rejects Court-proposed Compromise to List Both Members of Lesbian Couple as Parents|website=Haaretz|date=4 September 2018}}</ref> In December 2018, the [[Supreme Court of Israel|High Court of Justice]] ruled that same-sex parents have the right to be listed on their child(ren)'s birth certificates. In a landmark case, the top court ruled that the [[Ministry of Interior (Israel)|Interior Ministry]] cannot refuse this right based on the parent's sexual orientation. The ruling came after two gay men adopted a son, then tried to list both their names on his birth certificate, but government officials refused to do so. Supreme Court Justice [[Neal Hendel]] said in the decision: \"The principle of \"the good of the child\" argues for the recording of his entire family unit, and doesn't permit us to limit ourselves to only one of his parents in the birth certificate\u2026. The contrast with the treatment of a child adopted by a heterosexual couple, who has the right to have both adopted parents written in a birth certificate, is a contrast that applies both to the child and to the parents... It is unreasonable for the couple to be [legally] recognized as parents but for the certificate not to give expression to that fact.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/israel-top-court-gay-parents-birth-certificate/|title=Israel top court rules both gay parents should be put on birth certificate|work=Gay Star News|date=13 December 2018|first=James|last=Besanvalle}}</ref>\n\n===Gender identity and expression===\n{{See also|Legal aspects of transsexualism}}\nTreatment for [[gender dysphoria]] in Israel can be paid for using the country's [[Health care in Israel|public health insurance system]] if a patient receives approval by the Committee for Sex Reassignment operating out of [[Sheba Medical Center]] in [[Tel HaShomer]], which consists of an [[endocrinologist]], a [[urologist]], and a [[plastic surgeon]] and is organized by the [[Health Minister of Israel|Health Ministry]]. All [[sex reassignment surgery]] operations in Israel are furthermore performed by Dr. Haim Kaplan at [[Sheba Medical Center]] under this committee's approval. However, many [[transgender]] Israelis have had trouble getting approval for treatment by this committee due to their stringent opinions on gender dysphoria. Thus, many pay out of pocket for [[Hormone replacement therapy (transgender)|hormone replacement therapy]] and/or go overseas for [[sex reassignment surgery]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Aderet |first=Ofer |url=http://www.changelingaspects.com/PDF/Sex%20Change%20in%20Israel%20Gender%20Trap.pdf |title=Sex-change in Israel: Gender trap |date=22 June 2012 |access-date=30 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029180410/http://www.changelingaspects.com/PDF/Sex%20Change%20in%20Israel%20Gender%20Trap.pdf |archive-date=29 October 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA law was introduced to the [[Knesset]] in June 2013 to eliminate gender markers on [[Teudat Zehut|National Identity Cards]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fiske |first=Gavriel |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/mk-pushes-gender-neutral-id-cards/ |title=MK pushes gender-neutral ID cards |date=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nSince 2015, the Health Ministry has allowed transgender people to change legal gender without undergoing sex reassignment surgery or a sex change operation.<ref>{{Cite newspaper | title=Israel recognizes sex changes without operation | journal=Haaretz | url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/.premium-1.637786 | accessdate=2015-01-23| date=2015-01-18 | last1=Hovel | first1=Revital }}</ref>\n\n===Military service===\n{{See also|Sexual orientation and gender identity in the Israeli military}}\n[[Coming out|Openly gay]], lesbian and bisexual soldiers serve without hindrance in all branches of the military. Discrimination against gay, lesbian and bisexual soldiers in recruitment, placement and promotion is prohibited in Israel.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/16/world/tel-aviv-journal-once-taboo-a-gay-israeli-treads-the-halls-of-power.html?pagewanted=1 | work=[[The New York Times]] | title=Tel Aviv Journal; Once Taboo, a Gay Israeli Treads the Halls of Power | first=Joel | last=Greenberg | date=16 October 2002 | accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref> Harassment on the grounds of sexual orientation is also prohibited in the Israeli military. The military recognizes same-sex couples, including widows and widowers of the same sex.<ref>[http://www.izkor.gov.il/HalalKorot.aspx?id=513304 Izkor], in the Israeli Ministry of Defense site (Hebrew)</ref> Soldiers are also allowed to participate in gay [[pride parade]]s.<ref>[http://www.news1.co.il/Archive/001-D-114912-00.html Soldiers can participate in Pride Parades], News-1 (Hebrew)</ref> The [[Israeli Defense Forces]] currently does not consider [[gender dysphoria]] to be a disqualifying condition for service. Furthermore, the [[Israeli Defense Forces|IDF]] considers certain [[Transitioning (transgender)|transition]]-specific medical treatment ([[Hormone replacement therapy (transgender)|hormone replacement therapy]] and [[sex reassignment surgery]]) and [[Sex reassignment therapy#Psychological treatment|counseling]] to be medically necessary for those diagnosed with [[transsexualism]] and thus pays for said treatments. The [[Israeli Defense Forces|IDF]] also determines gender specific army regulations (length of service, which gender to be housed with, whether they are to wear a male or female uniform, etc.) on a case-by-case basis for its [[transgender]] soldiers. However, given that Israeli law makes it difficult for its transsexuals to begin transition until they reach 18, the draft age, and does not normally allow for [[sex reassignment surgery]] to be performed before the age of 21, so far the only person who underwent surgery while serving is Shachae Erez, the first openly transgender person to become an officer. Furthermore, many draftees diagnosed with gender dysphoria can receive exemption from military service at their own request.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ginsburg |first=Mitch |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/idfs-gays-find-friends-at-the-top-lingering-homophobia-on-the-ground/ |title=IDF's gays find friends at the top, lingering homophobia on the ground |date=29 July 2013}}</ref> Officially, the IDF policy does not prohibit [[intersex]] persons from [[Intersex people and military service|service]].<ref name=pmid19055190>{{cite journal |doi=10.7205/MILMED.173.11.1132 |pmid=19055190 |title=Intersex Patients in Military Service |journal=Military Medicine |volume=173 |issue=11 |pages=1132\u20135 |year=2008 |last1=Marom |first1=Tal |last2=Itskoviz |first2=David |last3=Ostfeld |first3=Ishay |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n===LGBT immigration to Israel and the Law of Return===\nOn 10 June 2011, the ''[[Law of Return]]'' was tested when a gay male couple, one Jewish and one Catholic, made Aliyah to Israel. This couple was the first same-sex,  different-religion married couple to request joint Aliyah status, although opposite-sex married couples of opposite religions receive joint Aliyah as a matter of course. The Jewish man quickly received citizenship but the decision of citizenship for his husband was delayed by the Ministry of the Interior despite the clause in the law saying the spouse of the Jewish immigrant must also be granted citizenship.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/israel-refuses-citizenship-for-gay-man-married-to-jewish-immigrant-1.369936|title=Israel refuses citizenship for gay man married to Jewish immigrant|author=Ilan Lior|date=28 June 2011|work=Haaretz.com}}</ref> On 10 August 2011, the Ministry of the Interior granted citizenship to the non-Jewish husband as required by the ''Law of Return''.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.haaretz.com/weekend/anglo-file/ministry-grants-citizenship-to-gay-spouse-of-immigrant-1.382066|title=Ministry grants citizenship to gay spouse of immigrant|author=Raphael Ahren|date=2 September 2011|work=Haaretz.com}}</ref> In 2014, Interior Minister Gidon Sa'ar officially decided that, according to the ''Law of Return'', Jews in same-sex relationships married abroad wishing to immigrate to Israel can do so - even if their partners are not Jewish - and both them and their partners will receive Israeli citizenship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/183971|title=Right of Return Extended to Gay Couples|work=Arutz Sheva}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, [[Attorney General of Israel|Attorney General]] [[Avichai Mandelblit]] issued an instruction to Israel's Interior Ministry to consider applications for citizenship by same-sex and opposite-sex couples equally under the same terms. The same-sex spouse of an Israeli will now be able to claim Israeli citizenship at the same speed as an opposite-sex spouse. Previously, same-sex couples had to wait up to seven years, and would generally only be granted permanent residency rather than citizenship. The process was far quicker for opposite-sex couples.<ref name=\"pink\">[http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2016/12/10/israel-is-to-begin-recognising-same-sex-marriage-as-an-equal-route-to-citizenship/ Israel is to begin recognising same-sex marriage as an equal route to citizenship] Pink News</ref> The decision came in response to a lawsuit filed before the High Court of Justice by the Gay Fathers Association.\n\n===Discrimination protections===\nLGBT couples in Israel have the same\npension, inheritance and medical rights as\nheterosexual couples.<ref name=lgbtprotection />  In 1992, legislation was passed into law to prohibit [[employment discrimination]] on the basis of [[sexual orientation]],<ref name=lgbtprotection>[http://www.keshetuk.org/uploads/1/3/8/6/13861493/keshet_uk_factsheet_israel_mar13_v3.pdf Life for LGBT people in Israel]</ref> with some exemptions for religious organizations. In 1997, an amendment was added to the nation's ''Libel and Slander Law''.<ref name=isrgahat>[http://embassies.gov.il/la/AboutIsrael/IsraelExperience/Pages/Gay-Israel.aspx Gay Israel]</ref> The amendment broadened the prohibition of uttering and publishing defamation and slander, motivated by the sexual orientation of a person.<ref name=isrgahat /> Moreover, the law specifies that every violent crime, motivated by sexual orientation, shall be considered a hate crime, doubling the punishment.<ref name=isrgahat /> The ''[[Prohibition of Discrimination in Products, Services and Entry into Places of Entertainment and Public Places Law, 2000]]'' ({{lang-he|\u05d7\u05d5\u05e7 \u05d0\u05d9\u05e1\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d4\u05e4\u05dc\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d1\u05de\u05d5\u05e6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd, \u05d1\u05e9\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05d1\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05e1\u05d4 \u05dc\u05de\u05e7\u05d5\u05de\u05d5\u05ea \u05d1\u05d9\u05d3\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d5\u05dc\u05de\u05e7\u05d5\u05de\u05d5\u05ea \u05e6\u05d9\u05d1\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd}}; [[Arabic]]: {{lang|ar|\u062d\u0638\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0645\u064a\u064a\u0632 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u062a\u062c\u0627\u062a \u0648\u0627\u0644\u062e\u062f\u0645\u0627\u062a \u0648\u0627\u0644\u062f\u062e\u0648\u0644 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u0623\u0645\u0627\u0643\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0631\u0641\u064a\u0647 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0627\u0643\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645\u0629}}) prohibits discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation, among others, on the part of those who provide products, public services or operate public places.\n\nSince 2014, LGBT youth have been protected at different schools around the country.<ref>[http://www.glaad.org/blog/israeli-parliament-bans-discrimination-against-lgbt-youth-schools Israeli Parliament bans discrimination against LGBT youth in schools]</ref>\n\n===Conversion therapy===\n[[Conversion therapy]] has a negative effect on the lives of LGBT people, and can lead to low self-esteem, depression and suicide ideation. It commonly includes [[Electroconvulsive therapy|electroshock therapy]], forced [[chemical castration]], [[exorcism]], the administration of nausea-inducing drugs, and especially talk therapy.\n\nIn October 2014, the Ministry of Health issued a statement announcing that it considers conversion therapy to \"create false impressions of scientific recognition even though there is no scientific evidence that it is at all successful. It may also cause harm to the individual.\"<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Health/Health-Ministry-warns-against-conversion-therapy-for-homosexuals-378122 Health Ministry warns against conversion therapy for homosexuals]</ref> The Ministry created a complaints committee to investigate allegations of conversion therapy by mental health professionals. According to February 2017 reports, none of the 20 complaints filed had been dealt with by the committee. The committee is supposed to convene monthly. Several MKs, namely Yael German and [[Eyal Ben-Reuven]], have called the committee \"dysfunctional\".<ref name=\"therapy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.jpost.com/Business-and-Innovation/Health-and-Science/Health-Min-complaints-committee-on-conversion-therapy-is-dysfunctional-496787|title=HEALTH MIN. COMPLAINTS COMMITTEE ON CONVERSION THERAPY IS DYSFUNCTIONAL|newspaper=The Jerusalem Post|date=14 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, the [[Knesset]] rejected a bill introduced by former Health Minister [[Yael German]] that would have banned conversion therapy in Israel for minors. The bill was rejected 37-45.<ref>[http://www.timesofisrael.com/day-after-marking-lgbt-rights-knesset-nixes-5-gender-equality-bills/ Day after marking LGBT rights, Knesset nixes 5 gender equality bills]</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, the [[Israel Medical Association]], which represents about 90% of all doctors in Israel, explicitly banned all its members from performing any conversion therapy on patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/israeli-doctors-ban-conversion-therapy-for-gay-people-1.6828815|title=Israeli Doctors Ban 'Conversion Therapy' for Gay People|work=Haaretz|date=10 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, interim [[Ministry of Education (Israel)|Minister of Education]] [[Rafi Peretz]] attracted criticism after he endorsed the pseudoscientific practice and claimed to have personally performed such therapies. Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] rejected Peretz's comments as unacceptable, saying they \"do not represent [his] government's position\" and that \"[he] made it clear to him that the Israeli educational system will continue to accept all Jewish children whoever they are and without any difference based on sexual orientation.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Dalton |first=Jane |date=14 July 2019 |title=Gay conversion therapy works and I\u2019ve given it, says Israeli education minister |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/gay-conversion-therapy-israel-minister-rafi-peretz-lgbt-netanyahu-a9004396.html |work=[[The Independent]] |location= |access-date=14 July 2019}}</ref> Thousands of Israeli teachers signed a petition demanding Perez's dismissal,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/middle-east/calls-for-sacking-of-israeli-minister-over-gay-conversion-support-1.3957529|title=Calls for sacking of Israeli minister over 'gay conversion' support|work=The Irish Times|date=15 July 2019|last=Weiss|first=Mark}}</ref> and more than a thousand people protested his comments in Tel Aviv and in Peretz's hometown calling for his resignation, with the presence of former Israeli Prime Minister [[Ehud Barak]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/hundreds-rally-for-ouster-of-israeli-education-minister-after-gay-conversion-remarks-1.7500130|title=Hundreds Rally For Ouster Of Israeli Education Minister After Gay Conversion Remarks|work=Haaretz|date=14 July 2019}}</ref> Days later, Peretz backtracked from his comments, calling conversion therapy \"inappropriate,\" but added that \"individuals with a homosexual orientation have the right to receive professional help\".<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/israeli-education-minister-backtracks-on-gay-therapy-comments-11726516|title=Israeli education minister backtracks on gay therapy comments|work=Channel News Asia|date=17 July 2019|location=Jerusalem}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israel-s-education-minister-now-says-he-opposes-gay-conversion-therapy-1.7532713|title=Israel's Education Minister Now Says He Opposes Gay 'Convesion Therapy'|work=Haaretz|date=16 July 2019}}</ref> Following his comments, hundreds of LGBT Israelis recounted their \"painful\" and \"destructive\" experiences with conversion therapy.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.timesofisrael.com/i-survived-abusive-religious-conversion-therapy/|title=I survived abusive religious 'conversion' therapy|work=Jewish News|date=17 July 2019|last=Hyman|first=Joe}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.israelhayom.com/opinions/weve-seen-the-damage-conversion-therapy-causes/|title=We've seen the damage 'conversion therapy' causes|work=Israel Hayom|date=16 July 2019|last=Friedman|first=Aviad}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2019/07/16/orthodoxy-and-gay-conversion-therapy/|title=Orthodoxy and Gay Conversion Therapy|work=The Algemeiner|date=16 July 2019|last=Boteach|first=Shmuley}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/gay-israelis-come-forward-to-decry-predatory-harmful-conversion-therapy/|title=Gay Israelis come forward to describe predatory, harmful conversion therapy|work=The Times of Israel|date=15 July 2019|last=Staff|first=Toi}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Conversion-therapy-can-kill-Religious-LGBT-community-members-speak-out-596082|title=Conversion therapy can kill: Religious LGBT community members speak out|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=19 July 2019|last=Joffre|first=Tzvi}}</ref>\n\nSeveral conversion therapy advocates and licensed professionals have moved to Israel from the [[United States]], due to [[List of U.S. jurisdictions banning conversion therapy|a growing number of bans]] on the [[Pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]] practice there.<ref name=\"therapy\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/amp/israel-news/.premium-the-constituency-that-keeps-conversion-therapy-legal-in-israel-1.7500412|title=The Constituency That Keeps 'Conversion Therapy' Legal in Israel|work=Haaretz|date=15 July 2019|last=Efrati|first=Ido}}</ref> The Israel Psychological Association opposes conversion therapy.<ref name=\"therapy\"/>\n\nIn July 2019, an opinion published in ''[[Haaretz]]'' called for an outright legal ban on the practice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/opinion/.premium-time-to-ban-conversion-therapy-1.7532421|title=Opinion // Time To Ban 'Conversion Therapy'|work=Haaretz|date=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Blood donation===\nSince 1 June 2017, gay and bisexual men in Israel have been allowed to legally donate blood following a one-year deferral period.<ref>[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4975976,00.html Israel finally receives blood donations from gays and Ethiopian immigrants]</ref> However, no deferral was in place for lesbians or bisexual women.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mdais.org/%D7%A9%D7%90%D7%9C%D7%95%D7%AA-%D7%95%D7%AA%D7%A9%D7%95%D7%91%D7%95%D7%AA-%D7%A9%D7%99%D7%A8%D7%95%D7%AA%D7%99-%D7%94%D7%93%D7%9D/%D7%9E%D7%99-%D7%99%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%9C-%D7%9C%D7%90-%D7%99%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%9C-%D7%9C%D7%AA%D7%A8%D7%95%D7%9D-%D7%93%D7%9D |title=Who may/may not donate blood? |publisher=[[Magen David Adom]] (in Hebrew)}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, the Health Ministry approved new regulations allowing gay and bisexual men to donate blood, regardless of when they last had sex; just like for straight men.<ref>[http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/01/11/israel-to-allow-gay-and-bisexual-men-to-donate-blood-regardless-of-when-they-last-had-sex/ Israel to allow gay and bisexual men to donate blood \u2013 regardless of when they last had sex]</ref>\n\n===Other court rulings===\n* The [[Supreme Court of Israel|Supreme Court]] ruled on 30 November 1994 that the partner of a gay employee at [[El Al]], Israel's national airline, is entitled to free airline tickets just as the spouse of any heterosexual employee is.<ref>[http://www.icj.org/sogicasebook/el-al-israel-airlines-ltd-v-danielowitz-israeli-supreme-court-sitting-as-the-high-court-of-justice-30-november-1994/ El-Al Israel Airlines Ltd v. Danielowitz, Israeli Supreme Court sitting as the High Court of Justice (30 November 1994)]</ref>\n* The Supreme Court recognized in May 2000 a lesbian as the adoptive mother of the four-year-old biological son of her same-sex partner, and ordered the [[Interior Ministry]] to register the adoption.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/may/30/israel Israel grants rights to lesbian mothers]</ref>\n* An Israeli family court on 17 March 2002 turned down an application from a lesbian couple to have their partnership union declared legal. The couple was united in a [[Same-sex marriage in Germany|civil ceremony in Germany]]. The women wanted the court to recognize their partnership as a civil marriage under Israeli law. The court said that since the women are not recognized as a family under Israeli law, the court is not authorized to rule on their case. A government lawyer who was asked by the court to give a legal opinion on the case on behalf of the Israeli Government said that the state objected to granting the request.<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/1.5228258 Court Rejects Lesbians' Bid for Recognition as a Couple], ''Haaretz'', 18 March 2002</ref>\n* On 14 November 2004, the [[Nazareth]] District Court ruled that same-sex couples have the same [[inheritance]] rights as married couples. This ruling overturned a Family Court ruling that an elderly man from [[Kiryat Shmona]] was not entitled to spousal rights. The man had sought the estate of his late partner, with whom he lived for several decades. The Nazareth judges ruled that the term \"man and woman\" as spelled out in Israel's inheritance law also includes same-sex couples. Judges Nissim Maman and Gabriela Levy, who issued the majority opinion, based their decision on a loose interpretation of the term \"partner\" as defined in other court rulings, such as those dealing with issues related to [[employee benefit]]s, and thus applied the interpretation to the inheritance law. The acting president of the Nazareth District Court, Menachem Ben-David, issued the minority opinion, arguing that the legal text should not be interpreted \"contrary to the lingual significance.\" A government spokesperson said the ruling would be appealed.<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/1.4756574 Nazareth Court Sets Precedent in Same-sex Couple Case, ''Haaretz'', 15 November 2004]</ref>\n* In December 2004, the Tel Aviv District Court ruled that the Government cannot [[Deportation|deport]] the Colombian partner of a gay Israeli man. The 32-year-old Colombian entered Israel on a visitors [[Visa (document)|visa]] which had long expired and the Interior Ministry had ordered him deported. His partner is an Israeli citizen and a soldier in the Israel Defense Forces. The couple filed an emergency petition with the Tel Aviv District Court. The men were represented by the [[Association for Civil Rights in Israel]]. Judge [[Uzi Vogelman]] ruled that the Government had acted illegally in attempting to deport the man. In 1999, Supreme Court ruling established that the ministry could not deport foreign nationals married to Israeli citizens. Vogelman's decision extends that decision to apply to common-law marriages, including same-sex couples.<ref>[https://www.acri.org.il/en/2008/02/07/the-immigration-rights-of-same-sex-couples/ The immigration rights of same-sex couples], ''Association for Civil Rights in Israel</ref>\n* In March 2008, Israel's Interior Ministry granted a gay Palestinian from [[Jenin]] a rare residency permit to live with his partner of 8 years in Tel Aviv after he said his sexuality put his life in danger in the [[West Bank]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/lifestyleMolt/idUKL2586865820080325 | work=Reuters | title=Gay Palestinian gets OK to live with Israeli lover | date=25 March 2008}}</ref>\n* In 2012, the first same-sex Israeli couple was granted a divorce by an Israeli family court. The divorce of Tel Aviv University Professor [[Uzi Even]], the first openly gay Knesset member, and Dr. Amit Kama was granted by the Ramat Gan Family Court, according to [[Haaretz]], which ordered the Interior Minister to register their status as divorced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/breaking-news/israel-grants-first-gay-divorce|title=Israel Grants First Gay Divorce - The Jewish Week|work=The Jewish Week}}</ref>\n* In December 2016, [[Attorney General of Israel|Attorney General]] [[Avichai Mandelblit]] issued an instruction to Israel's Interior Ministry to consider applications for citizenship by same-sex and opposite-sex couples equally under the same terms.<ref name=\"pink\"/>\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:Flickr - Government Press Office (GPO) - P.M Ariel Sharon meeting with representatives of the Homosexual and Lesbian community.jpg|thumb|[[Ariel Sharon]] meeting with representatives of the LGBT community in [[Jerusalem]], 2002]]\n[[File:2013-03-30 Ostermarsch Hannover vom Kr\u00f6pcke aus, Regenbogenfahne Frieden Peace hebr\u00e4isch Schalom arabisch Salam.jpg|thumb|[[Rainbow flag]] with ''[[Shalom]]'' and ''[[\u0160-L-M|Salaam]]'' meaning ''[[peace]]'' in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] and [[Arabic language|Arabic]] respectively]]\nIsrael's [[Labor (Israel)|Labor Party]] and [[Meretz]] support LGBT rights, as did the now-defunct [[Shinui]]. Under [[Tzipi Livni]], [[Kadima]] has reached out to the LGBT community.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mozgovaya |first=Natasha |url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1089783.html |title=Livni, Clinton voice support for gay community in Israel and U.S |publisher=Haaretz.com |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1104611.html|title=Livni to gay Israelis: Don't let hate crime stop you living your lives|author=Ben Hartman|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]|date=2 August 2009}}</ref> Other minor liberal or progressive political parties support a similar platform as well, including the [[The Greens (Israel)|Greens]] and the [[Ale Yarok|Green Leaf Party]]. Officials from a number of parties, including [[Yael German]] of [[Yesh Atid]], [[Limor Livnat]] of the ruling [[Likud]]-[[Yisrael Beiteinu|Beiteinu]], and openly gay [[Nitzan Horowitz]] of [[Meretz]], back [[same-sex marriage]] and have pledged support for LGBT causes. Representatives from other parties, including [[Hatnuah]], [[Hadash]] and the [[Israeli Labour Party|Labor Party]], have also pledged support. Minister and MK [[Limor Livnat]], however, did state that getting the ruling [[Likud Yisrael Beiteinu|Likud-Beiteinu]] to legislate same-sex marriage would be difficult due to differing opinions concerning the issue within the party, but promised to do her utmost to get her party behind the issue.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/israel%E2%80%99s-politicians-give-unprecedent-pledge-legislate-pro-gay-laws060113|title=Party representatives discuss same-sex marriage}}</ref> Ahead of the [[April 2019 Israeli legislative election|April 2019 legislative election]], [[Yisrael Beiteinu]], one of the more conservative political parties in the country, announced that its doors were open to everyone regardless of their [[sexual orientation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Opinion/A-proud-Knesset-594116|title=A Proud Knesset|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 October 2002, [[Meretz]] MK [[Uzi Even]] made history by becoming the first openly gay member of the Knesset. Five more openly gay Israelis - [[Nitzan Horowitz]], [[Itzik Shmuli|Itzik Smuli]], [[Yorai Lahav-Hertzano]], [[Idan Roll]] and [[Amir Ohana]] - have been elected to the Knesset since then.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/outward/2016/01/19/amir_ohana_likud_s_first_openly_gay_knesset_member_interviewed.html|title=Israel\u2019s First Openly Gay Likud Lawmaker on Being in a Coalition With Anti-Gay Parties|last=Hoare|first=Liam|date=2016-01-19|newspaper=Slate|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref> In 2019, after the [[April 2019 Israeli legislative election|2019 general elections]], a record-breaking of 5 openly gay MKs got elected. They are [[Itzik Shmuli|Itzik Smuli]] ([[Israeli Labor Party|Labor]]), [[Amir Ohana]] ([[Likud]]), [[Eitan Ginzburg]], [[Idan Roll]] and [[Yorai Lahav-Hertzano]] (each being a member of [[Blue and White (political alliance)|Blue and White]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/amp/israel-news/elections/.premium-israelis-poised-for-their-gayest-parliament-yet-1.7001257|title=Israelis Poised for Their Gayest Parliament Yet|work=Haaretz|date=10 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the city of [[Ra'anana]] elected [[Eitan Ginzburg]] (he later became an MK) as mayor, making him the first openly gay mayor in Israel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.jpost.com/Israel-News/Raanana-gets-countrys-first-gay-mayor-546533|title=TEL AVIV SUBURB GETS COUNTRY\u2019S FIRST GAY MAYOR|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=20 March 2018|last=Hoffman|first=Gil}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ahead of the [[September 2019 Israeli legislative election|September 2019 legislative election]], [[Nitzan Horowitz]] successfully challenged incumbent [[Tamar Zandberg]] for the leadership of [[Meretz]], which made Meretz the first Israeli party to elect an openly gay person as its leader.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/israels-meretz-party-becomes-first-to-elect-an-openly-gay-leader |title=Israel's Meretz party becomes country's first to elect an openly gay leader - Jewish Telegraphic Agency |publisher=Jta.org |date= |accessdate=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Israel's first gay party leader Nitzan Horowitz elected head of Meretzr (sic)|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Meretz-now-has-new-leader-Nitzan-Horowitz-593944|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=27 June 2019 |accessdate=27 June 2019|author=Jeremy Sharon}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, [[Prime Minister of Israel|Prime Minister]] [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] appointed [[Evan Cohen]], a linguist and LGBT rights activist, as the foreign media spokesperson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.jpost.com/Israel-News/LGBT-Likud-leader-appointed-Netanyahus-English-spokesman-595626|title=New Netanyahu Spokesman To 'Post': Not Appointed Because I'm Gay|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=15 July 2019|last=Hoffman|first=Gil}}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, there still have been anti-gay politicians. In 1997, [[President of Israel|President]] [[Ezer Weizman]] compared homosexuality to alcoholism in front of high school students.<ref>Silver, Ian. [http://www.betham.org/kulanu/iansilver.html Homosexuality And Judaism] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070831131848/http://www.betham.org/kulanu/iansilver.html |date=31 August 2007 }}</ref> This provoked major controversy, and the President received numerous calls from [[civil rights]] activists and liberal [[Knesset]] members. Shortly following, 300 people demonstrated outside of Weizman's residence, demanding his resignation. He later apologised for these statements.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/5219/edition_id/96/format/html/displaystory.html |title=Israeli president apologizes for his anti-gay statements |publisher=Jewishsf.com |date=3 January 1997 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> On 20 February 2008, Shlomo Benizri, a Knesset member from the religious [[Shas]] party, a member of Prime Minister [[Ehud Olmert]]'s ruling coalition, blamed earthquakes that had recently struck the Middle East on the activities of homosexuals. Benizri said in a Knesset plenary session, \"Why do earthquakes happen? ... One of the reasons is the things to which the Knesset gives legitimacy, to sodomy.\" He recommended that instead of merely reinforcing buildings to withstand earthquakes, the Government should pass legislation to outlaw \"perversions like adoptions by gay couples\". Benizri stated that, \"A cost-effective way of averting earthquake damage would be to stop passing legislation on how to encourage homosexual activity in the State of Israel, which anyways causes earthquakes.\"<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/956334.html Shas MK blames gays for recent earthquakes in the region]</ref>\n\nIn 2015, [[Bezalel Smotrich]], a Knesset member from the [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]]-religious [[Jewish Home]] party, referred to LGBT people as \"abnormal\", stating: \"At home, everyone can be abnormal, and people can form whatever family unit they want. But they can't make demands from me, as the state.\" In the same discussion, he told the audience, \"I am a proud [[homophobia|homophobe]]\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Jewish Home hopeful boasts of being \u2018proud homophobe\u2019|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/jewish-home-hopeful-boasts-of-being-proud-homophobe|publisher=The Times of Israel|date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> He later apologized, and retracted his statement, saying: \"Someone shouted from the crowd, and I responded inattentively\".<ref>{{cite news|title=MK Smotrich: The government I'll be part of, will not recognize same-sex couples.|url=http://news.nana10.co.il/Article/?ArticleID=1121758|publisher=Nana10|date=April 19, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151224005930/http://news.nana10.co.il/Article/?ArticleID=1121758|archivedate=December 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Netanyahu Government will not recognize same-sex marriage|url=http://gogay.co.il/item.php?id=18829|publisher=GoGay.co.il|date=April 19, 2015}}</ref> In July 2015, after the Jerusalem LGBT pride stabbing, Smotrich called it a \"beast parade\", and refused to retract his homophobic remarks.<ref name=\"jpost.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Politics-And-Diplomacy/Religious-Zionist-lawmaker-refuses-to-back-down-says-homosexuality-an-abomination-410934|title=SMOTRICH: LGBT COMMUNITY ATTACKS, SLANDERS ANYONE WHO THINKS DIFFERENTLY FROM THEM|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=2 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.haaretz.com/beta/1.669230|title=Right-wing MK: Jerusalem Pride Parade Is an 'Abomination'|journal=Haaretz|date=2 August 2015}}</ref> In August 2015, Smotrich accused LGBT organizations of controlling the media, claiming they use their control to gain public sympathy and silence those who share his conservative views.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4690957,00.html|title=Bayit Yehudi MK: Gays control the media|work=Ynetnews|date=15 August 2018|last=Karni|first=Tuval}}</ref> An Israeli NGO, Ometz, filed a complaint with the Knesset Ethics Committee to intervene and investigate Smotrich's comments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/ngo-files-complaint-against-mk-for-gays-control-the-media-remark/|title=NGO files complaint against MK for 'Gays control the media' remark|work=The Times of Israel|date=16 August 2015|last=Pileggi|first=Tamar}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February 2016, the Knesset marked the first LGBT rights day, but on 24 February 2016, the parties that form the governing coalition, [[Likud]], [[United Torah Judaism]], [[Shas]], [[Kulanu]], and [[the Jewish Home]], supported by opposition members, defeated bills to recognize bereaved [[widower]]s, ban [[conversion therapy]], recognize [[same-sex marriage]], and train health professionals to deal with gender and sexual orientation issues.<ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-knesset-scraps-bills-for-lgbt-community-1.5409191 |title=Knesset Scraps Bills for LGBT Community After Marking Gay Rights Day |journal=Haaretz |last=Lis |first=Jonathan |date=25 February 2016 |access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nTwo days before the [[April 2019 Israeli legislative election|April 2019 legislative election]], Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] hosted a group of representatives of the LGBT community at the Prime Minister's residence for the first time in 10 years. Although the meeting was described as \"warm\" and \"good\", representatives of the LGBT community however were disappointed after the meeting ended with the refusal of Netanyahu to make promises to advance pro-LGBT legislation due to the pressure of right-wing religious and ultra-Orthodox coalition parties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.jpost.com/Israel-News/Benjamin-Netanyahu/Netanyahu-meets-with-LGBT-activists-wont-promise-push-in-coalition-talks-586013|title=NETANYAHU MEETS WITH LGBT ACTIVISTS, WON\u2019T PROMISE PUSH IN COALITION TALKS|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=7 April 2019|last=Harkov|first=Lahav}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/261492|title='Netanyahu refuses to commit to LGBT agenda'|work=Arutz Sheva|date=7 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.israelhayom.com/2019/04/08/i-hear-you-i-will-work-for-you-pm-tells-lgbt-community-leaders/|title=\u2018I hear you, I will work for you,\u2019 PM tells LGBTQ leaders|work=Israel Hayom|date=8 April 2019|last=Kahana|first=Ariel}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-meets-with-lgbt-leaders-for-first-time-in-10-years/|title=Netanyahu meets with LGBT leaders for first time in 10 years|work=The Times of Israel|date=7 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, interim [[Ministry of Education (Israel)|Education Ministe]] [[Rafi Peretz]] attracted criticism from when he endorsed [[conversion therapy]]. Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] rejected Peretz's comments as unacceptable, saying that they \"do not represent [his] government's position\" and that \"[he] made it clear to him that the Israeli educational system will continue to accept all Jewish children whoever they are and without any difference based on sexual orientation.\" Thousands of Israeli teachers signed a petition demanding his sacking,<ref name=\":0\"/> and more than a thousand people protested his comments in Tel Aviv and in Peretz's hometown,  calling for his dismissal.<ref name=\":1\"/> Days layer, Peretz backtracked from his comments, labelling conversion therapy \"inappropriate,\" but added that \"individuals with a homosexual orientation have the right to receive professional help\".<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\":3\"/><ref name=\":4\"/><ref name=\":5\"/><ref name=\":6\"/><ref name=\":7\"/><ref name=\":8\"/>\n\n==Society==\n\n===Living conditions===\n[[File:Tel Aviv Gay Pride Parade 2015 (18549971060).jpg|thumb|The 2015 [[Tel Aviv Pride]] parade]]\n[[File:Tel Aviv Gay Pride Parade 2018 (1528881).jpg|right|thumb|The 2018 Tel Aviv Pride parade]]\n[[File:Two flags meet (7700750632).jpg|thumb|right|An LGBT and Israeli flag at the 2012 [[Jerusalem gay pride parade|Jerusalem Pride parade]]]]\n\nIsrael has an active [[LGBT community]], with well attended annual gay [[Pride parade|pride festivals]],<ref>{{cite web|author=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0442 |url=http://www.jerusalemshots.com/cat_en91.html |title=Jerusalem Photos :: People, Demonstrations |publisher=Jerusalemshots.com |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jun/10/tel-aviv-gay-pride-parade|title=Tel Aviv's Gay Pride parade draws thousands to the city|author=Sherwood, Harriet|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=2011-10-05|accessdate=2012-05-17}}</ref> held in [[Tel Aviv Pride|Tel Aviv]] and [[Jerusalem gay pride parade|Jerusalem]] since 1998. Pride events are also held regularly in [[Haifa]], [[Petah Tikva]], [[Hadera]], [[Ra'anana]], [[Eilat]], and [[Rishon LeZion]]. In 2016, the first-ever pride parade scheduled in [[Beersheba]] was cancelled by the [[Supreme Court (Israel)|Israeli Supreme Court]] due to security concerns.<ref name=\"jtafirstbeershebagaypride\">{{cite news|title=First Beersheba gay pride march canceled over route change|url=http://www.jta.org/2016/07/14/news-opinion/israel-middle-east/first-beersheba-gay-pride-march-canceled-over-route-change|accessdate=July 17, 2016|work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|date=July 14, 2016}}</ref> Israel is one of only eleven foreign countries to have a chapter of the U.S. group [[PFLAG]], called [[Tehila (organization)|Tehila]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tehila.org.il/ |title=\u05ea\u05d4\u05dc\"\u05d4 &#124; \u05d0\u05ea\u05dd \u05dc\u05d0 \u05dc\u05d1\u05d3 &#124; \u05d3\u05e3 \u05d4\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea |publisher=Tehila.org.il |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref>\n\nThe Jerusalem parade gained international coverage when three marchers were stabbed in 2005. The perpetrator was subsequently sentenced to twelve years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3212934,00.html |title=Gay Parade stabber gets 12 years in prison \u2013 Israel News, Ynetnews |publisher=Ynetnews.com |date=20 June 1995 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> An attempt by Jerusalem's mayor, a [[Haredi]] Jew, to thwart Jerusalem Pride in June 2005 had been challenged in the courts. The mayor lost and was ordered to contribute funds to the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3099922,00.html |title=Gays slam Jerusalem mayor \u2013 Israel News, Ynetnews |publisher=Ynetnews.com |date=20 June 1995 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> The [[World Pride]] Festival was planned for [[Jerusalem]] in August 2005, despite protests and opposition from members of the three major religions in Jerusalem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2006-07-26/news/17302820_1_lesbian-gay-jerusalem-open-house|title=Broad opposition to World Pride in Jerusalem / Religious, gay leaders criticize international event; crisis in Lebanon ends parade plans|work=SFGate|date=2006-07-26}}</ref> However, it was postponed due to [[Israel's unilateral disengagement plan|Israel's pullout from the Gaza Strip]], which required the presence of most Israeli police forces and would thus leave the parade with little to no security. However, that parade had been plagued with threats of violence, as well as consistent grandstanding against it by some Jewish, Muslim and Christian leaders and members of the Knesset.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3271831,00.html |title=Gay leader not daunted by Muslim threat \u2013 Israel News, Ynetnews |publisher=Ynetnews.com |date=20 June 1995 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> In November 2006, more than two thousand members of the [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] community jammed into streets in an Orthodox neighbourhood in a show of force aimed at pressuring authorities into cancelling the [[gay pride]] parade to be held in [[Jerusalem]]. About a dozen people were reported injured.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.365gay.com/Newscon06/11/110206jerusalem.htm |title=3rd Night of Anti-Gay Riots in Jerusalem |date=2 November 2006 |publisher=365Gay.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926215949/http://www.365gay.com/Newscon06/11/110206jerusalem.htm |archivedate=26 September 2007}}</ref> Six people were stabbed in 2015.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-33726634|title=Jerusalem Gay Pride: Six stabbed 'by ultra-Orthodox Jew'|journal=BBC News|date=2015-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/30/middleeast/jerusalem-gay-pride-parade-stabbings/|title=6 stabbed at Jerusalem gay pride parade, police say - CNN.com|author=[[Oren Liebermann]] and Jason Hanna, CNN|date=30 July 2015|work=CNN}}</ref> One of the victims, 16-year-old Shira Banki, died of her wounds at the [[Hadassah Medical Center]] three days later, on 2 August 2015.<ref name=\"pinknewsjoe\">{{cite news |author=Joe Williams |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/08/02/victim-of-jerusalem-pride-attack-dies-of-injuries/ |title=Victim of Jerusalem Pride attack dies of injuries] |newspaper=[[PinkNews]] |date=2 August 2015}}</ref> The number of Jerusalem pride participants after the 2015 attack was smaller than in years past. In 2016, some 25,000 took part, many in solidarity with the LGBT community following the deadly stabbing attack,<ref name=\"march\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/ten-thousand-march-in-jerusalem-pride-parade-under-heavy-security/|title=Over 10,000 march in Jerusalem Pride Parade under heavy security|work=The Times of Israel|date=6 June 2019}}</ref> while in 2017, at least 22,000 marched in the parade.<ref name=\"march\"/> In 2018, at least 20,000 marched in the parade.<ref name=\"march\"/> On 6 June 2019, around 15,000 people marched at the event, under tight security with a reported 2,500 security personnel. At least 49 people who wanted to violenty disturb the event were arrested.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/gay-justice-minister-joins-jerusalem-pride-event-but-not-everyones-celebrating/|title=Gay justice minister joins Jerusalem Pride event, but not everyone's celebrating|work=The Times of Israel|date=6 June 2019|last=Horovitz|first=David}}</ref>\n\n[[Tel Aviv Pride]] is one of the largest pride parades in the world. There were 200,000 participants reported in 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/thousands-crowd-tel-aviv-streets-for-annal-pride-parade/ | title=200,000 crowd Tel Aviv streets for annual pride parade | newspaper=Times of Israel | accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref> The parade is the biggest pride celebration in continental [[Asia]], drawing more than 200,000 people in 2017, approximately 30,000 of them tourists.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/over-200000-attend-tel-aviv-gay-pride-parade-30000-from-abroad/|title=Over 200,000 attend Tel Aviv Gay Pride Parade, some 30,000 from abroad|journal=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=2017-06-09|accessdate=2017-07-29}}</ref> There were more than 250,000 participants reported in 2018,<ref>{{cite news |title=Tel Aviv pride parade draws 250,000 Israelis, foreigners |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/tel-aviv-pride-parade-draws-250-000-israelis-foreigners-n881466 |work=NBC News |date=8 June 2018}}</ref> and again more than 250,000 participants in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.i24news.tv/fr/actu/israel/societe/1560513404-tel-aviv-plus-d-un-quart-de-million-de-participants-au-defile-de-la-gay-pride|title=Tel Aviv: plus de 250.000 participants au d\u00e9fil\u00e9 de la Gay Pride|work=i24 News|date=14 June 2019|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Tel-Aviv-Pride-Parade-kicks-off-for-21st-time-with-theme-The-Struggle-Continues-592539|title=Tel Aviv Pride Parade Held With 250,000 Attendants Celebrating LGBTQ|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=16 June 2019|last=Dennen|first=Sydney}}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2009, an unknown assailant opened fire at Tel Aviv's main LGBT youth center, the [[2009 Tel Aviv gay centre shooting|Barnoar]], killing two and injuring fifteen others.<ref>Gross, Aeyal, \u201cThe Politics of LGBT Rights in Israel\u201d, Columbia Human Rights Law Review vol. 46, no. 2 (Winter 2015): 106-109</ref> The attack sent shockwaves throughout the worldwide gay community and throughout Israel, sparking an immense reaction throughout the country. Before this attack, it had only been mainly left-leaning politicians that supported the LGBT community in Israel.<ref>Gross, Aeyal, \u201cThe Politics of LGBT Rights in Israel\u201d, Columbia Human Rights Law Review vol. 46, no. 2 (Winter 2015): 110</ref> The issue for LGBT rights and acceptance began to slowly shift towards the center of Israel's political spectrum. This shift had slowly begun when Israel's Foreign Minister [[Tzipi Livni]] appeared at gay pride events in the months prior to the shooting. However, in the aftermath of this massacre, right-wing politicians began to publicly show their support for the gay community.\n\nOn 6 October 2016, Finance Minister [[Moshe Kahlon]] announced that the Israel Government had issued an order to give a divided 10 million [[Israeli new shekel|shekels]] to various governments over a two-year period to examine the nation's LGBT community for possible discriminations. A leading LGBT nonprofit called the move historic and ''[[Haaretz]]'' journalist Ilan Lior noted that it would even result in a major examination of issues such as the MSM blood transfusion restrictions.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-1.746166 In Historic Move, Israel Radically Increases Funding for LGBT Community]</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, in a report to [[President of Israel|President]] [[Reuven Rivlin]] by the LGBT association [[The Aguda \u2013 Israel's LGBT Task Force]], it was revealed that in 2018 there had been a 54% increase in homophobic incidents compared to 2017. The report highlighted that an anti-gay incident takes place about every ten hours on average in Israel. On social networks, a homophobic comment is detected every four minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fr.timesofisrael.com/hausse-de-54-des-incidents-homophobes-en-israel-en-2018/|title=Hausse de 54 % des incidents homophobes en Isra\u00ebl en 2018/|work=The Times of Israel|date=11 February 2019|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, [[Shlomo Amar]], the [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardic]] [[Chief Rabbi]] of [[Jerusalem]], was criticised for stating that gay people cannot be religious by saying that \"They aren't religious. It would be better if they cast off their kippah and Shabbat [observance] and show their true faces.\", and advocating for the pseudoscientific practice of [[conversion therapy]]. Ne'emanei Torah Va'Avodah and the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) criticised his comments. Jerusalem councilmembers Yossi Chavilov and Laura Warton called for the removal of Amar from his post as rabbi, as did openly gay politician [[Avi Buskila]] and [[Blue and White (political alliance)|Blue and White]] MK [[Eitan Ginzburg]]. Fellow [[Blue and White (political alliance)|Blue and White]] MK [[Yael German]] advised Amar to follow the example of [[Pope Francis]] in his moves to accept the LGBT community. The [[Jerusalem Open House]] association and three LGBT Jewish groups, [[Bat Kol (organization)|Bat-Kol]], [[Havruta (organization)|Havruta]] and the Gay Religious Community, condemned his comments as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/jerusalem-chief-rabbi-calls-homosexuality-a-wild-lust-that-needs-to-be-overcome-1.7569976|title=Jerusalem Chief Rabbi Calls Homosexuality 'A Wild Lust That Needs To Be Overcome'|work=Haaretz|date=24 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/israel-news/1765041/efforts-to-oust-jerusalem-chief-sephardi-rabbi-hagaon-harav-amar-after-anti-toeiva-remarks.html|title=Efforts To Oust Jerusalem Chief Sephardi Rabbi, HaGaon HaRav Amar After Anti-Toeiva Remarks|work=The Yeshiva World|date=26 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/adl-condemns-jerusalem-chief-rabbis-hateful-comments-on-homosexuals/|title=ADL condemns Jerusalem chief rabbi's 'hateful comments' on homosexuals|work=The Times of Israel|date=24 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/jerusalem-chief-rabbi-gay-people-arent-religious-should-cast-off-observance/|title=Jerusalem chief rabbi: Gay people cannot be religious, shouldn't pretend to be|work=The Times of Israel|date=23 July 2019|last=Winer|first=Stuart}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israel-s-homophobia-problem-just-got-even-worse-1.7569418|title=Israel's Homophobia Problem Just Got Even Worse|work=Haaretz|date=24 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://forward.com/fast-forward/428152/jerusalem-chief-rabbi-condemns-homosexuality-orthodox-israel-lgbt/|title=Jerusalem Chief Rabbi: Homosexuality Is 'A Wild Lust Than Needs To Be Overcome'|work=Forward|date=24 July 2019|last=Dolsten|first=Josefin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Jerusalem-chief-rabbi-homosexuality-wild-lust-that-needs-to-be-overcome-596626|title=Jerusalem Chief Rabbi: Homosexuality 'Wild Lust That Needs To Be Overcome'|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=24 July 2019|last=Dolsten|first=Josefin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/266415|title=Jerusalem chief rabbi calls on gays to 'overcome' homosexuality|work=Arutz Sheva|date=24 July 2019|last=Dolsten|first=Josefin}}</ref> He also caused controversy in 2016 by saying that homosexuality is an \"abomination cult\" for which the Torah prescribes the death penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-38023884|title=Israel Chief Rabbi Amar condemned for 'gay death penalty' comment|work=BBC News|date=18 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, a 16-year-old teenager who lives in the Beit Dror LGBT center in [[Tel Aviv]] was stabbed several times and seriously wounded by his brother for refusing to adopt \"a religious lifestyle\". [[Israel Gay Youth]] (IGY) called the stabbing a hate crime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/teen-seriously-wounded-in-stabbing-near-tel-aviv-lgbt-youth-hostel/|title=Teen seriously hurt in stabbing at Tel Aviv LGBT youth hostel; brother suspected|work=The Times of Israel|date=26 July 2019}}</ref> The condition of the victim stabilized after he underwent surgery at the [[Tel Aviv Sourasky Medical Center]]. Media reported that the victim and two suspects were all Muslim brothers from the Arab town of [[Tamra]] in northern Israel and that the victim was removed from his home by social services due to harassment from his family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israeli-teenager-seriously-wounded-in-stabbing-outside-lgbt-youth-shelter-1.7577291|title=Israeli Teenager Seriously Wounded In Stabbing Outside LGBT Youth Shelter|work=Haaretz|date=26 July 2019}}</ref> Nearly 1,000 LGBT people and allies marched in Tel Aviv under the banner \"fighting for our lives\" to denounce violence against LGBT people in the wake of the attack. The march was attended by openly gay [[Blue and White (political alliance)|Blue and White]] MKs [[Eitan Ginzburg]] and [[Idan Roll]], who said the party was committed to ending violence against the LGBT community, and by [[Meretz]] leader [[Nitzan Horowitz]], Israel's first ever openly gay party leader, and [[Etai Pinkas|Etai Pinkas-Arad]], who holds the LGBT portfolio at the [[Tel Aviv-Yafo Municipality]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-fighting-for-our-lives-over-a-thousand-march-in-tel-aviv-for-transgender-rights-1.7582432|title='Fighting For Our Lives': Over A Thousand March in Tel Aviv For Transgender Rights|work=Haaretz|date=28 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/hundreds-march-against-transgender-violence-in-tel-aviv-after-teen-stabbed/|title=Hundreds march against transgender violence in Tel Aviv after teen stabbed|work=The Times of Israel|date=28 July 2019}}</ref> The stabbing was also condemned as a hate crime by a number of politicians, among them [[Nitzan Horowitz]] and by some Arab lawmakers, namely [[Meretz]] MK [[Issawi Frej]], [[Hadash]] party leader [[Ayman Odeh]], Hadash MK [[Aida Touma-Sliman]] and [[Balad (political party)|Balad]] MK Mtanes Shihadeh.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/arab-lawmakers-condemn-stabbing-outside-lgbt-youth-hostel/|title=Arab lawmakers condemn stabbing outside LGBT youth hostel|work=The Times of Israel|date=27 July 2019}}</ref> [[Green Movement (Israel)|Green Movement]] MK [[Stav Shaffir]] blamed members of the religious right for intolerance towards LGBT Israelis, to which [[Ministry of Transport and Road Safety|Transport Minister]] [[Bezalel Smotrich]] ([[The Jewish Home]]) called her \"stupid\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/smotrich-shaffir-stupid-for-blaming-religious-right-for-anti-lgbt-violence/|title=Smotrich: Shaffir 'stupid' for blaming religious right for anti-LGBT violence|work=The Times of Israel|date=29 July 2019}}</ref> Four days later, the two suspects in the stabbing turned themselves in.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/brothers-of-youth-stabbed-outside-lgbt-hostel-in-tel-aviv-turn-themselves-in/|title=Brothers of youth stabbed outside LGBT hostel in Tel Aviv turn themselves in|work=The Times of Israel|date=30 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israeli-police-arrests-brothers-of-teen-stabbed-outside-tel-aviv-lgbtq-shelter-1.7606601|title=Israeli Police Arrests Brothers Of Teen Stabbed Outside Tel Aviv LGBTQ Shelter|work=Haaretz|date=30 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the LGBT association [[The Aguda \u2013 Israel's LGBT Task Force]] announced that gay pride events would be held in 12 locales that have never held them before. Among these are [[Tiberias]], [[Beit Shemesh]], [[Zikhron Ya'akov]], [[Ramat Gan]], [[Petah Tikva]], [[Pardes Hanna-Karkur]], [[Netanya]], [[Yavne]] and [[Kiryat Bialik]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-record-number-of-israeli-locales-to-hold-gay-pride-events-for-the-first-time-1.7301827|title=Record Number of Israeli Locales to Hold Gay Pride Events for the First Time|work=Haaretz|date=28 May 2019|last=Yaron|first=Lee}}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nOn 23 February 2016, the Ministry of Health approved a pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) program to prevent HIV transmission, making Israel one of the first countries to implement it. The drugs are handed out at AIDS centers in hospitals and clinics that serve the LGBT community, in addition to health fund clinics.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Business-and-Innovation/Health-and-Science/Israel-approves-drug-that-prevents-HIV-infection-445846 ISRAEL APPROVES DRUG THAT PREVENTS HIV INFECTION]</ref>\n\nOne of the Israeli National Health Funds, Clalit operates a dedicated LGBT-friendly health clinic. It is located in Tel-Aviv. It was the first LGBT-friendly clinic in the whole of Israel.<ref>[http://gaycenter.org.il/?page_id=12 \u05d4\u05e8\u05e9\u05de\u05d4 \u05dc\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05d6\u05dc\u05d8\u05e8]</ref>\n\n===Public opinion===\nA 2013 public opinion poll by ''[[Haaretz]]'' showed support for same-sex marriage at 59% among Israelis.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ho |first=Spencer |date=15 December 2013 |title=Poll: 70% of Israelis support recognition for gays |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/poll-70-of-israelis-support-recognition-for-gays/ |newspaper=The Times of Israel |accessdate=31 December 2014}}</ref> A Hiddush survey made in 2016 found that 76% of Israelis supported the recognition of same-sex marriage or civil unions. The poll showed an increase in public support on this issue in Israel.<ref>[http://mobile.mako.co.il/news-israel/education-q2_2016/Article-569c3b14b5a0551004.htm \u05e1\u05e7\u05e8: 76% \u05d1\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e0\u05d9\u05e9\u05d5\u05d0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d7\u05d3 \u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd]</ref> A June 2017 poll found that 79% of Israelis supported legally recognising same-sex unions.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Wide-support-for-gay-marriage-as-Israel-celebrates-Pride-496348 WIDE SUPPORT FOR GAY MARRIAGE AS ISRAEL CELEBRATES PRIDE]</ref>\n\n===LGBT rights movement===\n[[File:Yaar hagaava.jpg|thumb|A sign at Ya'ar HaGa'ava (\"Pride Forest\") in the [[Upper Galilee]], dedicated to Israel's LGBT community.]]\nSince the 1970s, there has been an active [[LGBT social movements|gay rights movement]] that has often affiliated itself with the Israeli [[Feminism|feminist]] movement and various liberal and [[Social democracy|social democratic]] political parties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegully.com/essays/gaymundo/020220_gay_israel_history.html |title=Queer in the Land of Sodom |publisher=Thegully.com |date=21 February 2002 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> The oldest Israeli LGBT organization is [[The Aguda \u2013 Israel's LGBT Task Force|The Aguda]], founded in 1975.\n\n===Media===\nOne of the first [[Israeli newspapers]] to cover the subject of gay people was a 1962 article in the now defunct ''[[HaOlam HaZeh]]''. Taking a sensationalist tone, the newspaper warned of a \"secret underground\" movement within Israel.<ref name=\"books.google.com\">{{cite book|last=Walzer|first=Lee|url=https://archive.org/details/betweensodomeden00walz |url-access=registration|title=Between Sodom and Eden : A Gay Journey Through Today's Changing Israel|year=2000|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-231-11394-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/betweensodomeden00walz/page/141 141]}}</ref> This was the typical manner with which the Israeli news media would deal with [[LGBT]] issues, beyond silence, until the late 1980s.\n\nIt was then that the Tel Aviv weekly newspaper ''HaIr'' began to publish a chronicle about an Israeli gay man, known at the time as ''Moshe'', who would later reveal himself to be [[Gal Uchovsky]].<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> The second major shift in how Israeli media dealt with [[LGBT]] issues came in 1991, when the [[Histadrut]] Labor Federation began to include, in its official publication, a section on [[LGBT]] social and political topics. This was followed by gradually more supportive press coverage on the Israeli LGBT community and its human rights objectives.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite book|last=Walzer|first=Lee|url=https://archive.org/details/betweensodomeden00walz |url-access=registration|title=Between Sodom and Eden : A Gay Journey Through Today's Changing Israel|year=2000|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-231-11394-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/betweensodomeden00walz/page/150 150]}}</ref> Today, the two Israeli daily newspapers have openly gay editors and/or writers, and several LGBT-publications have come and gone.\n\nRadio stations such as Radio Tzafon and Radio Radius both have scheduled times for guests to come on the air and talk about LGBT social and political topics.\n\n===Pinkwashing===\n{{further|Pinkwashing (LGBT)}}\nSarah Schulman, a writer and professor at the [[City University of New York]], claims Israeli [[Public diplomacy (Israel)|government public relations campaign]] exploits their LGBT rights record to promote public perception of Israel as a \"modern democracy\", a \"safe and secure place for investment\", and a \"tourist destination with the sun and the sand\".<ref>Avraham, Eli. (2009), \"Marketing and managing nation branding during prolonged crisis: The case of Israel\". Vol. 5, 3, pp.202\u2013212.</ref> In August 2011, the ''Jerusalem Post'' reported that the Foreign Ministry was promoting \"Gay Israel\" as part of its campaigns to counter the negative stereotypes that many liberal Americans and Europeans have of Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel/Foreign-Ministry-promoting-Gay-Israel |title=Foreign Ministry promoting Gay Israel |work=Jerusalem Post |accessdate=22 March 2014}}</ref> Critics of Israel like [[Jasbir Puar]], an associate professor of Women's and Gender Studies at [[Rutgers University]], cite the Israeli Government's comparison of gay rights in Israel and in the [[occupied Palestinian territories]] as an example of pinkwashing. Citing WorldPride, which Jerusalem hosted in 2006, she wrote: \"Within global gay and lesbian organising circuits, to be gay-friendly is to be modern, cosmopolitan, developed, first-world, global north, and, most significantly, democratic.\"<ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/jul/01/israels-gay-propaganda-war |title=Israel's gay propaganda war |work=[[ynetnews.com]] |date=1 July 2010 |first=Jasbir|last=Puar |accessdate=22 March 2014}}</ref> [[Joseph Massad]], associate professor of modern Arab politics and intellectual history at [[Columbia University]], has written that the Israeli Government \"insist[s] on advertising and exaggerating its recent record on LGBT rights ... to fend off international condemnation of its violations of the rights of the Palestinian people.\"<ref name=kaufman>{{cite news|last=Kaufman|first=David|title=Is Israel Using Gay Rights to Excuse Its Policy on Palestine?|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2070415,00.html|newspaper=Time magazine|date=13 May 2011|accessdate=26 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/stop-using-palestinian-gays-to-whitewash-israel-s-image-1.6887 |title='Stop using Palestinian gays to whitewash Israel's image' |work=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=26 January 2015|date=1 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nIdo Aharoni, former head of the Brand Israel project, responded to such criticism saying: \"We are not trying to hide the conflict, but broaden the conversation. We want to create a sense of relevance with other communities.\" <ref name=kaufman/> [[Alan Dershowitz]], criminal and civil liberties lawyer, has said that the term \"pinkwashing\" is used against Israel by \"some radical gay activists\" who are [[anti-Semitic]] \"bigots\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/alan-dershowitz/the-pinkwashing-campaign-_b_2790669.html |title=The Pinkwashing Campaign Against Israel: Another Conspiracy Theory |work=Huffington Post |accessdate=22 March 2014|date=March 2013 }}</ref>\n\nSeveral LGBT Palestinians were reported to have been blackmailed by the [[Israel Defense Forces]] to become informants. Reports stated that [[Mossad|Israeli intelligence]] pries into Palestinians' internet activity and phone calls so as to identify and blackmail LGBT people and turn them into informants against other Palestinians.<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Connor |first=Nigel |url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/read/gay-palestinians-are-being-blackmailed-into-working-as-informants |title=Gay Palestinians Are Being Blackmailed Into Working As Informants &#124; VICE &#124; United Kingdom |publisher=VICE |date=2013-02-19 |accessdate=2016-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.annahar.com/article/203736-revealed-israel-is-a-gay-mecca--new-york-times-promotes-a-pinkwashed-democracy |title=Revealed: Israel is a gay Mecca - New York Times promotes a pink-washed democracy - An-Nahar |publisher=En.annahar.com |date=2015-01-08 |accessdate=2016-01-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131194652/http://en.annahar.com/article/203736-revealed-israel-is-a-gay-mecca--new-york-times-promotes-a-pinkwashed-democracy |archivedate=31 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> According to an Israeli Intelligence Corps officer: \"If anyone interests us, we'd collect information on his or her economic situation and mental state. Then we would plan how we can perform an operation around this individual, in order to turn them into a collaborator or something of the sort.\"<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/12/israeli-intelligence-unit-testimonies |title='Any Palestinian is exposed to monitoring by the Israeli Big Brother' &#124; World news |journal=The Guardian |date= 2014-09-12|accessdate=2016-01-26}}</ref>\n\n===Film and television===\nThe first Israeli LGBT-themed film came from openly gay director [[Amos Guttman]] and was called ''[[Drifting (1983 film)|Nagu'a]]'' (English title ''Drifting'').<ref name=\"Walzer 2000\">{{cite book |last=Walzer |first=Lee |url=https://archive.org/details/betweensodomeden00walz |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/betweensodomeden00walz/page/175 175] |title=Between Sodom and Eden: A Gay Journey Through Today's Changing Israel |year=2000 |publisher=Columbia University Press |location=New York |isbn=978-0-231-11394-6 }}</ref> Guttman was its co-writer. The film follows a young Israeli gay man, living and working with his grandparents, who has dreams of making a film and finding true love. Guttman, who died of AIDS in 1993, would write and direct another Israeli gay-themed film titled ''[[Amazing Grace (1992 film)|Amazing Grace]]'' (1992). Both films are considered to be autobiographies of the director. In total, Guttman directed four films and three short films. His portrayal of Israeli gay men was dark, and his films are considered to be targeted at the LGBT community in Israel, and not to the general public.\n\n[[File:Eytan Fox 2012 Shankbone.JPG|thumb|upright|Israeli director [[Eytan Fox]]]]\nAnother notable Israeli director to tackle LGBT themes in films is [[Eytan Fox]]. His first film, ''Time Off'' (1990), was the second film made in Israel to focus on gay people. He has directed and written several other successful LGBT-themed films, including ''[[Ba'al Ba'al Lev]]'' (1997), ''[[Yossi & Jagger]]'' (2002), ''[[Walk on Water (film)|Walk on Water]]'' (2004), and ''[[The Bubble (2006 film)|The Bubble]]'' (2006).<ref>{{cite web |author=Andrejs Visockis |url=http://andysfilmworld.blogspot.com/2008/01/yossi-jagger-israel-2002.html |title=Andy's Film World: ''Yossi & Jagger'' (Israel, 2002) |publisher=Andysfilmworld.blogspot.com |date=27 January 2008 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> Fox was also involved in the first Israeli prime time TV drama made for a general audience which dealt extensively with [[LGBT]]-themes, ''Florentin'' (1997\u20132000). This was an Israeli television series about a group of post-military service, Israeli twenty-somethings living in [[Florentin (Tel Aviv)|Florentin]]. It was the first Israeli series to have a gay person among its major characters, and was part of a slow trend that had been unfolding in the 1990s with shows such as ''Straight and to the Point'' and ''Siton''.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nToday, there is more programming for a [[LGBT]] audience. In 1993, the first commercial TV network in Israel, [[Channel 2 (Israel)|Channel 2]], went on the air. It regularly dealt with [[LGBT]] social and political topics, and, in particular, helped generate greater visibility and acceptance of transgender celebrities such as [[Dana International]].<ref name=\"Walzer 2000\"/> The LGBT community in Israel was also brought to the media's attention following the winning of the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] in 1998 by Dana International, an Israeli [[transsexual|transwoman]]. At present, LGBT people in Israel can be seen on television in a variety of shows, mostly as hosts (such as [[Assi Azar]]), contestants in [[reality show]]s or characters on [[soap opera]]s.\n\n==Palestinian issues==\n{{further|LGBT rights in the Palestinian territories}}\nPalestinian society tends to be conservative, with families tending to see homosexuality and [[cross-dressing]] as immoral acts, deserving of condemnation. Some LGBT Palestinians have relocated to Israel, often fleeing harsh intolerance that includes physical abuse, death, or disowning. Significant [[expatriate]] groups exist in [[Tel Aviv]] and [[Netanya]], where many live with their Israeli same-sex partners who help keep their presence in Israel hidden from the police (who would pursue them not for their sexual orientation, but for staying illegally in the country).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/page_view_story.asp?intarticleid%3D13623 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-07-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051018001739/http://www.jta.org/page_view_story.asp?intarticleid=13623 |archivedate=18 October 2005 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/mwt/feature/2002/02/21/ezra_selim/ |title=Sleeping with the enemy \u2013 Middle East |work=Salon.com |date=21 February 2002 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baywindows.com/main.cfm/include/detail/storyid/245628.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20051122220931/http://www.baywindows.com/main.cfm/include/detail/storyid/245628.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=22 November 2005|title=Where Jews and Arabs find ways to mix peacefully in the Holy Land|work=Bay Windows|date=22 May 2002|last=Cassels|first=Peter}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Aswat was founded, which describes itself as a Palestinian lesbian support group. However, the group is headquartered in [[Haifa]], Israel, and is geared toward Arab lesbians in Israel and the Palestinian Authority. A secret association of Aswat was founded in [[Ramallah]] in March 2007 by four gay students.<ref>[http://www.aswatgroup.org/english/about.php?article=212 Our Mission and Aims] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070811234504/http://www.aswatgroup.org/english/about.php?article=212 |date=11 August 2007 }}</ref> The Israeli [[Jerusalem Open House]] has opened an Arab chapter called Alqaws,<ref>[http://www.alqaws.org/?id=500 Alqaws]</ref> reaching out to gay and lesbian Palestinians. In 2008, Israel granted a gay Palestinian a residency permit to live with his Israeli partner in [[Tel Aviv]] following death threats from Palestinians regarding his homosexuality. Aswat claimed that gays are sometimes targeted by the Israeli security services and are told that they must collaborate with Israel or face being outed.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKL2586865820080325 | work=Reuters | title=Gay Palestinian gets OK to live with Israeli lover |author= Rebecca Harrison | date=25 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Notable individuals==\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Aderet (singer)|Aderet]], musician \n* [[Corinne Alal]], musician ([[:he:\u05e7\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05df \u05d0\u05dc\u05d0\u05dc|he]])\n* [[Yossi Avni-Levy]], diplomat\n* [[Assi Azar]], TV personality\n* [[Orna Banai]], actress\n* [[Jean-Pierre Barda]], musician and actor\n* [[Apollo Braun]], musician and author\n* [[Eliad Cohen]], model\n* [[Evan Cohen]], linguist and LGBT rights activist, foreign media spokesperson<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-taps-south-africa-born-linguist-as-new-foreign-media-spokesperson/|title=Netanyahu taps linguist and LGBTQ rights activist as foreign media spokesperson|work=The Times of Israel|date=14 July 2019|last=Ahren|first=Raphael}}</ref>\n* [[Dana International]], musician\n* [[Jonathan Danilowitz]], activist\n* [[Ran Danker]], actor\n* [[Jason Danino-Holt]], anchor\n* [[Irit Dinur]], mathematician/computer scientist\n* [[Uzi Even]], scientist and politician\n* [[Rose Fostanes|Rose \"Osang\" Fostanes]], musician\n* [[Eytan Fox]], director\n* [[Marcia Freedman]], activist and politician\n* [[Robert Friend (poet)|Robert Friend]], poet\n* [[Amir Fryszer Guttman]], musician\n* [[Eitan Ginzburg]], politician\n* [[Amos Guttman]], director\n* [[Yuval Noah Harari]], historian\n* [[Matan Hodorov]], journalist\n* [[Nitzan Horowitz]], politician\n* [[Dario Hunter|Dario David Hunter]], rabbi\n* [[Rona Kenan]], musician\n* [[Yorai Lahav-Hertzano]], politician\n* [[Asi Levi]], actress\n* [[Ivri Lider]], musician\n* [[Michael Lucas (director)|Michael Lucas]], director\n* [[Lyrik]], musician \n* [[Idan Matalon]], video blogger\n* [[Doron Medalie]], musician \n* [[Gil Mossinson|Gili Mossinson]], basketball player<ref>[http://m.jpost.com/Israel-News/Sports/Israeli-sports-world-rocked-as-pro-basketball-player-comes-out-of-closet-453921#article=6017MEIwNUQwRUY5RjVFNTI2RDk2NTVDQUQyRTY4N0U2RTQ= ISRAELI PRO BASKETBALL PLAYER COMES OUT AS BISEXUAL IN INDEPENDENCE DAY POST]</ref>\n* [[Ezra Nawi]], activist\n* [[Adi Nes]], photographer\n* [[Offer Nissim]], musician\n* [[Tzipora Obziler]], tennis player\n* [[Amir Ohana]], politician\n* [[Dana Olmert]], activist\n* [[Yotam Ottolenghi]], chef\n* [[Etai Pinkas]], activist\n* [[Yehuda Poliker]], musician<ref>[http://awiderbridge.org/yehuda-poliker/ YEHUDA POLIKER]</ref><ref>[http://jewishjournal.com/current_edition/213534/israeli-yehuda-poliker-brings-greek-infused-music-to-ucla/ Israeli Yehuda Poliker brings Greek-infused music to UCLA]</ref>\n* [[Yehudit Ravitz]], musician\n* [[Idan Roll]], politician\n* [[Jonathan Sagall]], actor\n* [[Itzik Shmuli]], politician\n* [[Gil Shohat]], musician\n* [[Harel Skaat]], musician\n* [[Dori Spivak]], judge\n* [[Hovi Star]], musician \n* [[Gal Uchovsky]], screenwriter and producer\n* [[Yeho]], musician \n* [[Yona Wallach]], poet\n* [[Ron Yosef]], activist\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Summary table==\n{{LGBT rights summary\n| legality = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 1963 ''[[de facto]]'', since 1988 ''[[de jure]]'')\n| equal_aoc = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| antidiscrimination = \n| antidiscrimination_employment = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 1992)\n| antidiscrimination_goods = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2000)\n| antidiscrimination_other = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 1997)\n| antidiscrimination_genderid = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n| marriage = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]/[[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Same-sex marriage from abroad recognised since 2006)<ref name=\"elyon1.court.gov.il\"/>\n| recognition = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Unregistered cohabitation since 1994)\n| joint_adoption = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2008)\n| step_adoption = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2005)\n| military_service = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 1993)\n| gender_change = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| surrogacy1 = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]/[[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Surrogacy for Israeli gay male couples is possible only abroad)\n| ivf_access = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| blood_donation = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (No deferral since 2018)\n| immigration = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2016)<ref name=\"pink\"/>\n| conversion_therapy = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]/[[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Practice of conversion therapy in the public health system banned since 2014)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Israel|LGBT}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[2009 Tel Aviv gay centre shooting]]\n* [[Homosexuality and Judaism]]\n* [[Human rights in Israel]]\n* [[LGBT history in Israel]]\n* [[LGBT in the Middle East]]\n* [[LGBT rights by country or territory]]\n* [[LGBT rights in Asia]]\n* [[List of LGBT Jews]]\n* ''[[Men of Israel]]''\n* [[Tel Aviv Municipal LGBT Community Center]]\n* [[Tel Aviv Pride]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.il/MFA/IsraelExperience/Pages/Gay_Israel.aspx|title=Gay Israel|work=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Israel)|Israel Ministry of Foreign Affairs]]|date=19 July 2018}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.glbtqarchive.com/ssh/israel_S.pdf|title=Israel|work=[[glbtq.com]]|date=2006}}\n* {{Curlie|Regional/Middle_East/Israel/Society_and_Culture/Gay,_Lesbian,_and_Bisexual|Israel: Society and Culture: Gay, Lesbian, and Bisexual}}\n\n{{LGBT in Israel}}\n{{Asia topic|LGBT rights in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:LGBT rights in Israel}}\n[[Category:LGBT rights in Israel| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Rights of lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender people in Israel}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox LGBT rights\n| location_header              = [[Israel]]\n| image                        = Israel (orthographic projection) with disputed territories.svg\n| legal_status                 = Legal since 1988 (but no record of enforcement of \"buggery\" law before this, and the Attorney General declared that laws against homosexuality would not be enforced in 1963)\n| gender_identity_expression   = Legal sex change possible\n| recognition_of_relationships = [[Unregistered cohabitation in Israel|Unregistered cohabitation since 1994]];<br />[[Recognition of same-sex unions in Israel|Same-sex marriages performed outside of Israel recognized since 2006]]\n| recognition_of_relationships_restrictions = Only marriages sanctioned by the religious authorities may be performed within Israel (this applies to opposite-sex couples who are not eligible for religious weddings also)\n| adoption                     = Yes, same-sex couples allowed to adopt\n| military                     = [[Sexual orientation and gender identity in the Israeli military|LGBT people allowed to serve openly]]\n| discrimination_protections   = Sexual orientation protection in employment and other services; both sexual orientation and gender identity protections in schools ([[#Discrimination protections|see below]])\n}}\n\n'''Lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) rights in Israel''' are the most developed in the [[Middle East]], and among the most tolerant in [[Asia]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/love-sex/taboo-tolerance/the-five-most-improved-places-for-gay-tolerance-932635.html | location=London | work=The Independent | title=The five most improved places for gay tolerance | date=17 September 2008}}</ref> Although same-sex sexual activity was legalized in 1988, the former law against sodomy had not been enforced since a court decision in 1963. [[Israel]] became the first country in Asia to recognize [[Unregistered cohabitation in Israel|unregistered cohabitation]] between same-sex couples, making it the first country in Asia to recognize same-sex unions in any capacity. Although [[Same-sex marriage in Israel|same-sex marriages]] are not performed in the country, Israel recognizes same-sex marriages performed elsewhere. Discrimination on the grounds of sexual orientation was prohibited in 1992. Same-sex couples are allowed to jointly adopt, following a landmark court decision in 2008. Previously, stepchild adoption as well limited co-guardianship rights for non-biological parents was permitted. [[LGBT]] people are also allowed to serve [[Coming out|openly]] in the military.\n\n[[Tel Aviv]] has frequently been referred to by publishers as one of the most gay-friendly cities in the world,<ref>\"The world's most gay-friendly places\". Calgary Herald. 29 June 2011.</ref> famous for its annual [[Tel Aviv Pride|Pride Parade]] and gay beach,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/07/02/dispatch-gay-tel-aviv/?_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Anthony | last=Grant | title=Dispatch | date=2 July 2010}}</ref> earning it the nickname \"the gay capital of the Middle East\" by ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'' magazine.<ref>James Kirchick. Out. [http://www.out.com/entertainment/2007/07/29/was-arafat-gay Was Arafat Gay?]</ref> According to LGBT travelers, it was ranked as the best gay city in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/LifeStyle/Tel-Aviv-named-worlds-best-gay-city-for-2011|title=Tel Aviv named 'world's best gay city' for 2011|work=The Jerusalem Post - JPost.com}}</ref> despite reports of some LGBT violence during the 2000s,<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/two-killed-in-shooting-at-tel-aviv-gay-center-1.281193|title=Two killed in shooting at Tel Aviv gay center|author=Haaretz Service and News Agencies|date=1 August 2009|work=Haaretz.com}}</ref> which were criticized by Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] and President [[Shimon Peres]]. A monument dedicated to the [[Persecution of homosexuals in Nazi Germany and the Holocaust|gay victims of the Holocaust]] was erected in Tel Aviv in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |date=10 January 2014 |title=Tel Aviv unveils first memorial to gay Holocaust victims |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-25687190 |newspaper=BBC News |accessdate=1 January 2015}}</ref> [[Opinion poll]]s have found that a majority of Israelis support the legalization of same-sex marriage,<ref>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/most-israelis-favor-same-sex-marriage-but-half-of-mks-mum-on-issue/ Most Israelis favor same-sex marriage, but half of MKs mum on issue]</ref> as well as adoption and surrogacy rights for same-sex couples.<ref name=\"ynetnews\"/>\n\n==Law==\n\n===Same-sex sexual activity===\nThe State of Israel inherited the ''[[Buggery Act]] of 1533'' as part of the British Mandate's legal code. There is no known record that it was ever enforced against homosexual acts that took place between consenting adults in private. In certain cases, defendants were found guilty of \"sodomy\" (which according to Israeli law included [[oral sex]] as well), apparently by way of plea bargains: Those defendants had been indicted for more serious sexual offences. It was also used as \"[[Aggravation (law)|aggravating circumstances]]\" for other sexual offences. There were also several cases of soldiers tried for homosexual acts in military courts. [[Attorney General of Israel|The Attorney General]] decided in the early 1960s, and the [[Supreme Court of Israel|Israeli Supreme Court]] ruled in 1963, that the law should not be applied to acts between consenting adults in private. The ban on consensual same-sex sexual acts was formally repealed by the National Legislative Assembly ([[Knesset]]) in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tau.ac.il/law/aeyalgross/Danilowitz.htm |title=Supreme Court of Israel |publisher=Tau.ac.il |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> The [[age of consent]] for both homosexual and heterosexual acts is 16 years of age.\n\n===Recognition of same-sex relationships===\n{{Main|Unregistered cohabitation in Israel|Recognition of same-sex unions in Israel}}\n[[File:Hayovel gay 3.JPG|thumb|Signs supporting same-sex marriage in [[Herzliya]], 2012]]\nBetween 1994 and 2007, numerous rights were granted to Israeli same-sex couples.<ref>[http://www.acri.org.il/en/2009/02/15/protecting-and-promoting-lgbt-rights-in-israel/ Protecting and Promoting LGBT Rights in Israel]</ref>\n\nSame-sex marriage cannot legally be performed in Israel. Israeli law allows same-sex marriages performed elsewhere to be registered, but not recognized based upon a 2006 Israeli Supreme Court decision which stated \"Before we conclude, let us reemphasize what it is that we are deciding today, and what it is that we are not deciding today. We are deciding that within the context of the status of the population registry as a recorder of statistics, the registration official should register in the population register what is implied by the public certificate that is presented to him by the petitioners, according to which the petitioners are married and in view of the role of the registration official as a collector of statistical material for the purpose of managing the registry...We are not deciding that marriage between persons of the same sex is recognized in Israel; we are not recognizing a new status of such marriages; we are not adopting any position with regard to recognition in Israel of marriages between persons of the same sex that take place outside Israel (whether between Israeli residents or between persons who are not Israeli residents)\"<ref name=\"elyon1.court.gov.il\">{{cite web |url=http://elyon1.court.gov.il/files_eng/05/450/030/a09/05030450.a09.htm |title=Judgement of the Supreme Court sitting as the High Court of Justice }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Civil marriage]] doesn't exist in Israel for heterosexual couples either (except where both heterosexual spouses do not belong to any of the recognized religious communities in the country),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/136544|title=Civil Marriage for Non-Jews|work=Arutz Sheva}}</ref> and therefore only a marriage sanctioned by the small number of officially recognized religious authorities can take place within Israel. (This restriction forces not only same-sex couples, but also all mixed-religion heterosexual couples and any person who wishes a non-religious marriage, to marry outside the country.)\n\nThe State of Israel allows foreign partners of its homosexual [[citizenry]] to receive residency permits. The Civil Service Commission extends spousal benefits and pensions to the partners of homosexual employees. The Israeli State Attorney's Office has extended the spousal exemption from property-transfer taxes to same-sex couples. Israel's Attorney General has granted legal recognition to same-sex couples in financial and other business matters. [[Attorney General]] [[Meni Mazuz]] said the couples will be treated the same as common-law spouses, recognizing them as legal units for tax, real estate, and financial purposes. Mazuz made his decision by refusing to appeal a district court ruling in an inheritance case that recognized the legality of a same-sex union, his office said in a statement. Mazuz did differentiate, however, between recognizing same-sex unions for financial and practical purposes, as he did, and changing the law to officially sanction the unions, which would be a matter for Parliament, according to the statement.\n\nThe city of [[Tel Aviv]] recognizes unmarried couples, including gays and lesbians, as family units and grants them discounts for [[municipal services]]. Under the bylaw, unmarried couples qualify for the same discounts on daycare and the use of swimming pools, sports facilities, and other city-sponsored activities that married couples enjoy. On 29 January 2007, following a Supreme Court ruling ordering them to do so, Jerusalem registered its first same-sex couple, Avi and Binyamin Rose.<ref>{{cite web |last=Eglash |first=Ruth |url=http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1167467842994&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull |title=Jerusalem registers its first gay couple &#124; Israel &#124; Jerusalem Post |publisher=Fr.jpost.com |date=30 January 2007 |accessdate=2011-06-14 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Israel's marriage law was amended with the passage of the ''Civil Union Law for Citizens with no Religious Affiliation, 2010'',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Julie|first1=Dayer|title=\u05d2\u05df \u05d4\u05e8\u05de\u05d5\u05d6\u05d5 \u05d0\u05d5\u05dc\u05dd (\u05d0\u05d5\u05dc\u05de\u05d5\u05ea) \u05d0\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9\u05e2\u05d9\u05df, \u05d9\u05d5\u05e7\u05e8\u05ea\u05d9 (\u05d9\u05d5\u05e7\u05e8\u05ea\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd) \u05d1\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05e9\u05dc\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05de\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9\u05e2\u05d9\u05df \u05d1\u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6 \u05d4\u05d0\u05e8\u05e5, \u05d2\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d0\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6|url=http://www.hermozo.co.il|website=\u05d4\u05e8\u05de\u05d5\u05d6\u05d5|publisher=\u05d0\u05d5\u05dc\u05dd \u05d0\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05de\u05e8\u05db\u05d6|accessdate=21 September 2016|language=he-IL|date=4 March 2013}}</ref> allowing an opposite-sex couple to form a [[civil union]] in Israel if they are both registered as officially not belonging to any religion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myjewishlearning.com/israel/Contemporary_Life/Society_and_Religious_Issues/Freedom_of_Religion/civil_marriage_in_israel.shtml|title=Civil Marriage in Israel|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/review/data/eng/law/kns18_CivilUnion_eng.pdf Civil Union Law for Citizens with no Religious Affiliation, 2010]</ref>\n\nThere have been 5 failed legislative attempts in the [[Knesset]] to recognise same-sex unions. The first attempt was a civil marriage bill, which included provisions for same-sex marriages, introduced by [[Meretz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontopmag.com/article/3320/Israeli_Knesset_To_Consider_Gay_Marriage|title=Israeli Knesset To Consider Gay Marriage|website=On Top Magazine}}</ref> The bill was rejected in May 2012 in a 39 to 11 vote, with 70 not attending.<ref name=\"bill\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/05/16/israeli-parliament-rejects-gay-and-inter-faith-civil-marriage-bill/|title=Israeli parliament rejects gay and inter-faith civil marriage bill|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jpost.com/DiplomacyAndPolitics/Article.aspx?id=270221 |author=Harkov, Lahav |title=Knesset rejects marriage equality bill |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post |date=16 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522013505/http://www.jpost.com/DiplomacyAndPolitics/Article.aspx?id=270221 |archivedate=22 May 2012 }}</ref> The second and third attempts were two similar bills that would have provided for [[civil union]]s in Israel for both opposite-sex and same-sex couples; one introduced by [[Hatnuah]],<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/livni-to-sponsor-groundbreaking-knesset-bill-allowing-same-sex-civil-partnership.premium-1.529818|title=Israeli Ministers Set to Vote on Bill Allowing Same-sex Civil Unions|journal=Haaretz|first=Jonathan|last=Lis|date=16 June 2013|via=Haaretz}}</ref> and the other by [[Yesh Atid]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/30/world/middleeast/centrist-party-in-israel-introduces-civil-union-bill.html |author=Rudoren, Jodi |title=Centrist Party in Israel Introduces Civil Union Measure |journal=The New York Times |date=29 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper|author1=JODI RUDOREN|title=Centrist Party in Israel Introduces Civil Union Measure|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/30/world/middleeast/centrist-party-in-israel-introduces-civil-union-bill.html|journal=The New York Times|accessdate=20 January 2015|date=29 October 2013}}</ref> At the same time, [[Meretz]] proposed a civil marriage bill, which included provisions for same-sex marriages. On 8 July 2015, the Knesset rejected the [[Meretz]] and [[Yesh Atid]] bills, in a 39-50 vote,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Politics-And-Diplomacy/Knesset-shoots-down-civil-union-bills-408373 |title=Knesset shoots down civil union bills |newspaper=The Jerusalem Post |date=8 July 2015}}</ref> while Hatnuah's bill was rejected on 22 February 2016 in a 40-47 vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/day-after-marking-lgbt-rights-knesset-nixes-5-gender-equality-bills/ |author=Newman, Marissa |title=Day after marking LGBT rights, Knesset nixes 5 gender equality bills |publisher=The News of Israel |date=24 February 2016}}</ref> In June 2018, the Knesset rejected a same-sex marriage bill introduced by [[The Zionist Union]]. The bill failed by just three votes, 39-42.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishpress.com/news/breaking-news/gay-marriage-law-fails-on-3-votes-says-shaffir/2018/06/08/|title=Gay Marriage Law Fails on 3 Votes, Says Shaffir|publisher=Jewish Press|date=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5284391,00.html|title=PM brags about gay community, but Knesset rejects same-sex civil union bill|work=Ynetnews|first1=Shahar|last1=Hay|first2=Alexandra|last2=Lukash|first3=Nir|last3=Cohen|date=11 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/247165|title=Arab MKs skip vote on recognizing gay marriage|work=Israel National News|last=Baruch|first=Hezki|date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Adoption and parenting===\n[[LGBT adoption|Adoption by LGBT parents]] had only been permitted in certain restricted situations, notably when a previous connection exists between the adopting parent and the child, such as being a family member or a foster child. On 10 January 2005, the [[Supreme Court of Israel|Supreme Court]] ruled that a lesbian couple is able to legally [[Adoption|adopt]] each other's children. During the past 15 years that Tal and Avital Jarus-Hakak had lived together, they had a total of three children. The couple petitioned the Tel Aviv Family Court for the right to formally adopt each other's children in 1997, but the request was rejected because Israel's adoption law had no provisions for same-sex couples. The couple appealed. While they failed to get a favorable ruling in the Tel Aviv District Court, the Supreme Court accepted the case. Citing Article 25 of the ''Adoption of Children Law of 1981'' ({{lang-he|\u05d7\u05d5\u05e7 \u05d0\u05d9\u05de\u05d5\u05e5 \u05d9\u05dc\u05d3\u05d9\u05dd, \u05ea\u05e9\u05de\"\u05d0-1981}}; [[Arabic]]: {{lang|ar|\u0642\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u062a\u0628\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0637\u0641\u0627\u0644 1981}}), the Jarus-Hakaks argued that the law allows for \"special circumstances\" for adoption when it is for the good of the child, even if the child's parents are still alive. The only condition is that the person seeking to adopt be single. The couple argued that since the state does not recognize same-sex marriage, they are single by law. They added that adoption was in the best interest of the children if one of their natural mothers should die. The Supreme Court of Israel agreed, ruling 7\u20132 in favor of the couple. Following the Supreme Court ruling, the couple was allowed to adopt each other's biological children on 12 February 2006. Before that, the gay partner of the parent was granted guardianship over their partner's children. Lesbian couples can also legally gain access to IVF and assisted insemination.\n\nIn February 2008, a court in [[Israel]] ruled that same-sex couples are now permitted to adopt a child even if that child is not biologically related to either parent.<ref name=\"Haaretz\">[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/953097.html AG okays wider adoption rights for same-sex couples], By Yuval Yoaz, 12 February 2008.</ref> This marked a watershed in granting [[Egalitarianism|equal rights]] to all [[gay]] people in Israel.<ref name=\"Haaretz\" /> [[isRealli]], the official blog of the State of Israel, frequently publishes updates on gay adoption news in Israel. The site also has a complete timeline of [[LGBT Rights|gay rights]] milestones in Israel. On 10 March 2009, the Tel Aviv Family Court ruled that former Knesset member [[Uzi Even]] and his partner, Amit Kama, could legally adopt their 30-year-old foster son, Yossi, making them the first same-sex male couple in Israel whose right of adoption was legally acknowledged.<ref name=edelman>{{Cite news | last = Edelman | first = Ofra | title = Gay couple wins right to adopt foster son | work = Haaretz | accessdate = 2009-03-11 | date = 11 March 2009 | url = http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1070060.html}}</ref> However, same-sex couples could only adopt children heterosexual couples did not want.\n\nOn 28 January 2014, the Israel High Court of Justice ruled in favor of a May 2013 modification by Israel Attorney General Yehuda Weinstein and stated that same-sex couples in Israel could easily adopt through [[surrogacy]] so long as the biological parent in the same-sex relationship was willing to take a paternity test or present highly convincing alternative medical and legal evidence of paternity.<ref name=surrogateisrael>[http://www.jpost.com/National-News/High-Court-orders-Israel-to-recognize-gay-adoption-of-child-born-through-surrogacy-339655 HIGH COURT ORDERS ISRAEL TO RECOGNIZE GAY ADOPTION OF CHILD BORN THROUGH SURROGACY]</ref> Prior to the 2013 modification, both a paternity test by the biological parent and a lengthy legal process by the non-biological parent were required in order for a joint adoption to take place for same-sex couples participating in surrogacy.<ref name=surrogateisrael /> This ruling was further enhanced in August 2016 when the Tel Aviv Family Court ruled that Israeli same-sex couples could adopt through surrogacy from individuals residing in either Israel or from other countries.<ref name=surroisrael>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Court-Gay-adoption-of-child-born-through-surrogacy-possible-without-paternity-test-463681 COURT: GAY ADOPTION OF CHILD BORN THROUGH SURROGACY POSSIBLE WITHOUT PATERNITY TEST]</ref>\n\nIn late August 2017, the Israeli Government announced that it no longer opposes same-sex adoption and that new criteria for adoption would be enacted. Under the new criteria, the potential parents can legally adopt a child, regardless of their sexual orientation; opposite-sex and same-sex couples being given equal treatment.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/1.809647 In Complete Reversal, Israel Says It No Longer Opposes Same-sex Adoption]</ref> Previously, same-sex couples could only adopt children opposite-sex couples did not want to adopt. From 2008 to 2017, only 3 same-sex couples (out of 550 applicants) were able to adopt, compared to 1,000 opposite-sex adoptions.<ref>[https://www.thejc.com/news/israel/reversal-over-israel-s-same-sex-adoption-policy-1.443803 Reversal over Israel\u2019s same-sex adoption policy]</ref> According to a poll conducted earlier in August 2017, 60% of Israelis supported adoption rights for same-sex couples, while 33% were against.<ref name=\"ynetnews\">[https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5001831,00.html Poll finds 60% of Israelis support same-sex adoptions]</ref> As of 2019, however, the Justice Minister has blocked the criteria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-despite-promise-to-top-court-israel-still-discriminates-on-gay-adoption-1.7339552|title=Despite Promise to Top Court, Israel Still Discriminates Against Gay Couples Wanting to Adopt|work=Haaretz|date=6 June 2019|last=Yaron|first=Lee}}</ref>\n\nIsraeli surrogacy law allows opposite-sex couples to sign a surrogacy agreement with a surrogate mother. In July 2018, the Knesset passed a bill expending surrogacy rights to single women, but rejected an amendment that would have included same-sex couples. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu supported the amendment, but later voted against it due to objections from Orthodox groups. Subsequently, an estimated 100,000 people marched in Tel Aviv in protest.<ref>[https://www.i24news.tv/en/news/israel/179963-180722-thousands-to-protest-strike-over-surrogacy-law-excluding-gay-men 100,000 in Israel protest, strike over surrogacy law excluding gay men]</ref> The protests also received support from multiple companies, including [[Apple Inc.]], [[Microsoft]], [[Israir Airlines]] and many more, and an opinion poll conducted in July 2018 found that 57% of Israelis were in favour of surrogacy for same-sex couples. Despite the passage of the law, several court rulings have protected surrogacy rights for same-sex couples.<ref name=\"surroisrael\"/> In February 2020, the Israeli Supreme Court unanimously ruled that same-sex couples should be given access to surrogacy, holding that the current law harms the \"right to equality\" and gave the state one year to amend the existing legislation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/article/rkVSudHEI|title=Supreme Court rules same-sex couples be given access to surrogacy|date=2020-02-27|website=ynetnews|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, the Israeli High Court proposed to make it easier for children raised by same-sex couples to be registered on official documents with the names of both their parents. Under the proposal, the non-biological parent would have to send a notice to the Interior Ministry. However, the Israeli Government rejected this measure, and insisted that same-sex couples should receive a court order if they wish to register their child(ren) with both their names.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/amp/israel-news/.premium-israel-rejects-compromise-on-legal-requirements-for-lesbian-parents-1.6450803|title=Israel Rejects Court-proposed Compromise to List Both Members of Lesbian Couple as Parents|website=Haaretz|date=4 September 2018}}</ref> In December 2018, the [[Supreme Court of Israel|High Court of Justice]] ruled that same-sex parents have the right to be listed on their child(ren)'s birth certificates. In a landmark case, the top court ruled that the [[Ministry of Interior (Israel)|Interior Ministry]] cannot refuse this right based on the parent's sexual orientation. The ruling came after two gay men adopted a son, then tried to list both their names on his birth certificate, but government officials refused to do so. Supreme Court Justice [[Neal Hendel]] said in the decision: \"The principle of \"the good of the child\" argues for the recording of his entire family unit, and doesn't permit us to limit ourselves to only one of his parents in the birth certificate\u2026. The contrast with the treatment of a child adopted by a heterosexual couple, who has the right to have both adopted parents written in a birth certificate, is a contrast that applies both to the child and to the parents... It is unreasonable for the couple to be [legally] recognized as parents but for the certificate not to give expression to that fact.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/israel-top-court-gay-parents-birth-certificate/|title=Israel top court rules both gay parents should be put on birth certificate|work=Gay Star News|date=13 December 2018|first=James|last=Besanvalle}}</ref>\n\n===Gender identity and expression===\n{{See also|Legal aspects of transsexualism}}\nTreatment for [[gender dysphoria]] in Israel can be paid for using the country's [[Health care in Israel|public health insurance system]] if a patient receives approval by the Committee for Sex Reassignment operating out of [[Sheba Medical Center]] in [[Tel HaShomer]], which consists of an [[endocrinologist]], a [[urologist]], and a [[plastic surgeon]] and is organized by the [[Health Minister of Israel|Health Ministry]]. All [[sex reassignment surgery]] operations in Israel are furthermore performed by Dr. Haim Kaplan at [[Sheba Medical Center]] under this committee's approval. However, many [[transgender]] Israelis have had trouble getting approval for treatment by this committee due to their stringent opinions on gender dysphoria. Thus, many pay out of pocket for [[Hormone replacement therapy (transgender)|hormone replacement therapy]] and/or go overseas for [[sex reassignment surgery]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Aderet |first=Ofer |url=http://www.changelingaspects.com/PDF/Sex%20Change%20in%20Israel%20Gender%20Trap.pdf |title=Sex-change in Israel: Gender trap |date=22 June 2012 |access-date=30 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029180410/http://www.changelingaspects.com/PDF/Sex%20Change%20in%20Israel%20Gender%20Trap.pdf |archive-date=29 October 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA law was introduced to the [[Knesset]] in June 2013 to eliminate gender markers on [[Teudat Zehut|National Identity Cards]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fiske |first=Gavriel |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/mk-pushes-gender-neutral-id-cards/ |title=MK pushes gender-neutral ID cards |date=4 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nSince 2015, the Health Ministry has allowed transgender people to change legal gender without undergoing sex reassignment surgery or a sex change operation.<ref>{{Cite newspaper | title=Israel recognizes sex changes without operation | journal=Haaretz | url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/.premium-1.637786 | accessdate=2015-01-23| date=2015-01-18 | last1=Hovel | first1=Revital }}</ref>\n\n===Military service===\n{{See also|Sexual orientation and gender identity in the Israeli military}}\n[[Coming out|Openly gay]], lesbian and bisexual soldiers serve without hindrance in all branches of the military. Discrimination against gay, lesbian and bisexual soldiers in recruitment, placement and promotion is prohibited in Israel.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/16/world/tel-aviv-journal-once-taboo-a-gay-israeli-treads-the-halls-of-power.html?pagewanted=1 | work=[[The New York Times]] | title=Tel Aviv Journal; Once Taboo, a Gay Israeli Treads the Halls of Power | first=Joel | last=Greenberg | date=16 October 2002 | accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref> Harassment on the grounds of sexual orientation is also prohibited in the Israeli military. The military recognizes same-sex couples, including widows and widowers of the same sex.<ref>[http://www.izkor.gov.il/HalalKorot.aspx?id=513304 Izkor], in the Israeli Ministry of Defense site (Hebrew)</ref> Soldiers are also allowed to participate in gay [[pride parade]]s.<ref>[http://www.news1.co.il/Archive/001-D-114912-00.html Soldiers can participate in Pride Parades], News-1 (Hebrew)</ref> The [[Israeli Defense Forces]] currently does not consider [[gender dysphoria]] to be a disqualifying condition for service. Furthermore, the [[Israeli Defense Forces|IDF]] considers certain [[Transitioning (transgender)|transition]]-specific medical treatment ([[Hormone replacement therapy (transgender)|hormone replacement therapy]] and [[sex reassignment surgery]]) and [[Sex reassignment therapy#Psychological treatment|counseling]] to be medically necessary for those diagnosed with [[transsexualism]] and thus pays for said treatments. The [[Israeli Defense Forces|IDF]] also determines gender specific army regulations (length of service, which gender to be housed with, whether they are to wear a male or female uniform, etc.) on a case-by-case basis for its [[transgender]] soldiers. However, given that Israeli law makes it difficult for its transsexuals to begin transition until they reach 18, the draft age, and does not normally allow for [[sex reassignment surgery]] to be performed before the age of 21, so far the only person who underwent surgery while serving is Shachae Erez, the first openly transgender person to become an officer. Furthermore, many draftees diagnosed with gender dysphoria can receive exemption from military service at their own request.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ginsburg |first=Mitch |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/idfs-gays-find-friends-at-the-top-lingering-homophobia-on-the-ground/ |title=IDF's gays find friends at the top, lingering homophobia on the ground |date=29 July 2013}}</ref> Officially, the IDF policy does not prohibit [[intersex]] persons from [[Intersex people and military service|service]].<ref name=pmid19055190>{{cite journal |doi=10.7205/MILMED.173.11.1132 |pmid=19055190 |title=Intersex Patients in Military Service |journal=Military Medicine |volume=173 |issue=11 |pages=1132\u20135 |year=2008 |last1=Marom |first1=Tal |last2=Itskoviz |first2=David |last3=Ostfeld |first3=Ishay |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n===LGBT immigration to Israel and the Law of Return===\nOn 10 June 2011, the ''[[Law of Return]]'' was tested when a gay male couple, one Jewish and one Catholic, made Aliyah to Israel. This couple was the first same-sex,  different-religion married couple to request joint Aliyah status, although opposite-sex married couples of opposite religions receive joint Aliyah as a matter of course. The Jewish man quickly received citizenship but the decision of citizenship for his husband was delayed by the Ministry of the Interior despite the clause in the law saying the spouse of the Jewish immigrant must also be granted citizenship.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/israel-refuses-citizenship-for-gay-man-married-to-jewish-immigrant-1.369936|title=Israel refuses citizenship for gay man married to Jewish immigrant|author=Ilan Lior|date=28 June 2011|work=Haaretz.com}}</ref> On 10 August 2011, the Ministry of the Interior granted citizenship to the non-Jewish husband as required by the ''Law of Return''.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.haaretz.com/weekend/anglo-file/ministry-grants-citizenship-to-gay-spouse-of-immigrant-1.382066|title=Ministry grants citizenship to gay spouse of immigrant|author=Raphael Ahren|date=2 September 2011|work=Haaretz.com}}</ref> In 2014, Interior Minister Gidon Sa'ar officially decided that, according to the ''Law of Return'', Jews in same-sex relationships married abroad wishing to immigrate to Israel can do so - even if their partners are not Jewish - and both them and their partners will receive Israeli citizenship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/183971|title=Right of Return Extended to Gay Couples|work=Arutz Sheva}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, [[Attorney General of Israel|Attorney General]] [[Avichai Mandelblit]] issued an instruction to Israel's Interior Ministry to consider applications for citizenship by same-sex and opposite-sex couples equally under the same terms. The same-sex spouse of an Israeli will now be able to claim Israeli citizenship at the same speed as an opposite-sex spouse. Previously, same-sex couples had to wait up to seven years, and would generally only be granted permanent residency rather than citizenship. The process was far quicker for opposite-sex couples.<ref name=\"pink\">[http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2016/12/10/israel-is-to-begin-recognising-same-sex-marriage-as-an-equal-route-to-citizenship/ Israel is to begin recognising same-sex marriage as an equal route to citizenship] Pink News</ref> The decision came in response to a lawsuit filed before the High Court of Justice by the Gay Fathers Association.\n\n===Discrimination protections===\nLGBT couples in Israel have the same\npension, inheritance and medical rights as\nheterosexual couples.<ref name=lgbtprotection />  In 1992, legislation was passed into law to prohibit [[employment discrimination]] on the basis of [[sexual orientation]],<ref name=lgbtprotection>[http://www.keshetuk.org/uploads/1/3/8/6/13861493/keshet_uk_factsheet_israel_mar13_v3.pdf Life for LGBT people in Israel]</ref> with some exemptions for religious organizations. In 1997, an amendment was added to the nation's ''Libel and Slander Law''.<ref name=isrgahat>[http://embassies.gov.il/la/AboutIsrael/IsraelExperience/Pages/Gay-Israel.aspx Gay Israel]</ref> The amendment broadened the prohibition of uttering and publishing defamation and slander, motivated by the sexual orientation of a person.<ref name=isrgahat /> Moreover, the law specifies that every violent crime, motivated by sexual orientation, shall be considered a hate crime, doubling the punishment.<ref name=isrgahat /> The ''[[Prohibition of Discrimination in Products, Services and Entry into Places of Entertainment and Public Places Law, 2000]]'' ({{lang-he|\u05d7\u05d5\u05e7 \u05d0\u05d9\u05e1\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d4\u05e4\u05dc\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d1\u05de\u05d5\u05e6\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd, \u05d1\u05e9\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea\u05d9\u05dd \u05d5\u05d1\u05db\u05e0\u05d9\u05e1\u05d4 \u05dc\u05de\u05e7\u05d5\u05de\u05d5\u05ea \u05d1\u05d9\u05d3\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d5\u05dc\u05de\u05e7\u05d5\u05de\u05d5\u05ea \u05e6\u05d9\u05d1\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd}}; [[Arabic]]: {{lang|ar|\u062d\u0638\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0645\u064a\u064a\u0632 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u062a\u062c\u0627\u062a \u0648\u0627\u0644\u062e\u062f\u0645\u0627\u062a \u0648\u0627\u0644\u062f\u062e\u0648\u0644 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u0623\u0645\u0627\u0643\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0631\u0641\u064a\u0647 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0627\u0643\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645\u0629}}) prohibits discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation, among others, on the part of those who provide products, public services or operate public places.\n\nSince 2014, LGBT youth have been protected at different schools around the country.<ref>[http://www.glaad.org/blog/israeli-parliament-bans-discrimination-against-lgbt-youth-schools Israeli Parliament bans discrimination against LGBT youth in schools]</ref>\n\n===Conversion therapy===\n[[Conversion therapy]] has a negative effect on the lives of LGBT people, and can lead to low self-esteem, depression and suicide ideation. It commonly includes [[Electroconvulsive therapy|electroshock therapy]], forced [[chemical castration]], [[exorcism]], the administration of nausea-inducing drugs, and especially talk therapy.\n\nIn October 2014, the Ministry of Health issued a statement announcing that it considers conversion therapy to \"create false impressions of scientific recognition even though there is no scientific evidence that it is at all successful. It may also cause harm to the individual.\"<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Health/Health-Ministry-warns-against-conversion-therapy-for-homosexuals-378122 Health Ministry warns against conversion therapy for homosexuals]</ref> The Ministry created a complaints committee to investigate allegations of conversion therapy by mental health professionals. According to February 2017 reports, none of the 20 complaints filed had been dealt with by the committee. The committee is supposed to convene monthly. Several MKs, namely Yael German and [[Eyal Ben-Reuven]], have called the committee \"dysfunctional\".<ref name=\"therapy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.jpost.com/Business-and-Innovation/Health-and-Science/Health-Min-complaints-committee-on-conversion-therapy-is-dysfunctional-496787|title=HEALTH MIN. COMPLAINTS COMMITTEE ON CONVERSION THERAPY IS DYSFUNCTIONAL|newspaper=The Jerusalem Post|date=14 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, the [[Knesset]] rejected a bill introduced by former Health Minister [[Yael German]] that would have banned conversion therapy in Israel for minors. The bill was rejected 37-45.<ref>[http://www.timesofisrael.com/day-after-marking-lgbt-rights-knesset-nixes-5-gender-equality-bills/ Day after marking LGBT rights, Knesset nixes 5 gender equality bills]</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, the [[Israel Medical Association]], which represents about 90% of all doctors in Israel, explicitly banned all its members from performing any conversion therapy on patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/israeli-doctors-ban-conversion-therapy-for-gay-people-1.6828815|title=Israeli Doctors Ban 'Conversion Therapy' for Gay People|work=Haaretz|date=10 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, interim [[Ministry of Education (Israel)|Minister of Education]] [[Rafi Peretz]] attracted criticism after he endorsed the pseudoscientific practice and claimed to have personally performed such therapies. Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] rejected Peretz's comments as unacceptable, saying they \"do not represent [his] government's position\" and that \"[he] made it clear to him that the Israeli educational system will continue to accept all Jewish children whoever they are and without any difference based on sexual orientation.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Dalton |first=Jane |date=14 July 2019 |title=Gay conversion therapy works and I\u2019ve given it, says Israeli education minister |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/gay-conversion-therapy-israel-minister-rafi-peretz-lgbt-netanyahu-a9004396.html |work=[[The Independent]] |location= |access-date=14 July 2019}}</ref> Thousands of Israeli teachers signed a petition demanding Perez's dismissal,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/middle-east/calls-for-sacking-of-israeli-minister-over-gay-conversion-support-1.3957529|title=Calls for sacking of Israeli minister over 'gay conversion' support|work=The Irish Times|date=15 July 2019|last=Weiss|first=Mark}}</ref> and more than a thousand people protested his comments in Tel Aviv and in Peretz's hometown calling for his resignation, with the presence of former Israeli Prime Minister [[Ehud Barak]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/hundreds-rally-for-ouster-of-israeli-education-minister-after-gay-conversion-remarks-1.7500130|title=Hundreds Rally For Ouster Of Israeli Education Minister After Gay Conversion Remarks|work=Haaretz|date=14 July 2019}}</ref> Days later, Peretz backtracked from his comments, calling conversion therapy \"inappropriate,\" but added that \"individuals with a homosexual orientation have the right to receive professional help\".<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/israeli-education-minister-backtracks-on-gay-therapy-comments-11726516|title=Israeli education minister backtracks on gay therapy comments|work=Channel News Asia|date=17 July 2019|location=Jerusalem}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israel-s-education-minister-now-says-he-opposes-gay-conversion-therapy-1.7532713|title=Israel's Education Minister Now Says He Opposes Gay 'Convesion Therapy'|work=Haaretz|date=16 July 2019}}</ref> Following his comments, hundreds of LGBT Israelis recounted their \"painful\" and \"destructive\" experiences with conversion therapy.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.timesofisrael.com/i-survived-abusive-religious-conversion-therapy/|title=I survived abusive religious 'conversion' therapy|work=Jewish News|date=17 July 2019|last=Hyman|first=Joe}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.israelhayom.com/opinions/weve-seen-the-damage-conversion-therapy-causes/|title=We've seen the damage 'conversion therapy' causes|work=Israel Hayom|date=16 July 2019|last=Friedman|first=Aviad}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2019/07/16/orthodoxy-and-gay-conversion-therapy/|title=Orthodoxy and Gay Conversion Therapy|work=The Algemeiner|date=16 July 2019|last=Boteach|first=Shmuley}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/gay-israelis-come-forward-to-decry-predatory-harmful-conversion-therapy/|title=Gay Israelis come forward to describe predatory, harmful conversion therapy|work=The Times of Israel|date=15 July 2019|last=Staff|first=Toi}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Conversion-therapy-can-kill-Religious-LGBT-community-members-speak-out-596082|title=Conversion therapy can kill: Religious LGBT community members speak out|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=19 July 2019|last=Joffre|first=Tzvi}}</ref>\n\nSeveral conversion therapy advocates and licensed professionals have moved to Israel from the [[United States]], due to [[List of U.S. jurisdictions banning conversion therapy|a growing number of bans]] on the [[Pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]] practice there.<ref name=\"therapy\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/amp/israel-news/.premium-the-constituency-that-keeps-conversion-therapy-legal-in-israel-1.7500412|title=The Constituency That Keeps 'Conversion Therapy' Legal in Israel|work=Haaretz|date=15 July 2019|last=Efrati|first=Ido}}</ref> The Israel Psychological Association opposes conversion therapy.<ref name=\"therapy\"/>\n\nIn July 2019, an opinion published in ''[[Haaretz]]'' called for an outright legal ban on the practice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/opinion/.premium-time-to-ban-conversion-therapy-1.7532421|title=Opinion // Time To Ban 'Conversion Therapy'|work=Haaretz|date=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Blood donation===\nSince 1 June 2017, gay and bisexual men in Israel have been allowed to legally donate blood following a one-year deferral period.<ref>[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4975976,00.html Israel finally receives blood donations from gays and Ethiopian immigrants]</ref> However, no deferral was in place for lesbians or bisexual women.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mdais.org/%D7%A9%D7%90%D7%9C%D7%95%D7%AA-%D7%95%D7%AA%D7%A9%D7%95%D7%91%D7%95%D7%AA-%D7%A9%D7%99%D7%A8%D7%95%D7%AA%D7%99-%D7%94%D7%93%D7%9D/%D7%9E%D7%99-%D7%99%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%9C-%D7%9C%D7%90-%D7%99%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%9C-%D7%9C%D7%AA%D7%A8%D7%95%D7%9D-%D7%93%D7%9D |title=Who may/may not donate blood? |publisher=[[Magen David Adom]] (in Hebrew)}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, the Health Ministry approved new regulations allowing gay and bisexual men to donate blood, regardless of when they last had sex; just like for straight men.<ref>[http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/01/11/israel-to-allow-gay-and-bisexual-men-to-donate-blood-regardless-of-when-they-last-had-sex/ Israel to allow gay and bisexual men to donate blood \u2013 regardless of when they last had sex]</ref>\n\n===Other court rulings===\n* The [[Supreme Court of Israel|Supreme Court]] ruled on 30 November 1994 that the partner of a gay employee at [[El Al]], Israel's national airline, is entitled to free airline tickets just as the spouse of any heterosexual employee is.<ref>[http://www.icj.org/sogicasebook/el-al-israel-airlines-ltd-v-danielowitz-israeli-supreme-court-sitting-as-the-high-court-of-justice-30-november-1994/ El-Al Israel Airlines Ltd v. Danielowitz, Israeli Supreme Court sitting as the High Court of Justice (30 November 1994)]</ref>\n* The Supreme Court recognized in May 2000 a lesbian as the adoptive mother of the four-year-old biological son of her same-sex partner, and ordered the [[Interior Ministry]] to register the adoption.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/may/30/israel Israel grants rights to lesbian mothers]</ref>\n* An Israeli family court on 17 March 2002 turned down an application from a lesbian couple to have their partnership union declared legal. The couple was united in a [[Same-sex marriage in Germany|civil ceremony in Germany]]. The women wanted the court to recognize their partnership as a civil marriage under Israeli law. The court said that since the women are not recognized as a family under Israeli law, the court is not authorized to rule on their case. A government lawyer who was asked by the court to give a legal opinion on the case on behalf of the Israeli Government said that the state objected to granting the request.<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/1.5228258 Court Rejects Lesbians' Bid for Recognition as a Couple], ''Haaretz'', 18 March 2002</ref>\n* On 14 November 2004, the [[Nazareth]] District Court ruled that same-sex couples have the same [[inheritance]] rights as married couples. This ruling overturned a Family Court ruling that an elderly man from [[Kiryat Shmona]] was not entitled to spousal rights. The man had sought the estate of his late partner, with whom he lived for several decades. The Nazareth judges ruled that the term \"man and woman\" as spelled out in Israel's inheritance law also includes same-sex couples. Judges Nissim Maman and Gabriela Levy, who issued the majority opinion, based their decision on a loose interpretation of the term \"partner\" as defined in other court rulings, such as those dealing with issues related to [[employee benefit]]s, and thus applied the interpretation to the inheritance law. The acting president of the Nazareth District Court, Menachem Ben-David, issued the minority opinion, arguing that the legal text should not be interpreted \"contrary to the lingual significance.\" A government spokesperson said the ruling would be appealed.<ref>[https://www.haaretz.com/1.4756574 Nazareth Court Sets Precedent in Same-sex Couple Case, ''Haaretz'', 15 November 2004]</ref>\n* In December 2004, the Tel Aviv District Court ruled that the Government cannot [[Deportation|deport]] the Colombian partner of a gay Israeli man. The 32-year-old Colombian entered Israel on a visitors [[Visa (document)|visa]] which had long expired and the Interior Ministry had ordered him deported. His partner is an Israeli citizen and a soldier in the Israel Defense Forces. The couple filed an emergency petition with the Tel Aviv District Court. The men were represented by the [[Association for Civil Rights in Israel]]. Judge [[Uzi Vogelman]] ruled that the Government had acted illegally in attempting to deport the man. In 1999, Supreme Court ruling established that the ministry could not deport foreign nationals married to Israeli citizens. Vogelman's decision extends that decision to apply to common-law marriages, including same-sex couples.<ref>[https://www.acri.org.il/en/2008/02/07/the-immigration-rights-of-same-sex-couples/ The immigration rights of same-sex couples], ''Association for Civil Rights in Israel</ref>\n* In March 2008, Israel's Interior Ministry granted a gay Palestinian from [[Jenin]] a rare residency permit to live with his partner of 8 years in Tel Aviv after he said his sexuality put his life in danger in the [[West Bank]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/lifestyleMolt/idUKL2586865820080325 | work=Reuters | title=Gay Palestinian gets OK to live with Israeli lover | date=25 March 2008}}</ref>\n* In 2012, the first same-sex Israeli couple was granted a divorce by an Israeli family court. The divorce of Tel Aviv University Professor [[Uzi Even]], the first openly gay Knesset member, and Dr. Amit Kama was granted by the Ramat Gan Family Court, according to [[Haaretz]], which ordered the Interior Minister to register their status as divorced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/breaking-news/israel-grants-first-gay-divorce|title=Israel Grants First Gay Divorce - The Jewish Week|work=The Jewish Week}}</ref>\n* In December 2016, [[Attorney General of Israel|Attorney General]] [[Avichai Mandelblit]] issued an instruction to Israel's Interior Ministry to consider applications for citizenship by same-sex and opposite-sex couples equally under the same terms.<ref name=\"pink\"/>\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:Flickr - Government Press Office (GPO) - P.M Ariel Sharon meeting with representatives of the Homosexual and Lesbian community.jpg|thumb|[[Ariel Sharon]] meeting with representatives of the LGBT community in [[Jerusalem]], 2002]]\n[[File:2013-03-30 Ostermarsch Hannover vom Kr\u00f6pcke aus, Regenbogenfahne Frieden Peace hebr\u00e4isch Schalom arabisch Salam.jpg|thumb|[[Rainbow flag]] with ''[[Shalom]]'' and ''[[\u0160-L-M|Salaam]]'' meaning ''[[peace]]'' in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] and [[Arabic language|Arabic]] respectively]]\nIsrael's [[Labor (Israel)|Labor Party]] and [[Meretz]] support LGBT rights, as did the now-defunct [[Shinui]]. Under [[Tzipi Livni]], [[Kadima]] has reached out to the LGBT community.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mozgovaya |first=Natasha |url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1089783.html |title=Livni, Clinton voice support for gay community in Israel and U.S |publisher=Haaretz.com |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1104611.html|title=Livni to gay Israelis: Don't let hate crime stop you living your lives|author=Ben Hartman|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]|date=2 August 2009}}</ref> Other minor liberal or progressive political parties support a similar platform as well, including the [[The Greens (Israel)|Greens]] and the [[Ale Yarok|Green Leaf Party]]. Officials from a number of parties, including [[Yael German]] of [[Yesh Atid]], [[Limor Livnat]] of the ruling [[Likud]]-[[Yisrael Beiteinu|Beiteinu]], and openly gay [[Nitzan Horowitz]] of [[Meretz]], back [[same-sex marriage]] and have pledged support for LGBT causes. Representatives from other parties, including [[Hatnuah]], [[Hadash]] and the [[Israeli Labour Party|Labor Party]], have also pledged support. Minister and MK [[Limor Livnat]], however, did state that getting the ruling [[Likud Yisrael Beiteinu|Likud-Beiteinu]] to legislate same-sex marriage would be difficult due to differing opinions concerning the issue within the party, but promised to do her utmost to get her party behind the issue.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/israel%E2%80%99s-politicians-give-unprecedent-pledge-legislate-pro-gay-laws060113|title=Party representatives discuss same-sex marriage}}</ref> Ahead of the [[April 2019 Israeli legislative election|April 2019 legislative election]], [[Yisrael Beiteinu]], one of the more conservative political parties in the country, announced that its doors were open to everyone regardless of their [[sexual orientation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Opinion/A-proud-Knesset-594116|title=A Proud Knesset|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 October 2002, [[Meretz]] MK [[Uzi Even]] made history by becoming the first openly gay member of the Knesset. Five more openly gay Israelis - [[Nitzan Horowitz]], [[Itzik Shmuli|Itzik Smuli]], [[Yorai Lahav-Hertzano]], [[Idan Roll]] and [[Amir Ohana]] - have been elected to the Knesset since then.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/outward/2016/01/19/amir_ohana_likud_s_first_openly_gay_knesset_member_interviewed.html|title=Israel\u2019s First Openly Gay Likud Lawmaker on Being in a Coalition With Anti-Gay Parties|last=Hoare|first=Liam|date=2016-01-19|newspaper=Slate|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref> In 2019, after the [[April 2019 Israeli legislative election|2019 general elections]], a record-breaking of 5 openly gay MKs got elected. They are [[Itzik Shmuli|Itzik Smuli]] ([[Israeli Labor Party|Labor]]), [[Amir Ohana]] ([[Likud]]), [[Eitan Ginzburg]], [[Idan Roll]] and [[Yorai Lahav-Hertzano]] (each being a member of [[Blue and White (political alliance)|Blue and White]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/amp/israel-news/elections/.premium-israelis-poised-for-their-gayest-parliament-yet-1.7001257|title=Israelis Poised for Their Gayest Parliament Yet|work=Haaretz|date=10 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the city of [[Ra'anana]] elected [[Eitan Ginzburg]] (he later became an MK) as mayor, making him the first openly gay mayor in Israel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.jpost.com/Israel-News/Raanana-gets-countrys-first-gay-mayor-546533|title=TEL AVIV SUBURB GETS COUNTRY\u2019S FIRST GAY MAYOR|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=20 March 2018|last=Hoffman|first=Gil}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ahead of the [[September 2019 Israeli legislative election|September 2019 legislative election]], [[Nitzan Horowitz]] successfully challenged incumbent [[Tamar Zandberg]] for the leadership of [[Meretz]], which made Meretz the first Israeli party to elect an openly gay person as its leader.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/israels-meretz-party-becomes-first-to-elect-an-openly-gay-leader |title=Israel's Meretz party becomes country's first to elect an openly gay leader - Jewish Telegraphic Agency |publisher=Jta.org |date= |accessdate=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Israel's first gay party leader Nitzan Horowitz elected head of Meretzr (sic)|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Meretz-now-has-new-leader-Nitzan-Horowitz-593944|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=27 June 2019 |accessdate=27 June 2019|author=Jeremy Sharon}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, [[Prime Minister of Israel|Prime Minister]] [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] appointed [[Evan Cohen]], a linguist and LGBT rights activist, as the foreign media spokesperson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.jpost.com/Israel-News/LGBT-Likud-leader-appointed-Netanyahus-English-spokesman-595626|title=New Netanyahu Spokesman To 'Post': Not Appointed Because I'm Gay|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=15 July 2019|last=Hoffman|first=Gil}}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, there still have been anti-gay politicians. In 1997, [[President of Israel|President]] [[Ezer Weizman]] compared homosexuality to alcoholism in front of high school students.<ref>Silver, Ian. [http://www.betham.org/kulanu/iansilver.html Homosexuality And Judaism] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070831131848/http://www.betham.org/kulanu/iansilver.html |date=31 August 2007 }}</ref> This provoked major controversy, and the President received numerous calls from [[civil rights]] activists and liberal [[Knesset]] members. Shortly following, 300 people demonstrated outside of Weizman's residence, demanding his resignation. He later apologised for these statements.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/5219/edition_id/96/format/html/displaystory.html |title=Israeli president apologizes for his anti-gay statements |publisher=Jewishsf.com |date=3 January 1997 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> On 20 February 2008, Shlomo Benizri, a Knesset member from the religious [[Shas]] party, a member of Prime Minister [[Ehud Olmert]]'s ruling coalition, blamed earthquakes that had recently struck the Middle East on the activities of homosexuals. Benizri said in a Knesset plenary session, \"Why do earthquakes happen? ... One of the reasons is the things to which the Knesset gives legitimacy, to sodomy.\" He recommended that instead of merely reinforcing buildings to withstand earthquakes, the Government should pass legislation to outlaw \"perversions like adoptions by gay couples\". Benizri stated that, \"A cost-effective way of averting earthquake damage would be to stop passing legislation on how to encourage homosexual activity in the State of Israel, which anyways causes earthquakes.\"<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/956334.html Shas MK blames gays for recent earthquakes in the region]</ref>\n\nIn 2015, [[Bezalel Smotrich]], a Knesset member from the [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]]-religious [[Jewish Home]] party, referred to LGBT people as \"abnormal\", stating: \"At home, everyone can be abnormal, and people can form whatever family unit they want. But they can't make demands from me, as the state.\" In the same discussion, he told the audience, \"I am a proud [[homophobia|homophobe]]\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Jewish Home hopeful boasts of being \u2018proud homophobe\u2019|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/jewish-home-hopeful-boasts-of-being-proud-homophobe|publisher=The Times of Israel|date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> He later apologized, and retracted his statement, saying: \"Someone shouted from the crowd, and I responded inattentively\".<ref>{{cite news|title=MK Smotrich: The government I'll be part of, will not recognize same-sex couples.|url=http://news.nana10.co.il/Article/?ArticleID=1121758|publisher=Nana10|date=April 19, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151224005930/http://news.nana10.co.il/Article/?ArticleID=1121758|archivedate=December 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Netanyahu Government will not recognize same-sex marriage|url=http://gogay.co.il/item.php?id=18829|publisher=GoGay.co.il|date=April 19, 2015}}</ref> In July 2015, after the Jerusalem LGBT pride stabbing, Smotrich called it a \"beast parade\", and refused to retract his homophobic remarks.<ref name=\"jpost.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Politics-And-Diplomacy/Religious-Zionist-lawmaker-refuses-to-back-down-says-homosexuality-an-abomination-410934|title=SMOTRICH: LGBT COMMUNITY ATTACKS, SLANDERS ANYONE WHO THINKS DIFFERENTLY FROM THEM|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=2 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.haaretz.com/beta/1.669230|title=Right-wing MK: Jerusalem Pride Parade Is an 'Abomination'|journal=Haaretz|date=2 August 2015}}</ref> In August 2015, Smotrich accused LGBT organizations of controlling the media, claiming they use their control to gain public sympathy and silence those who share his conservative views.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4690957,00.html|title=Bayit Yehudi MK: Gays control the media|work=Ynetnews|date=15 August 2018|last=Karni|first=Tuval}}</ref> An Israeli NGO, Ometz, filed a complaint with the Knesset Ethics Committee to intervene and investigate Smotrich's comments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/ngo-files-complaint-against-mk-for-gays-control-the-media-remark/|title=NGO files complaint against MK for 'Gays control the media' remark|work=The Times of Israel|date=16 August 2015|last=Pileggi|first=Tamar}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February 2016, the Knesset marked the first LGBT rights day, but on 24 February 2016, the parties that form the governing coalition, [[Likud]], [[United Torah Judaism]], [[Shas]], [[Kulanu]], and [[the Jewish Home]], supported by opposition members, defeated bills to recognize bereaved [[widower]]s, ban [[conversion therapy]], recognize [[same-sex marriage]], and train health professionals to deal with gender and sexual orientation issues.<ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-knesset-scraps-bills-for-lgbt-community-1.5409191 |title=Knesset Scraps Bills for LGBT Community After Marking Gay Rights Day |journal=Haaretz |last=Lis |first=Jonathan |date=25 February 2016 |access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nTwo days before the [[April 2019 Israeli legislative election|April 2019 legislative election]], Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] hosted a group of representatives of the LGBT community at the Prime Minister's residence for the first time in 10 years. Although the meeting was described as \"warm\" and \"good\", representatives of the LGBT community however were disappointed after the meeting ended with the refusal of Netanyahu to make promises to advance pro-LGBT legislation due to the pressure of right-wing religious and ultra-Orthodox coalition parties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.jpost.com/Israel-News/Benjamin-Netanyahu/Netanyahu-meets-with-LGBT-activists-wont-promise-push-in-coalition-talks-586013|title=NETANYAHU MEETS WITH LGBT ACTIVISTS, WON\u2019T PROMISE PUSH IN COALITION TALKS|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=7 April 2019|last=Harkov|first=Lahav}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/261492|title='Netanyahu refuses to commit to LGBT agenda'|work=Arutz Sheva|date=7 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.israelhayom.com/2019/04/08/i-hear-you-i-will-work-for-you-pm-tells-lgbt-community-leaders/|title=\u2018I hear you, I will work for you,\u2019 PM tells LGBTQ leaders|work=Israel Hayom|date=8 April 2019|last=Kahana|first=Ariel}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-meets-with-lgbt-leaders-for-first-time-in-10-years/|title=Netanyahu meets with LGBT leaders for first time in 10 years|work=The Times of Israel|date=7 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, interim [[Ministry of Education (Israel)|Education Ministe]] [[Rafi Peretz]] attracted criticism from when he endorsed [[conversion therapy]]. Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] rejected Peretz's comments as unacceptable, saying that they \"do not represent [his] government's position\" and that \"[he] made it clear to him that the Israeli educational system will continue to accept all Jewish children whoever they are and without any difference based on sexual orientation.\" Thousands of Israeli teachers signed a petition demanding his sacking,<ref name=\":0\"/> and more than a thousand people protested his comments in Tel Aviv and in Peretz's hometown,  calling for his dismissal.<ref name=\":1\"/> Days layer, Peretz backtracked from his comments, labelling conversion therapy \"inappropriate,\" but added that \"individuals with a homosexual orientation have the right to receive professional help\".<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\":3\"/><ref name=\":4\"/><ref name=\":5\"/><ref name=\":6\"/><ref name=\":7\"/><ref name=\":8\"/>\n\n==Society==\n\n===Living conditions===\n[[File:Tel Aviv Gay Pride Parade 2015 (18549971060).jpg|thumb|The 2015 [[Tel Aviv Pride]] parade]]\n[[File:Tel Aviv Gay Pride Parade 2018 (1528881).jpg|right|thumb|The 2018 Tel Aviv Pride parade]]\n[[File:Two flags meet (7700750632).jpg|thumb|right|An LGBT and Israeli flag at the 2012 [[Jerusalem gay pride parade|Jerusalem Pride parade]]]]\n\nIsrael has an active [[LGBT community]], with well attended annual gay [[Pride parade|pride festivals]],<ref>{{cite web|author=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0442 |url=http://www.jerusalemshots.com/cat_en91.html |title=Jerusalem Photos :: People, Demonstrations |publisher=Jerusalemshots.com |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/jun/10/tel-aviv-gay-pride-parade|title=Tel Aviv's Gay Pride parade draws thousands to the city|author=Sherwood, Harriet|journal=[[The Guardian]]|date=2011-10-05|accessdate=2012-05-17}}</ref> held in [[Tel Aviv Pride|Tel Aviv]] and [[Jerusalem gay pride parade|Jerusalem]] since 1998. Pride events are also held regularly in [[Haifa]], [[Petah Tikva]], [[Hadera]], [[Ra'anana]], [[Eilat]], and [[Rishon LeZion]]. In 2016, the first-ever pride parade scheduled in [[Beersheba]] was cancelled by the [[Supreme Court (Israel)|Israeli Supreme Court]] due to security concerns.<ref name=\"jtafirstbeershebagaypride\">{{cite news|title=First Beersheba gay pride march canceled over route change|url=http://www.jta.org/2016/07/14/news-opinion/israel-middle-east/first-beersheba-gay-pride-march-canceled-over-route-change|accessdate=July 17, 2016|work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|date=July 14, 2016}}</ref> Israel is one of only eleven foreign countries to have a chapter of the U.S. group [[PFLAG]], called [[Tehila (organization)|Tehila]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tehila.org.il/ |title=\u05ea\u05d4\u05dc\"\u05d4 &#124; \u05d0\u05ea\u05dd \u05dc\u05d0 \u05dc\u05d1\u05d3 &#124; \u05d3\u05e3 \u05d4\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea |publisher=Tehila.org.il |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref>\n\nThe Jerusalem parade gained international coverage when three marchers were stabbed in 2005. The perpetrator was subsequently sentenced to twelve years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3212934,00.html |title=Gay Parade stabber gets 12 years in prison \u2013 Israel News, Ynetnews |publisher=Ynetnews.com |date=20 June 1995 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> An attempt by Jerusalem's mayor, a [[Haredi]] Jew, to thwart Jerusalem Pride in June 2005 had been challenged in the courts. The mayor lost and was ordered to contribute funds to the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3099922,00.html |title=Gays slam Jerusalem mayor \u2013 Israel News, Ynetnews |publisher=Ynetnews.com |date=20 June 1995 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> The [[World Pride]] Festival was planned for [[Jerusalem]] in August 2005, despite protests and opposition from members of the three major religions in Jerusalem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2006-07-26/news/17302820_1_lesbian-gay-jerusalem-open-house|title=Broad opposition to World Pride in Jerusalem / Religious, gay leaders criticize international event; crisis in Lebanon ends parade plans|work=SFGate|date=2006-07-26}}</ref> However, it was postponed due to [[Israel's unilateral disengagement plan|Israel's pullout from the Gaza Strip]], which required the presence of most Israeli police forces and would thus leave the parade with little to no security. However, that parade had been plagued with threats of violence, as well as consistent grandstanding against it by some Jewish, Muslim and Christian leaders and members of the Knesset.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3271831,00.html |title=Gay leader not daunted by Muslim threat \u2013 Israel News, Ynetnews |publisher=Ynetnews.com |date=20 June 1995 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> In November 2006, more than two thousand members of the [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] community jammed into streets in an Orthodox neighbourhood in a show of force aimed at pressuring authorities into cancelling the [[gay pride]] parade to be held in [[Jerusalem]]. About a dozen people were reported injured.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.365gay.com/Newscon06/11/110206jerusalem.htm |title=3rd Night of Anti-Gay Riots in Jerusalem |date=2 November 2006 |publisher=365Gay.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926215949/http://www.365gay.com/Newscon06/11/110206jerusalem.htm |archivedate=26 September 2007}}</ref> Six people were stabbed in 2015.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-33726634|title=Jerusalem Gay Pride: Six stabbed 'by ultra-Orthodox Jew'|journal=BBC News|date=2015-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/30/middleeast/jerusalem-gay-pride-parade-stabbings/|title=6 stabbed at Jerusalem gay pride parade, police say - CNN.com|author=[[Oren Liebermann]] and Jason Hanna, CNN|date=30 July 2015|work=CNN}}</ref> One of the victims, 16-year-old Shira Banki, died of her wounds at the [[Hadassah Medical Center]] three days later, on 2 August 2015.<ref name=\"pinknewsjoe\">{{cite news |author=Joe Williams |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/08/02/victim-of-jerusalem-pride-attack-dies-of-injuries/ |title=Victim of Jerusalem Pride attack dies of injuries] |newspaper=[[PinkNews]] |date=2 August 2015}}</ref> The number of Jerusalem pride participants after the 2015 attack was smaller than in years past. In 2016, some 25,000 took part, many in solidarity with the LGBT community following the deadly stabbing attack,<ref name=\"march\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/ten-thousand-march-in-jerusalem-pride-parade-under-heavy-security/|title=Over 10,000 march in Jerusalem Pride Parade under heavy security|work=The Times of Israel|date=6 June 2019}}</ref> while in 2017, at least 22,000 marched in the parade.<ref name=\"march\"/> In 2018, at least 20,000 marched in the parade.<ref name=\"march\"/> On 6 June 2019, around 15,000 people marched at the event, under tight security with a reported 2,500 security personnel. At least 49 people who wanted to violenty disturb the event were arrested.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/gay-justice-minister-joins-jerusalem-pride-event-but-not-everyones-celebrating/|title=Gay justice minister joins Jerusalem Pride event, but not everyone's celebrating|work=The Times of Israel|date=6 June 2019|last=Horovitz|first=David}}</ref>\n\n[[Tel Aviv Pride]] is one of the largest pride parades in the world. There were 200,000 participants reported in 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/thousands-crowd-tel-aviv-streets-for-annal-pride-parade/ | title=200,000 crowd Tel Aviv streets for annual pride parade | newspaper=Times of Israel | accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref> The parade is the biggest pride celebration in continental [[Asia]], drawing more than 200,000 people in 2017, approximately 30,000 of them tourists.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/over-200000-attend-tel-aviv-gay-pride-parade-30000-from-abroad/|title=Over 200,000 attend Tel Aviv Gay Pride Parade, some 30,000 from abroad|journal=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=2017-06-09|accessdate=2017-07-29}}</ref> There were more than 250,000 participants reported in 2018,<ref>{{cite news |title=Tel Aviv pride parade draws 250,000 Israelis, foreigners |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/tel-aviv-pride-parade-draws-250-000-israelis-foreigners-n881466 |work=NBC News |date=8 June 2018}}</ref> and again more than 250,000 participants in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.i24news.tv/fr/actu/israel/societe/1560513404-tel-aviv-plus-d-un-quart-de-million-de-participants-au-defile-de-la-gay-pride|title=Tel Aviv: plus de 250.000 participants au d\u00e9fil\u00e9 de la Gay Pride|work=i24 News|date=14 June 2019|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Tel-Aviv-Pride-Parade-kicks-off-for-21st-time-with-theme-The-Struggle-Continues-592539|title=Tel Aviv Pride Parade Held With 250,000 Attendants Celebrating LGBTQ|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=16 June 2019|last=Dennen|first=Sydney}}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2009, an unknown assailant opened fire at Tel Aviv's main LGBT youth center, the [[2009 Tel Aviv gay centre shooting|Barnoar]], killing two and injuring fifteen others.<ref>Gross, Aeyal, \u201cThe Politics of LGBT Rights in Israel\u201d, Columbia Human Rights Law Review vol. 46, no. 2 (Winter 2015): 106-109</ref> The attack sent shockwaves throughout the worldwide gay community and throughout Israel, sparking an immense reaction throughout the country. Before this attack, it had only been mainly left-leaning politicians that supported the LGBT community in Israel.<ref>Gross, Aeyal, \u201cThe Politics of LGBT Rights in Israel\u201d, Columbia Human Rights Law Review vol. 46, no. 2 (Winter 2015): 110</ref> The issue for LGBT rights and acceptance began to slowly shift towards the center of Israel's political spectrum. This shift had slowly begun when Israel's Foreign Minister [[Tzipi Livni]] appeared at gay pride events in the months prior to the shooting. However, in the aftermath of this massacre, right-wing politicians began to publicly show their support for the gay community.\n\nOn 6 October 2016, Finance Minister [[Moshe Kahlon]] announced that the Israel Government had issued an order to give a divided 10 million [[Israeli new shekel|shekels]] to various governments over a two-year period to examine the nation's LGBT community for possible discriminations. A leading LGBT nonprofit called the move historic and ''[[Haaretz]]'' journalist Ilan Lior noted that it would even result in a major examination of issues such as the MSM blood transfusion restrictions.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-1.746166 In Historic Move, Israel Radically Increases Funding for LGBT Community]</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, in a report to [[President of Israel|President]] [[Reuven Rivlin]] by the LGBT association [[The Aguda \u2013 Israel's LGBT Task Force]], it was revealed that in 2018 there had been a 54% increase in homophobic incidents compared to 2017. The report highlighted that an anti-gay incident takes place about every ten hours on average in Israel. On social networks, a homophobic comment is detected every four minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fr.timesofisrael.com/hausse-de-54-des-incidents-homophobes-en-israel-en-2018/|title=Hausse de 54 % des incidents homophobes en Isra\u00ebl en 2018/|work=The Times of Israel|date=11 February 2019|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, [[Shlomo Amar]], the [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardic]] [[Chief Rabbi]] of [[Jerusalem]], was criticised for stating that gay people cannot be religious by saying that \"They aren't religious. It would be better if they cast off their kippah and Shabbat [observance] and show their true faces.\", and advocating for the pseudoscientific practice of [[conversion therapy]]. Ne'emanei Torah Va'Avodah and the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) criticised his comments. Jerusalem councilmembers Yossi Chavilov and Laura Warton called for the removal of Amar from his post as rabbi, as did openly gay politician [[Avi Buskila]] and [[Blue and White (political alliance)|Blue and White]] MK [[Eitan Ginzburg]]. Fellow [[Blue and White (political alliance)|Blue and White]] MK [[Yael German]] advised Amar to follow the example of [[Pope Francis]] in his moves to accept the LGBT community. The [[Jerusalem Open House]] association and three LGBT Jewish groups, [[Bat Kol (organization)|Bat-Kol]], [[Havruta (organization)|Havruta]] and the Gay Religious Community, condemned his comments as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/jerusalem-chief-rabbi-calls-homosexuality-a-wild-lust-that-needs-to-be-overcome-1.7569976|title=Jerusalem Chief Rabbi Calls Homosexuality 'A Wild Lust That Needs To Be Overcome'|work=Haaretz|date=24 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/israel-news/1765041/efforts-to-oust-jerusalem-chief-sephardi-rabbi-hagaon-harav-amar-after-anti-toeiva-remarks.html|title=Efforts To Oust Jerusalem Chief Sephardi Rabbi, HaGaon HaRav Amar After Anti-Toeiva Remarks|work=The Yeshiva World|date=26 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/adl-condemns-jerusalem-chief-rabbis-hateful-comments-on-homosexuals/|title=ADL condemns Jerusalem chief rabbi's 'hateful comments' on homosexuals|work=The Times of Israel|date=24 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/jerusalem-chief-rabbi-gay-people-arent-religious-should-cast-off-observance/|title=Jerusalem chief rabbi: Gay people cannot be religious, shouldn't pretend to be|work=The Times of Israel|date=23 July 2019|last=Winer|first=Stuart}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israel-s-homophobia-problem-just-got-even-worse-1.7569418|title=Israel's Homophobia Problem Just Got Even Worse|work=Haaretz|date=24 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://forward.com/fast-forward/428152/jerusalem-chief-rabbi-condemns-homosexuality-orthodox-israel-lgbt/|title=Jerusalem Chief Rabbi: Homosexuality Is 'A Wild Lust Than Needs To Be Overcome'|work=Forward|date=24 July 2019|last=Dolsten|first=Josefin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Jerusalem-chief-rabbi-homosexuality-wild-lust-that-needs-to-be-overcome-596626|title=Jerusalem Chief Rabbi: Homosexuality 'Wild Lust That Needs To Be Overcome'|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=24 July 2019|last=Dolsten|first=Josefin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/266415|title=Jerusalem chief rabbi calls on gays to 'overcome' homosexuality|work=Arutz Sheva|date=24 July 2019|last=Dolsten|first=Josefin}}</ref> He also caused controversy in 2016 by saying that homosexuality is an \"abomination cult\" for which the Torah prescribes the death penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-38023884|title=Israel Chief Rabbi Amar condemned for 'gay death penalty' comment|work=BBC News|date=18 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, a 16-year-old teenager who lives in the Beit Dror LGBT center in [[Tel Aviv]] was stabbed several times and seriously wounded by his brother for refusing to adopt \"a religious lifestyle\". [[Israel Gay Youth]] (IGY) called the stabbing a hate crime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/teen-seriously-wounded-in-stabbing-near-tel-aviv-lgbt-youth-hostel/|title=Teen seriously hurt in stabbing at Tel Aviv LGBT youth hostel; brother suspected|work=The Times of Israel|date=26 July 2019}}</ref> The condition of the victim stabilized after he underwent surgery at the [[Tel Aviv Sourasky Medical Center]]. Media reported that the victim and two suspects were all Muslim brothers from the Arab town of [[Tamra]] in northern Israel and that the victim was removed from his home by social services due to harassment from his family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israeli-teenager-seriously-wounded-in-stabbing-outside-lgbt-youth-shelter-1.7577291|title=Israeli Teenager Seriously Wounded In Stabbing Outside LGBT Youth Shelter|work=Haaretz|date=26 July 2019}}</ref> Nearly 1,000 LGBT people and allies marched in Tel Aviv under the banner \"fighting for our lives\" to denounce violence against LGBT people in the wake of the attack. The march was attended by openly gay [[Blue and White (political alliance)|Blue and White]] MKs [[Eitan Ginzburg]] and [[Idan Roll]], who said the party was committed to ending violence against the LGBT community, and by [[Meretz]] leader [[Nitzan Horowitz]], Israel's first ever openly gay party leader, and [[Etai Pinkas|Etai Pinkas-Arad]], who holds the LGBT portfolio at the [[Tel Aviv-Yafo Municipality]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-fighting-for-our-lives-over-a-thousand-march-in-tel-aviv-for-transgender-rights-1.7582432|title='Fighting For Our Lives': Over A Thousand March in Tel Aviv For Transgender Rights|work=Haaretz|date=28 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/hundreds-march-against-transgender-violence-in-tel-aviv-after-teen-stabbed/|title=Hundreds march against transgender violence in Tel Aviv after teen stabbed|work=The Times of Israel|date=28 July 2019}}</ref> The stabbing was also condemned as a hate crime by a number of politicians, among them [[Nitzan Horowitz]] and by some Arab lawmakers, namely [[Meretz]] MK [[Issawi Frej]], [[Hadash]] party leader [[Ayman Odeh]], Hadash MK [[Aida Touma-Sliman]] and [[Balad (political party)|Balad]] MK Mtanes Shihadeh.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/arab-lawmakers-condemn-stabbing-outside-lgbt-youth-hostel/|title=Arab lawmakers condemn stabbing outside LGBT youth hostel|work=The Times of Israel|date=27 July 2019}}</ref> [[Green Movement (Israel)|Green Movement]] MK [[Stav Shaffir]] blamed members of the religious right for intolerance towards LGBT Israelis, to which [[Ministry of Transport and Road Safety|Transport Minister]] [[Bezalel Smotrich]] ([[The Jewish Home]]) called her \"stupid\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/smotrich-shaffir-stupid-for-blaming-religious-right-for-anti-lgbt-violence/|title=Smotrich: Shaffir 'stupid' for blaming religious right for anti-LGBT violence|work=The Times of Israel|date=29 July 2019}}</ref> Four days later, the two suspects in the stabbing turned themselves in.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/brothers-of-youth-stabbed-outside-lgbt-hostel-in-tel-aviv-turn-themselves-in/|title=Brothers of youth stabbed outside LGBT hostel in Tel Aviv turn themselves in|work=The Times of Israel|date=30 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israeli-police-arrests-brothers-of-teen-stabbed-outside-tel-aviv-lgbtq-shelter-1.7606601|title=Israeli Police Arrests Brothers Of Teen Stabbed Outside Tel Aviv LGBTQ Shelter|work=Haaretz|date=30 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the LGBT association [[The Aguda \u2013 Israel's LGBT Task Force]] announced that gay pride events would be held in 12 locales that have never held them before. Among these are [[Tiberias]], [[Beit Shemesh]], [[Zikhron Ya'akov]], [[Ramat Gan]], [[Petah Tikva]], [[Pardes Hanna-Karkur]], [[Netanya]], [[Yavne]] and [[Kiryat Bialik]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-record-number-of-israeli-locales-to-hold-gay-pride-events-for-the-first-time-1.7301827|title=Record Number of Israeli Locales to Hold Gay Pride Events for the First Time|work=Haaretz|date=28 May 2019|last=Yaron|first=Lee}}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nOn 23 February 2016, the Ministry of Health approved a pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) program to prevent HIV transmission, making Israel one of the first countries to implement it. The drugs are handed out at AIDS centers in hospitals and clinics that serve the LGBT community, in addition to health fund clinics.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Business-and-Innovation/Health-and-Science/Israel-approves-drug-that-prevents-HIV-infection-445846 ISRAEL APPROVES DRUG THAT PREVENTS HIV INFECTION]</ref>\n\nOne of the Israeli National Health Funds, Clalit operates a dedicated LGBT-friendly health clinic. It is located in Tel-Aviv. It was the first LGBT-friendly clinic in the whole of Israel.<ref>[http://gaycenter.org.il/?page_id=12 \u05d4\u05e8\u05e9\u05de\u05d4 \u05dc\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05d6\u05dc\u05d8\u05e8]</ref>\n\n===Public opinion===\nA 2013 public opinion poll by ''[[Haaretz]]'' showed support for same-sex marriage at 59% among Israelis.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ho |first=Spencer |date=15 December 2013 |title=Poll: 70% of Israelis support recognition for gays |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/poll-70-of-israelis-support-recognition-for-gays/ |newspaper=The Times of Israel |accessdate=31 December 2014}}</ref> A Hiddush survey made in 2016 found that 76% of Israelis supported the recognition of same-sex marriage or civil unions. The poll showed an increase in public support on this issue in Israel.<ref>[http://mobile.mako.co.il/news-israel/education-q2_2016/Article-569c3b14b5a0551004.htm \u05e1\u05e7\u05e8: 76% \u05d1\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e0\u05d9\u05e9\u05d5\u05d0\u05d9\u05dd \u05d7\u05d3 \u05de\u05d9\u05e0\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd]</ref> A June 2017 poll found that 79% of Israelis supported legally recognising same-sex unions.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Wide-support-for-gay-marriage-as-Israel-celebrates-Pride-496348 WIDE SUPPORT FOR GAY MARRIAGE AS ISRAEL CELEBRATES PRIDE]</ref>\n\n===LGBT rights movement===\n[[File:Yaar hagaava.jpg|thumb|A sign at Ya'ar HaGa'ava (\"Pride Forest\") in the [[Upper Galilee]], dedicated to Israel's LGBT community.]]\nSince the 1970s, there has been an active [[LGBT social movements|gay rights movement]] that has often affiliated itself with the Israeli [[Feminism|feminist]] movement and various liberal and [[Social democracy|social democratic]] political parties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegully.com/essays/gaymundo/020220_gay_israel_history.html |title=Queer in the Land of Sodom |publisher=Thegully.com |date=21 February 2002 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> The oldest Israeli LGBT organization is [[The Aguda \u2013 Israel's LGBT Task Force|The Aguda]], founded in 1975.\n\n===Media===\nOne of the first [[Israeli newspapers]] to cover the subject of gay people was a 1962 article in the now defunct ''[[HaOlam HaZeh]]''. Taking a sensationalist tone, the newspaper warned of a \"secret underground\" movement within Israel.<ref name=\"books.google.com\">{{cite book|last=Walzer|first=Lee|url=https://archive.org/details/betweensodomeden00walz |url-access=registration|title=Between Sodom and Eden : A Gay Journey Through Today's Changing Israel|year=2000|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-231-11394-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/betweensodomeden00walz/page/141 141]}}</ref> This was the typical manner with which the Israeli news media would deal with [[LGBT]] issues, beyond silence, until the late 1980s.\n\nIt was then that the Tel Aviv weekly newspaper ''HaIr'' began to publish a chronicle about an Israeli gay man, known at the time as ''Moshe'', who would later reveal himself to be [[Gal Uchovsky]].<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> The second major shift in how Israeli media dealt with [[LGBT]] issues came in 1991, when the [[Histadrut]] Labor Federation began to include, in its official publication, a section on [[LGBT]] social and political topics. This was followed by gradually more supportive press coverage on the Israeli LGBT community and its human rights objectives.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite book|last=Walzer|first=Lee|url=https://archive.org/details/betweensodomeden00walz |url-access=registration|title=Between Sodom and Eden : A Gay Journey Through Today's Changing Israel|year=2000|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-231-11394-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/betweensodomeden00walz/page/150 150]}}</ref> Today, the two Israeli daily newspapers have openly gay editors and/or writers, and several LGBT-publications have come and gone.\n\nRadio stations such as Radio Tzafon and Radio Radius both have scheduled times for guests to come on the air and talk about LGBT social and political topics.\n\n===Pinkwashing===\n{{further|Pinkwashing (LGBT)}}\nSarah Schulman, a writer and professor at the [[City University of New York]], claims Israeli [[Public diplomacy (Israel)|government public relations campaign]] exploits their LGBT rights record to promote public perception of Israel as a \"modern democracy\", a \"safe and secure place for investment\", and a \"tourist destination with the sun and the sand\".<ref>Avraham, Eli. (2009), \"Marketing and managing nation branding during prolonged crisis: The case of Israel\". Vol. 5, 3, pp.202\u2013212.</ref> In August 2011, the ''Jerusalem Post'' reported that the Foreign Ministry was promoting \"Gay Israel\" as part of its campaigns to counter the negative stereotypes that many liberal Americans and Europeans have of Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/Israel/Foreign-Ministry-promoting-Gay-Israel |title=Foreign Ministry promoting Gay Israel |work=Jerusalem Post |accessdate=22 March 2014}}</ref> Critics of Israel like [[Jasbir Puar]], an associate professor of Women's and Gender Studies at [[Rutgers University]], cite the Israeli Government's comparison of gay rights in Israel and in the [[occupied Palestinian territories]] as an example of pinkwashing. Citing WorldPride, which Jerusalem hosted in 2006, she wrote: \"Within global gay and lesbian organising circuits, to be gay-friendly is to be modern, cosmopolitan, developed, first-world, global north, and, most significantly, democratic.\"<ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/jul/01/israels-gay-propaganda-war |title=Israel's gay propaganda war |work=[[ynetnews.com]] |date=1 July 2010 |first=Jasbir|last=Puar |accessdate=22 March 2014}}</ref> [[Joseph Massad]], associate professor of modern Arab politics and intellectual history at [[Columbia University]], has written that the Israeli Government \"insist[s] on advertising and exaggerating its recent record on LGBT rights ... to fend off international condemnation of its violations of the rights of the Palestinian people.\"<ref name=kaufman>{{cite news|last=Kaufman|first=David|title=Is Israel Using Gay Rights to Excuse Its Policy on Palestine?|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2070415,00.html|newspaper=Time magazine|date=13 May 2011|accessdate=26 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/stop-using-palestinian-gays-to-whitewash-israel-s-image-1.6887 |title='Stop using Palestinian gays to whitewash Israel's image' |work=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=26 January 2015|date=1 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nIdo Aharoni, former head of the Brand Israel project, responded to such criticism saying: \"We are not trying to hide the conflict, but broaden the conversation. We want to create a sense of relevance with other communities.\" <ref name=kaufman/> [[Alan Dershowitz]], criminal and civil liberties lawyer, has said that the term \"pinkwashing\" is used against Israel by \"some radical gay activists\" who are [[anti-Semitic]] \"bigots\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/alan-dershowitz/the-pinkwashing-campaign-_b_2790669.html |title=The Pinkwashing Campaign Against Israel: Another Conspiracy Theory |work=Huffington Post |accessdate=22 March 2014|date=March 2013 }}</ref>\n\nSeveral LGBT Palestinians were reported to have been blackmailed by the [[Israel Defense Forces]] to become informants. Reports stated that [[Mossad|Israeli intelligence]] pries into Palestinians' internet activity and phone calls so as to identify and blackmail LGBT people and turn them into informants against other Palestinians.<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Connor |first=Nigel |url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/read/gay-palestinians-are-being-blackmailed-into-working-as-informants |title=Gay Palestinians Are Being Blackmailed Into Working As Informants &#124; VICE &#124; United Kingdom |publisher=VICE |date=2013-02-19 |accessdate=2016-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.annahar.com/article/203736-revealed-israel-is-a-gay-mecca--new-york-times-promotes-a-pinkwashed-democracy |title=Revealed: Israel is a gay Mecca - New York Times promotes a pink-washed democracy - An-Nahar |publisher=En.annahar.com |date=2015-01-08 |accessdate=2016-01-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131194652/http://en.annahar.com/article/203736-revealed-israel-is-a-gay-mecca--new-york-times-promotes-a-pinkwashed-democracy |archivedate=31 January 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> According to an Israeli Intelligence Corps officer: \"If anyone interests us, we'd collect information on his or her economic situation and mental state. Then we would plan how we can perform an operation around this individual, in order to turn them into a collaborator or something of the sort.\"<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/12/israeli-intelligence-unit-testimonies |title='Any Palestinian is exposed to monitoring by the Israeli Big Brother' &#124; World news |journal=The Guardian |date= 2014-09-12|accessdate=2016-01-26}}</ref>\n\n===Film and television===\nThe first Israeli LGBT-themed film came from openly gay director [[Amos Guttman]] and was called ''[[Drifting (1983 film)|Nagu'a]]'' (English title ''Drifting'').<ref name=\"Walzer 2000\">{{cite book |last=Walzer |first=Lee |url=https://archive.org/details/betweensodomeden00walz |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/betweensodomeden00walz/page/175 175] |title=Between Sodom and Eden: A Gay Journey Through Today's Changing Israel |year=2000 |publisher=Columbia University Press |location=New York |isbn=978-0-231-11394-6 }}</ref> Guttman was its co-writer. The film follows a young Israeli gay man, living and working with his grandparents, who has dreams of making a film and finding true love. Guttman, who died of AIDS in 1993, would write and direct another Israeli gay-themed film titled ''[[Amazing Grace (1992 film)|Amazing Grace]]'' (1992). Both films are considered to be autobiographies of the director. In total, Guttman directed four films and three short films. His portrayal of Israeli gay men was dark, and his films are considered to be targeted at the LGBT community in Israel, and not to the general public.\n\n[[File:Eytan Fox 2012 Shankbone.JPG|thumb|upright|Israeli director [[Eytan Fox]]]]\nAnother notable Israeli director to tackle LGBT themes in films is [[Eytan Fox]]. His first film, ''Time Off'' (1990), was the second film made in Israel to focus on gay people. He has directed and written several other successful LGBT-themed films, including ''[[Ba'al Ba'al Lev]]'' (1997), ''[[Yossi & Jagger]]'' (2002), ''[[Walk on Water (film)|Walk on Water]]'' (2004), and ''[[The Bubble (2006 film)|The Bubble]]'' (2006).<ref>{{cite web |author=Andrejs Visockis |url=http://andysfilmworld.blogspot.com/2008/01/yossi-jagger-israel-2002.html |title=Andy's Film World: ''Yossi & Jagger'' (Israel, 2002) |publisher=Andysfilmworld.blogspot.com |date=27 January 2008 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref> Fox was also involved in the first Israeli prime time TV drama made for a general audience which dealt extensively with [[LGBT]]-themes, ''Florentin'' (1997\u20132000). This was an Israeli television series about a group of post-military service, Israeli twenty-somethings living in [[Florentin (Tel Aviv)|Florentin]]. It was the first Israeli series to have a gay person among its major characters, and was part of a slow trend that had been unfolding in the 1990s with shows such as ''Straight and to the Point'' and ''Siton''.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nToday, there is more programming for a [[LGBT]] audience. In 1993, the first commercial TV network in Israel, [[Channel 2 (Israel)|Channel 2]], went on the air. It regularly dealt with [[LGBT]] social and political topics, and, in particular, helped generate greater visibility and acceptance of transgender celebrities such as [[Dana International]].<ref name=\"Walzer 2000\"/> The LGBT community in Israel was also brought to the media's attention following the winning of the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] in 1998 by Dana International, an Israeli [[transsexual|transwoman]]. At present, LGBT people in Israel can be seen on television in a variety of shows, mostly as hosts (such as [[Assi Azar]]), contestants in [[reality show]]s or characters on [[soap opera]]s.\n\n==Palestinian issues==\n{{further|LGBT rights in the Palestinian territories}}\nPalestinian society tends to be conservative, with families tending to see homosexuality and [[cross-dressing]] as immoral acts, deserving of condemnation. Some LGBT Palestinians have relocated to Israel, often fleeing harsh intolerance that includes physical abuse, death, or disowning. Significant [[expatriate]] groups exist in [[Tel Aviv]] and [[Netanya]], where many live with their Israeli same-sex partners who help keep their presence in Israel hidden from the police (who would pursue them not for their sexual orientation, but for staying illegally in the country).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/page_view_story.asp?intarticleid%3D13623 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-07-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051018001739/http://www.jta.org/page_view_story.asp?intarticleid=13623 |archivedate=18 October 2005 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/mwt/feature/2002/02/21/ezra_selim/ |title=Sleeping with the enemy \u2013 Middle East |work=Salon.com |date=21 February 2002 |accessdate=2011-06-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baywindows.com/main.cfm/include/detail/storyid/245628.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20051122220931/http://www.baywindows.com/main.cfm/include/detail/storyid/245628.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=22 November 2005|title=Where Jews and Arabs find ways to mix peacefully in the Holy Land|work=Bay Windows|date=22 May 2002|last=Cassels|first=Peter}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Aswat was founded, which describes itself as a Palestinian lesbian support group. However, the group is headquartered in [[Haifa]], Israel, and is geared toward Arab lesbians in Israel and the Palestinian Authority. A secret association of Aswat was founded in [[Ramallah]] in March 2007 by four gay students.<ref>[http://www.aswatgroup.org/english/about.php?article=212 Our Mission and Aims] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070811234504/http://www.aswatgroup.org/english/about.php?article=212 |date=11 August 2007 }}</ref> The Israeli [[Jerusalem Open House]] has opened an Arab chapter called Alqaws,<ref>[http://www.alqaws.org/?id=500 Alqaws]</ref> reaching out to gay and lesbian Palestinians. In 2008, Israel granted a gay Palestinian a residency permit to live with his Israeli partner in [[Tel Aviv]] following death threats from Palestinians regarding his homosexuality. Aswat claimed that gays are sometimes targeted by the Israeli security services and are told that they must collaborate with Israel or face being outed.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKL2586865820080325 | work=Reuters | title=Gay Palestinian gets OK to live with Israeli lover |author= Rebecca Harrison | date=25 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Notable individuals==\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Aderet (singer)|Aderet]], musician \n* [[Corinne Alal]], musician ([[:he:\u05e7\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05df \u05d0\u05dc\u05d0\u05dc|he]])\n* [[Yossi Avni-Levy]], diplomat\n* [[Assi Azar]], TV personality\n* [[Orna Banai]], actress\n* [[Jean-Pierre Barda]], musician and actor\n* [[Apollo Braun]], musician and author\n* [[Eliad Cohen]], model\n* [[Evan Cohen]], linguist and LGBT rights activist, foreign media spokesperson<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/netanyahu-taps-south-africa-born-linguist-as-new-foreign-media-spokesperson/|title=Netanyahu taps linguist and LGBTQ rights activist as foreign media spokesperson|work=The Times of Israel|date=14 July 2019|last=Ahren|first=Raphael}}</ref>\n* [[Dana International]], musician\n* [[Jonathan Danilowitz]], activist\n* [[Ran Danker]], actor\n* [[Jason Danino-Holt]], anchor\n* [[Irit Dinur]], mathematician/computer scientist\n* [[Uzi Even]], scientist and politician\n* [[Rose Fostanes|Rose \"Osang\" Fostanes]], musician\n* [[Eytan Fox]], director\n* [[Marcia Freedman]], activist and politician\n* [[Robert Friend (poet)|Robert Friend]], poet\n* [[Amir Fryszer Guttman]], musician\n* [[Eitan Ginzburg]], politician\n* [[Amos Guttman]], director\n* [[Yuval Noah Harari]], historian\n* [[Matan Hodorov]], journalist\n* [[Nitzan Horowitz]], politician\n* [[Dario Hunter|Dario David Hunter]], rabbi\n* [[Rona Kenan]], musician\n* [[Yorai Lahav-Hertzano]], politician\n* [[Asi Levi]], actress\n* [[Ivri Lider]], musician\n* [[Michael Lucas (director)|Michael Lucas]], director\n* [[Lyrik]], musician \n* [[Idan Matalon]], video blogger\n* [[Doron Medalie]], musician \n* [[Gil Mossinson|Gili Mossinson]], basketball player<ref>[http://m.jpost.com/Israel-News/Sports/Israeli-sports-world-rocked-as-pro-basketball-player-comes-out-of-closet-453921#article=6017MEIwNUQwRUY5RjVFNTI2RDk2NTVDQUQyRTY4N0U2RTQ= ISRAELI PRO BASKETBALL PLAYER COMES OUT AS BISEXUAL IN INDEPENDENCE DAY POST]</ref>\n* [[Ezra Nawi]], activist\n* [[Adi Nes]], photographer\n* [[Offer Nissim]], musician\n* [[Tzipora Obziler]], tennis player\n* [[Amir Ohana]], politician\n* [[Dana Olmert]], activist\n* [[Yotam Ottolenghi]], chef\n* [[Etai Pinkas]], activist\n* [[Yehuda Poliker]], musician<ref>[http://awiderbridge.org/yehuda-poliker/ YEHUDA POLIKER]</ref><ref>[http://jewishjournal.com/current_edition/213534/israeli-yehuda-poliker-brings-greek-infused-music-to-ucla/ Israeli Yehuda Poliker brings Greek-infused music to UCLA]</ref>\n* [[Yehudit Ravitz]], musician\n* [[Idan Roll]], politician\n* [[Jonathan Sagall]], actor\n* [[Itzik Shmuli]], politician\n* [[Gil Shohat]], musician\n* [[Harel Skaat]], musician\n* [[Dori Spivak]], judge\n* [[Hovi Star]], musician \n* [[Gal Uchovsky]], screenwriter and producer\n* [[Yeho]], musician \n* [[Yona Wallach]], poet\n* [[Ron Yosef]], activist\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Summary table==\n{{LGBT rights summary\n| legality = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 1963 ''[[de facto]]'', since 1988 ''[[de jure]]'')\n| equal_aoc = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| antidiscrimination = \n| antidiscrimination_employment = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 1992)\n| antidiscrimination_goods = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2000)\n| antidiscrimination_other = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 1997)\n| antidiscrimination_genderid = [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n| marriage = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]/[[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Same-sex marriage from abroad recognised since 2006)<ref name=\"elyon1.court.gov.il\"/>\n| recognition = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Unregistered cohabitation since 1994)\n| joint_adoption = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2008)\n| step_adoption = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2005)\n| military_service = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 1993)\n| gender_change = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| surrogacy1 = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]/[[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Surrogacy for Israeli gay male couples is possible only abroad)\n| ivf_access = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]\n| blood_donation = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (No deferral since 2018)\n| immigration = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2016)<ref name=\"pink\"/>\n| conversion_therapy = [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]]/[[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]] (Practice of conversion therapy in the public health system banned since 2014)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Israel|LGBT}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[2009 Tel Aviv gay centre shooting]]\n* [[Homosexuality and Judaism]]\n* [[Human rights in Israel]]\n* [[LGBT history in Israel]]\n* [[LGBT in the Middle East]]\n* [[LGBT rights by country or territory]]\n* [[LGBT rights in Asia]]\n* [[List of LGBT Jews]]\n* ''[[Men of Israel]]''\n* [[Tel Aviv Municipal LGBT Community Center]]\n* [[Tel Aviv Pride]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.il/MFA/IsraelExperience/Pages/Gay_Israel.aspx|title=Gay Israel|work=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Israel)|Israel Ministry of Foreign Affairs]]|date=19 July 2018}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.glbtqarchive.com/ssh/israel_S.pdf|title=Israel|work=[[glbtq.com]]|date=2006}}\n* {{Curlie|Regional/Middle_East/Israel/Society_and_Culture/Gay,_Lesbian,_and_Bisexual|Israel: Society and Culture: Gay, Lesbian, and Bisexual}}\n\n{{LGBT in Israel}}\n{{Asia topic|LGBT rights in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:LGBT rights in Israel}}\n[[Category:LGBT rights in Israel| ]]\n", "name_user": "C.monarchist28", "label": "safe", "comment": "odd wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LGBT_rights_in_Israel"}
{"title_page": "Children of Chance (1949 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1949 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Children of Chance\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Luigi Zampa]]\n| producer       = [[John Sutro]]<br>Ludovico Toeplitz\n| writer         = [[Michael Medwin]]<br>Piero Tellini\n| starring       = [[Patricia Medina]]\n| music          = [[Nino Rota]]\n| cinematography = [[Carlo Montuori]]\n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|1949|10}}\n| runtime        = 99 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom \n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''Children of Chance''''' is a 1949 British [[drama film]] directed by [[Luigi Zampa]] and starring [[Patricia Medina]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/153273/Children-of-Chance/overview |title=New York Times: Children of Chance |accessdate=7 August 2008 |work=NY Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520101403/http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/153273/Children-of-Chance/overview |archive-date=20 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Patricia Medina]] as Agostina\n* [[Manning Whiley]] as Don Andrea\n* [[Yvonne Mitchell]] as Australia\n* [[Barbara Everest]] as Francesca\n* [[Eliot Makeham]] as Vicar\n* [[George Woodbridge (actor)|George Woodbridge]] as Butcher\n* Frank Tickle as Mayor\n* [[Eric Pohlmann]] as Sergeant\n* [[Edward Lexy]] as Doctor\n* [[Carlo Giustini]] as Marco\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Alarm Bells (film)|Alarm Bells]]'' (1949)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0041244|title=Children of Chance}}\n\n{{Luigi Zampa}}\n{{Nino Rota}}\n\n[[Category:1949 films]]\n[[Category:1949 drama films]]\n[[Category:1940s multilingual films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British drama films]]\n[[Category:British black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:British multilingual films]]\n[[Category:English-