{"title_page": "Chinese red-headed centipede", "text_new": "{{subspeciesbox\n| name = Chinese red-headed centipede\n| image = Scolopendra subspinipes mutilans DSC 1438.jpg\n| genus = Scolopendra\n| species = subspinipes\n| subspecies = mutilans\n| authority = [[Ludwig Carl Christian Koch|L. Koch]], 1878\n}}\nThe '''Chinese red-headed centipede''', also known as the '''Chinese red head''', (''Scolopendra subspinipes mutilans'') is a [[centipede]] from [[East Asia]] and [[Australasia]].&nbsp;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deh.gov.au/cgi-bin/abrs/fauna/details.pl?pstrVol=CHILOPODA;pstrTaxa=428;pstrChecklistMode=2 |title=Australian Faunal Directory: ''Scolopendra subspinipes mutilans'' |publisher=[[Department of the Environment and Heritage (Australia)|Australian Department of the Environment and Heritage]] |accessdate=10 June 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140913093059/http://www.environment.gov.au/biodiversity/abrs/online-resources/fauna/afd/home |archive-date=13 September 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It averages 20&nbsp;cm (8&nbsp;inches) in length and lives in damp environments.\n\nIn ancient Chinese traditions, this centipede is used for its healing properties. It is said that putting a Chinese red head on a rash or other skin-disease will speed up the healing process. The roasted dry centipede is pulverized and used in Korea for the treatment of back pain, [[Boil|furuncles]] and sores.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Moon|first=Surk-Sik|last2=Cho|first2=Namsun|last3=Shin|first3=Jongheon|last4=Seo|first4=Youngwan|last5=Lee|first5=Chong Ock|last6=Choi|first6=Sang Un|date=1996-01-01|title=Jineol, a Cytotoxic Alkaloid from the Centipede Scolopendra subspinipes|journal=Journal of Natural Products|volume=59|issue=8|pages=777\u2013779|doi=10.1021/np960188t|issn=0163-3864}}</ref>\n\n''Scolopendra subspinipes mutilans'' is known for harbouring little aggression to other centipedes, a trait very rare amongst giant centipedes and allows it to be kept communally.\n\nFemales are incubatoral mothers, guarding the eggs by wrapping their body around the clutch until it hatches.\n\n==Venom==\nThe venom of the Chinese red-headed centipede contains a small peptide toxin called [[RhTx]], which increases activation of the [[TRPV1]] ion channel, causing a localized burning pain.<ref name=yang2015>{{cite journal | last1 = Yang | first1 = S. | last2 = Yang | first2 = F. | last3 = Wei | first3 = N. | last4 = Hong | first4 = J. | last5 = Li | first5 = B. | last6 = Luo | first6 = L. | last7 = Lai | first7 = R. | year = 2015 | title = A pain-inducing centipede toxin targets the heat activation machinery of nociceptor TRPV1 | journal = Nature Communications | volume = 6| issue = 1| page = 8297| doi = 10.1038/ncomms9297 | pmid = 26420335 | pmc = 4589873 }}</ref> The crude venom is said to be toxic in mice and to induce platelet aggregation.<ref name=\":0\" /> In addition, another 26 neurotoxins belonging to 10 different groups of peptides have been identified.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/224977672 |title= Chemical Punch Packed in Venoms Makes Centipedes Excellent Predators |access-date = February 11, 2018 |date= May 1, 2012 |website= [[ResearchGate]] |language = English |quote= Twenty-six neurotoxin-like peptides belonging to ten groups were identified from the centipede venoms, Scolopendra subspinipes mutilans L. Koch by peptidomics combined with transcriptome analysis, revealing the diversity of neurotoxins. These neurotoxins each contain two to four intramolecular disulfide bridges, and in most cases, the disulfide framework is different from that found in neurotoxins from the venoms of spiders, scorpions, marine cone snails, sea anemones, and snakes (5S animals). |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180212001227/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/224977672_Chemical_Punch_Packed_in_Venoms_Makes_Centipedes_Excellent_Predators\n |archive-date= February 12, 2018}}</ref> In January 2018 Chinese scientists found an antidote to the painful poison of centipede in the drug [[retigabine]], used to treat [[epilepsy]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-01/26/c_136927370.htm |title= Chinese scientists find antidote to centipede venom |access-date = February 11, 2018 |last= Liangyu |date= January 26, 2018 |website= [[Xinhua News Agency]] |language = English |quote= Researchers at the Kunming Institute of Zoology found in experiments using mice and monkeys that retigabine can effectively treat symptoms of centipede venom such as heart failure, epilepsy, and respiratory depression. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180126135249/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-01/26/c_136927370.htm |archive-date= January 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ssm spooky toxin]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|position=left|Scolopendra subspinipes mutilans}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q130038}}\n\n[[Category:Scolopendridae]]\n[[Category:Fauna of Yunnan]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Ludwig Carl Christian Koch]]\n\n\n{{Myriapoda-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{subspeciesbox\n| name = Chinese red-headed centipede\n| image = Scolopendra subspinipes mutilans DSC 1438.jpg\n| genus = Scolopendra\n| species = subspinipes\n| subspecies = mutilans\n| authority = [[Ludwig Carl Christian Koch|L. Koch]], 1878\n}}\nThe '''Chinese red-headed centipede''', also known as the '''Chinese red head''', (''Scolopendra subspinipes mutilans'') is a [[centipede]] from [[East Asia]] and [[Australasia]].&nbsp;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deh.gov.au/cgi-bin/abrs/fauna/details.pl?pstrVol=CHILOPODA;pstrTaxa=428;pstrChecklistMode=2 |title=Australian Faunal Directory: ''Scolopendra subspinipes mutilans'' |publisher=[[Department of the Environment and Heritage (Australia)|Australian Department of the Environment and Heritage]] |accessdate=10 June 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140913093059/http://www.environment.gov.au/biodiversity/abrs/online-resources/fauna/afd/home |archive-date=13 September 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It averages 20&nbsp;cm (8&nbsp;inches) in length and lives in damp environments.\n\nIn ancient Chinese traditions, this centipede is used for its healing properties. It is said that putting a Chinese red head on a rash or other skin-disease will speed up the healing process. The roasted dry centipede is pulverized and used in Korea for the treatment of back pain, [[Boil|furuncles]] and sores.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Moon|first=Surk-Sik|last2=Cho|first2=Namsun|last3=Shin|first3=Jongheon|last4=Seo|first4=Youngwan|last5=Lee|first5=Chong Ock|last6=Choi|first6=Sang Un|date=1996-01-01|title=Jineol, a Cytotoxic Alkaloid from the Centipede Scolopendra subspinipes|journal=Journal of Natural Products|volume=59|issue=8|pages=777\u2013779|doi=10.1021/np960188t|issn=0163-3864}}</ref>\n\n''Scolopendra subspinipes mutilans'' is known for harbouring little aggression to other centipedes, a trait very rare amongst giant centipedes and allows it to be kept communally.\n\nFemales are incubatoral mothers, guarding the eggs by wrapping their body around the clutch until it hatches.\n\n==Venom==\nThe venom of the Chinese red-headed centipede contains a small peptide toxin called [[RhTx]], which increases activation of the [[TRPV1]] ion channel, causing a localized burning pain.<ref name=yang2015>\nYang, S., Yang, F., Wei, N., Hong, J., Li, B., Luo, L., ... & Lai, R. (2015). ''A pain-inducing centipede toxin targets the heat activation machinery of nociceptor TRPV1''. Nature Communications, 6. {{DOI|10.1038/ncomms9297}}. {{PMID|26420335}}</ref> The crude venom is said to be toxic in mice and to induce platelet aggregation.<ref name=\":0\" /> In addition, another 26 neurotoxins belonging to 10 different groups of peptides have been identified.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/224977672 |title= Chemical Punch Packed in Venoms Makes Centipedes Excellent Predators |access-date = February 11, 2018 |date= May 1, 2012 |website= [[ResearchGate]] |language = English |quote= Twenty-six neurotoxin-like peptides belonging to ten groups were identified from the centipede venoms, Scolopendra subspinipes mutilans L. Koch by peptidomics combined with transcriptome analysis, revealing the diversity of neurotoxins. These neurotoxins each contain two to four intramolecular disulfide bridges, and in most cases, the disulfide framework is different from that found in neurotoxins from the venoms of spiders, scorpions, marine cone snails, sea anemones, and snakes (5S animals). |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180212001227/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/224977672_Chemical_Punch_Packed_in_Venoms_Makes_Centipedes_Excellent_Predators\n |archive-date= February 12, 2018}}</ref> In January 2018 Chinese scientists found an antidote to the painful poison of centipede in the drug [[retigabine]], used to treat [[epilepsy]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-01/26/c_136927370.htm |title= Chinese scientists find antidote to centipede venom |access-date = February 11, 2018 |last= Liangyu |date= January 26, 2018 |website= [[Xinhua News Agency]] |language = English |quote= Researchers at the Kunming Institute of Zoology found in experiments using mice and monkeys that retigabine can effectively treat symptoms of centipede venom such as heart failure, epilepsy, and respiratory depression. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180126135249/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-01/26/c_136927370.htm |archive-date= January 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ssm spooky toxin]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|position=left|Scolopendra subspinipes mutilans}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q130038}}\n\n[[Category:Scolopendridae]]\n[[Category:Fauna of Yunnan]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Ludwig Carl Christian Koch]]\n\n{{Myriapoda-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_red-headed_centipede"}
